author: Simon Vozick-Levinson
snippet: West may be obnoxious, but at least he's interested in confronting those aspects of his identity through his music. Few stars of comparable wattage would dare do the same.

author: Antonio Rowe
snippet: My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fanstasy is Kanye’s long-awaited opus, a work of art that sees him finally reach the potential that was clear for all to see in College Dropout.

author: Greg Watkins
snippet: My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy is a true testament to Kanyes magnificent ability to craft and create music.

author: Jim Carroll
snippet: My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy is a magnificent, headspinning, audacious work.

author: Rob Sheffield
snippet: It’s his best album, but it’s more than that — it’s also a rock-star manifesto for a downsizing world.

author: Matthew Cole
snippet: No rap album I've heard can boast better production than this one. The music is exhilarating, often abrasive, never predictable, at times stunningly gorgeous. These are the finest tracks that any group of rappers has yet to rhyme over.

author: Sean Highkin
snippet: A frequently astonishing, no-holds-barred tour de force that not only eclipses his previous four albums in scope and creativity (no small feat), but also makes everything else on the radio sound positively amateurish by comparison.

author: Michael Denslow
snippet: My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy is hands-down the most ambitious mainstream rap album ever made.
My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy is genuinely a great record.

author: Kevin Ritchie
snippet: An ornately orchestrated pop epic built on a classic hip-hop foundation, Twisted Fantasy is his best since his debut.

author: Andy Gill
snippet: My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy is one of pop's gaudiest, most grandiose efforts of recent years, a no-holds-barred musical extravaganza in which any notion of good taste is abandoned at the door.

author: Will Lavin
snippet: Kanye’s genius extends way past just constructing a track. The order in which each song is listed is perfect.

author: David Amidon
snippet: But it is the heart, soul, and humanity of My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy that ultimately marks it as the defining pop moment of 2010.

author: Ryan Dombal
snippet: As a result, the record comes off like a culmination and an instant greatest hits, the ultimate realization of his strongest talents and divisive public persona.

author: Danny Djeljosevic
snippet: Never before has a hip-hop album been so decadent, yet so beatific and inspiringly adventurous – an explosive synthesis of everything Kanye has learned after four albums.

author: Chris Barth
snippet: This album is a benchmark, a high water point for mainstream conceptual rap. It’s Kanye’s most complex and complete release and one of the most consistently impressive hip hop albums in recent years.

author: Mariel Concepcion
snippet: Needless to say, West has proved once again that he is most on point in the face of adversity.

author: daba
snippet: With My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy, Kanye West has lurched to the vanguard of modern mainstream music.

author: M.T. Richards
snippet: In its many contradictions, My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy—perhaps this century’s definitive portrait of torment, vanity, self-delusion, and pathos—has given way to stirring new possibilities.

author: Nathan Rabin
snippet: Kanye’s best album since The College Dropout, My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy finds its creator in complete control of the chaos swirling inside his vivid imagination.

author: Adam Park
snippet: This is not just West's best album, it's a keen contender for the most ambitious LP in hip-hop history.

author: Adam Johns
snippet: For rap fans it's both a testament to the versatility of the genre and Kanye's own brilliance that he can make something so refreshingly different which still fits comfortably in the rap canon.

author: Embling
snippet: Fantasy is hardly as difficult or artsy as it wants to think it is, but its emotional complexity more than compensates for bulging song lengths and near-constant pomposity.

author: Andy Kellman
snippet: Whether loved or loathed, fully enjoyed or merely admired, this album should be regarded as a deeply fascinating accomplishment.

author: Chris Mandle
snippet: It’s the best thing he’s done since his game-changing debut, and heartening evidence to suggest the self-professed Louis Vuitton don is in a good place right now.

author: Chris Martins
snippet: It's a sinister, orchestral, hugely grandiose affair that owes as much to the artist's self-aggrandizing ego as to the voracious id that would destroy it publicly.

author: Jay Soul
snippet: This may prove to be his most influential, inimitable, watershed moment thus far, simply it terms of audacity and quality control.

author: Clayton Purdom
snippet: It’s a sprawling monument to wholeness towering over an artistically and emotionally fragmented landscape. It’s Kanye, like we said, doing him: a circuit at last complete.

author: Tom Lea
snippet: It’s one of the grandest hip-hop records of all time ... full of vocoder, guitar, narration and overheard betrayals, and it’s frequently torn between whether it wants to be a rugged, raw rap record or a grandiose pop opera.

author: Sean L. Maloney
snippet: Fantasy will stand as an album that dared to push the entire medium of recorded music forward, for better or worse.

author: Jake Paine
snippet: From nine-minute douchebag manifestos, to enlisting an A-list Grammy ensemble to piece-mealing his album out to the masses every Friday, My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy defies logic and it ignores convention.

Fantasy is Kanye West's best album yet, and if that wasn't enough, it's also a shining example of what mainstream hip-hop can and should be: dynamic, focused, revealing, personable, and most important - the passion!

author: Gareth O'Malley
snippet: There is no weak link; there is not a single misstep (and this is a 68-minute-long album). This may very well be his masterpiece.
After the comparative disappointment of 2008's 808s & Heartbreak, West returned with this restlessly inventive 70-minute set.

author: Craig Mathieson
snippet: My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy is eclectic but never offhand; it's hip-hop where every deviation serves the song's texture, every boast contrasts with slyly lacerating self-appraisal.

author: John Aizlewood
snippet: Massive in every sense, My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy is the work of a man who feels compelled to be bigger, better and braver.

author: Kitty Empire
snippet: My Dark Twisted Fantasy – a flawed near-masterpiece – doesn't impress just by dint of numbers.

author: Bernadette McNulty
snippet: It’s certainly good to have West’s unique talent back in music, but this ambitious behemoth may be easier to admire than to listen to.
A fascinating record, a sumptuous musical banquet at which Bon Iver and Aphex Twin rub shoulders with Jay-Z, Smokey Robinson and a whole Broadway chorus.

author: Dave Kerr
snippet: Here he balances pastiche and drama with such glorious levity that to stick a fork in any part of his rich palette would be a cruelty of Dickensian proportions.
This album, then, shows West pushing out from basic formulae, experimenting and not just trying new things but carrying ideas right through until they are fully formed and flourishing.

author: Gabbie Nirenburg
snippet: Kanye West’s Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy is a sprawling, ambitious, orchestral fuck-you of an album, and he wants you to know it.

author: Justin De La Cruz
snippet: After a goofy intro on Dark Fantasy, ‘Ye takes it all back to his fantasies in Chicago, when he was producing beats and managing artists with a dream of making it big.

author: Anthony Fantano
snippet: Kanye's fifth studio album is easily his most ambitious effort yet. The production is extremely stunning. To be honest, this album sounds like a really huge undertaking with all of it's extra instrumentation, studio tricks, and samples.

author: Alex Macpherson
snippet: This album offers beats that retread past glories, and an emotional palette narrowed to a range roughly as wide as West's navel.

author: Niall Doherty
snippet: A seamless coming together of artists, cultures and themes on a record by a band that doesn’t even exist; on ‘Plastic Beach’, Damon Albarn’s Midas touch is bordering on genius.

author: Huw Jones
snippet: To handpick highlights from Plastic Beach should be considered lofty praise indeed; this is an album where the mind-boggling and the mind-blowing are wall to wall. Its brilliance adopts many guises throughout its 16 tracks.

author: Michael Cragg
snippet: Its real strength lies in the fact that it implores you to return for repeated visits to a world riddled with other people’s cast-offs. Ironically, it recycles nothing; everything here is box fresh.

author: Helen Brown
snippet: This action-packed concept album finds the cartoon band on an isolated island constructed entirely of consumer detritus and exploring the melancholy beauty of mankind’s interaction with the natural world. It’s a great metaphor for the playful way Damon Albarn has built up the Gorillaz’ danceably eclectic sound from offcuts of hip hop, funk, alternative rock, pop, world and electronica.

author: David Everley
snippet: There was nothing like Demon Days before and there's been nothing like it since. Until now... Plastic Beach picks up several steps on from where its predecessor left off.

author: George Booker
snippet: The album is schizophrenic in it's assemblage of hollow, scrub-cleaned elements into deceptively evergreen tapestries.

author: Nathan Kamal
snippet: If the band never create another record, it will stand as their masterpiece and a new paradigm of collaboration.

author: Billboard Staff
snippet: Gorillaz may have originated as a way for Damon Albarn to sidestep the limelight, but on the cartoon group’s third album, “Plastic Beach,” he very much takes center stage.

author: Ted Maider
snippet: SThe Gorillaz are hanging out on what looks like the coolest Play Mobile set of an island I have ever seen and have created a record that is just as amazing as the previous two.

author: Sean Highkin
snippet: This anything-goes approach makes Plastic Beach equally enjoyable on the surface level and rewarding of closer attention.

author: Anthony Fantano
snippet: Plastic Beach's music and concept have aged scarily well over the years.

author: Sean Fennessey
snippet: Ex-Blur frontman Damon Albarn ditches the idea of writing pop songs a cartoon band might front and makes one of his most gorgeous pop records in years.

author: Craig Jenkins
snippet: He never panders to them; instead, Plastic Beach‘s guest vocals are anchored by Albarn’s own melodic flair. His falsettoed ennui shines through, and the songs are loaded with Albarn’s pet sounds.

author: Noel Murray
snippet: Where Gorillaz and Demon Days often got bogged down in idle experimentation, Plastic Beach feels more urgent and less fiddly.

author: Clayton Purdom
snippet: Gorillaz’ third record, some sort of masterpiece within the band’s canon, and undoubtedly the best chillwave record ever recorded.

author: Oli Shilling
snippet: Track by track, this album works brilliantly, with most songs successfully employing guest stars. Most impressive, however, is how cohesively the album plays, rolling from song to song; each being identifiable as trademark Gorillaz.

author: Wendy Roby
snippet: Because past the pop songs, past the soaring (and let’s not make any bones about it, this album soars in places) this is a supremely clever album. I mean, who better to deliver a lecture on throwaway living than a Technicolor cartoon band?

author: Richard Trapunski
snippet: One might think the project would crumble under its own weight, but after a few listens it melds into a consistent parcel of didactic, retro/futuristic synth-pop ... It shouldn’t work, but it really does.

author: Alexis Petridis
snippet: The cartoon character shtick may be tired, but Damon Albarn's other talents never fail to impress.
It displays a sonic ambition, an openmindedness and a melodic gift that puts so much modern pop to shame.

author: Andy Gill
snippet: The most successful track is "Stylo", a Kraftwerkian electro-twitch on which the efforts of Albarn, Mos Def and the Bobby Womack impress.
There’s no overwhelming track to break the flow of the album, Plastic Beach rolls along at an almost soothing pace and all the tracks on offer serve only to compliment each other.

author: Brian Boyd
snippet: It’s a sprawl, but a beautiful sprawl.

author: Stephen Thomas Erlewine
snippet: Plastic Beach is the first Gorillaz album to play like a soundtrack to a cartoon -- which isn’t entirely a bad thing, because as Albarn grows as a composer, he’s a master of subtly shifting moods and intricately threaded allusions, often creating richly detailed collages that are miniature marvels.

author: B McGhee
snippet: Albarn doesn’t give us a “Clint Eastwood” or a “Dare” this time around, but in spite of a messy and patently artificial conceptual framework, Plastic Beach feels clean, shiny, and new.

author: Leah Greenblatt
snippet: Like its name, Plastic Beach has a sharp tang of cognitive dissonance — its songs sound like dispatches from a crew of hip-kid astronauts, unmoored in some space-dust ether ... In the end, Beach offers a vision of the future as digitized kitsch: groovy, yes, but lonely too.

author: Steve 'Flash' Juon
snippet: While “Plastic Beach” may not be for everyone, I have no problem visiting their non-sandy shore and still wanting to come back for more.

author: Nick Annan
snippet: An intoxicating cocktail of musical styles and pioneers, ‘Plastic Beach’ is instantly recognisable as a Gorillaz album despite, or perhaps because of, its scatter shot styles, contributors and voices.

author: Rob Sheffield
snippet: Plastic Beach, Gorillaz's third excellent album in a row, is all Albarn — he writes the tunes, produces, sings, plays most of the music and gets people on the phone for left-field cameos.

author: Lawrence Vaughan
snippet: Of the sixteen tracks at least seven are filler and with repeat performances, ‘Plastic Beach’ does feel a tad recycled towards the end; more Blackpool than Hawaii, it’s still an album full of brilliance from a bona fide British genius.

author: Slava Kuperstein
snippet: Complaints regarding Plastic Beach are minor, particularly considering its astounding ambitions. While not flawless in execution like Demon Days, Gorillaz’ third effort is, nonetheless, brilliant much more often than not.

author: Jillian Mapes
snippet: It’s a lot to take in, and the mind is not sure where to start.

author: Jon Dolan
snippet: It’s a jumble.

author: James McMahon
snippet: We might not be sure who or what they are any more but we're sure about the tunes.

author: Michael Kabran
snippet: Fortunately, Plastic Beach‘s weaknesses are few and far between. Overall, while the album isn’t an artistic triumph or grand satirical gesture, it is an enjoyable ride and is the best place to start if you just want a taste of Albarn’s post-Blur musical prowess and Hewlett’s animation wizardry.

The music that wraps around the concept is never boring and much of it is excellent ... What's lacking is the nailed-on megatune--a "Clint Eastwood" or "Feel Good Inc"--that we've come to expect from a Gorillaz album.

author: Ally Brown
snippet: Gorillaz' third album Plastic Beach is reminiscent because its impressive and wide-ranging cast list ... has gathered to grumble about consumption and pollution issues, and because the variety of guests has forced Damon Albarn into some dizzyingly eclectic styles.

author: Ben Murphy
snippet: There are treasures to be found here, but as an album, ‘Plastic Beach’ has too much filler to sustain your attention across its length.

author: Bernard Zuel
snippet: Albarn just about pulls all of his ideas off on Plastic Beach, which is more than clever; it's impressive.

author: Jason Draper
snippet: while very nice and, indeed, wonderful in places, Plastic Beach doesn’t quite keep us full either.

author: John Aizlewood
snippet: The results are as weird, wonderful and frustrating as Gorillaz have ever been. There's some kind of vague eco-concept going on but it's so woolly as to be meaningless and while its running time is just 59 minutes, there's still too much filler padding out the final third.

author: Benjamin Boles
snippet: Murphy is still a brat, but this is a more emotionally mature and personal album than most of us thought him capable of.

author: Jason Adams
snippet: Golden-voiced Murphy ... doesn't try for any cheap Bowie-baritone vocal mimicry, and his lyrics and musicianship have greater depth and polish. The best inspiration should come with improvements, and Murphy's are vast.

author: Sean O'Neal
snippet: Perhaps the rumor that this is his last LCD album is behind that newfound urgency. If true, it’s a shame, as the band’s Krautrock/Talking Heads-funk fusion has never sounded livelier.

author: Andrew Baer
snippet: Wearing his love for Bowie on his sleeve for all to see serves him well - this album is the most lyrically focused LCD outing and the most uncompromising, with most songs breaking the six minute mark and a few breaking nine. It’s not just a great dance album; it’s a great pop album.

author: Rachael Maddux
snippet: Murphy and his crew are fully committed to this album. There’s a remarkable sustained energy to this collection; its electronic textures thrum and shimmy, and wall after sonic wall is built up and torn down with impeccable precision.

author: Ryan Dombal
snippet: Even considering his bold-name touchstones for This Is Happening, it would be shortsighted to cry rip-off; Murphy is remaking essential 70s art-rock in his own hyper-modern, self-aware image.

author: Andrew Burgess
snippet: This Is Happening suffers no shortage of really great songs. Each track is a well-executed study in the finer points of the long form, each thumping and building, wavering and shifting in the haze of its own self-contained ecosystem.

author: Anthony Lombardi
snippet: Not only has the band wrapped up the themes of the record with impeachable, spotless playing and production, but the man at the center of it all hasn’t lost his penchant for writing quality tunes either, as nearly anything you blind-spot off This Is Happening will prove.

author: Adam Park
snippet: As farewells go, this is proper fond. Sound of gold!

author: Derek Miller
snippet: This is Happening doesn't succeed as mere gold nugget pastiche though. Murphy embeds these references into the kind of physical trap-jams on which he and the DFA brand have always thrived.

author: Jim Scott
snippet: Somehow Murphy not only lives up to this self-imposed pressure, he revels in it. Each dip and twirl and change of pace clears the way for something even more exciting. It's roller coaster music.

author: Anthony Fantano
snippet: LCD Soundsystem's third and final album is an ambitious trip into the sounds of dance and rock fusion.

author: Sean Highkin
snippet: While This is Happening isn’t as wall-to-wall brilliant as Sound of Silver, if it is indeed his last record with this project, he’s leaving his legacy in just as good of shape as Jay-Z left his with The Black Album before his (unfortunately temporary) retirement.

author: Matthew Richardson
snippet: This Is Happening is a record that knows -- made by a band that knows -- that disco is better when it's just not so satisfied with itself.

author: Adam Offitzer
snippet: Perhaps with Sound of Silver, LCD Soundsystem has set the bar too high for itself. But with the many standouts on the album and the bliss they provide on their own, it’s not too hard to think that Murphy could have topped himself once again with a little less jamming and ranting.

author: Philip Cosores
snippet: Sure LCD Soundsystem songs are fun, but they also make you question why they are fun, whether they are actually fun, what fun means, whether we can ever answer these questions, and whether when all is done, are you happy with what you’re doing. It’s meta-party music.

author: Neil McCormick
snippet: This is an album that manages to maintain the essential simplicity demanded by the dance floor while packing itself to bursting with complex ideas. And if that sounds like a contradiction, well, take it up with Professor Murphy after class.
What keeps Murphy from being an insufferable know-it-all is how he folds deeper emotions into his references.

author: Emily Mackay
snippet: He’s set the bar high, but if this is to be James Murphy’s swansong, it’s a brave and powerful way to bow out.

author: Jody Rosen
snippet: On This Is Happening, Murphy, now 40, remains a hipster, often expressing his emotions through quips, asides and allusions ... But Happening also includes Murphy's most earnest, lovelorn songs.
With This Is Happening, Murphy remains far ahead of pretenders trying to steal his thunder.
Backed by colorful electronic textures, infectious basslines and futuristic rock melodies, the singer/ producer conveys the hard truths of life over nine tracks.

author: Tim Sendra
snippet: This Is Happening doesn’t quite reach the monumental heights of Sound of Silver, but it serves as an almost-there companion and further proof that LCD Soundsystem is one of the most exciting and interesting bands around in the 2000s.

author: Alexis Petridis
snippet: You could argue that This Is Happening lacks its predecessor's startling sense of mapping out new territories, but if it confines itself to doing what LCD Soundsystem do, it does it all incredibly well.

author: Jim Carroll
snippet: Such familiarity doesn’t breed contempt when the results are as punchy, punky, sardonic and smart as this.

author: Jakob Dorof
snippet: These fine-detail improvements are what make This Is Happening LCD’s best work to date, though mumblings about how Murphy might be repeating himself a bit remain valid.
This is a fantastic record, one of the year's best, but perhaps one that suggests that Murphy has said what he needed to say.

author: Nathan Kamal
snippet: This Is Happening is a great record and one of the best of the year so far. Only by the heights which Murphy can reach could it possibly be found wanting. If this is LCD’s final album, he’ll have a lot to be proud of.

author: Shawn Reynaldo
snippet: The new record doesn't quite live up to its predecessor, but its middle third is especially strong.
Overwrought at times, LCD Soundsystem still provide an abstract view of an often muddied genre.

author: Dave Hughes
snippet: As good as this record is (and it is often very good), LCD Soundsystem can do, and has done, much better.

author: Simon Hampson
snippet: Partly because it doesn’t break new ground for the band, This is Happening initially sounds a little drab. As with their previous records, there is a sternness and detachment in how it approaches dance rhythms.

author: Mark Abraham
snippet: In a technical sense it sounds, like everything Murphy produces, pristine.

author: Michael Wheeler
snippet: If Sound of Silver was the sound of someone reaching far enough to make something just plain great, then This is Happening is the sound of a man with great taste who really understands music, making dumb body music with hidden depths if anyone cares to investigate.

author: John Aizlewood
snippet: Murphy has already hinted that this might be LCD Soundsystem's final bulletin. On this evidence he wasn't teasing and the glum reality is that This Is Happening isn't happening enough.
Familiar elements (Nancy Wang's cheerleading vocals, sparse instrumentation colliding, lyrical misanthropy) are present and correct, but everything is bolder and deeper.
If this is indeed, as rumoured, LCD's final bout, it finds them a little heavy and tired, but occasionally deceptively light on their feet.

author: Ally Brown
snippet: This Is Happening is still a fine – if marginally flawed – end to a largely magnificent trilogy.

author: Chris Mandle
snippet: A hopping mad journey into the unknown, as hip-hop's young adventurer hacks his way to sonic pastures new.

author: Jay Soul
snippet: I’m not sure that this will be everyone’s cup of tea, but the majority of Cudi fans should recognise it as a breath of fresh air – not to mention, aided and abetted by crack production squad, a sublime musical treat.
Cudi is very much in a world of his own.

author: Charles Aaron
snippet: Man on the Moon II: The Legend of Mr. Rager, the sequel to The End of Day, is a revelation, boldly reshaping Cudi’s sound.

With an unorthodox flow, off-key rhyme pattern, and the help of Kanye West, Cudi’s debut album, which featured the smash hit ‘Day ‘n’ Nite’, introduced the music buying public to a guy ready to quite literally give himself to music.

The most important thing to take away from The Legend Of Mr. Rager is the knowledge that as long as artists like Kid Cudi are out there feeling as alone as we do sometimes...well, then we are never really alone.

author: Daniel Koren
snippet: He’s discussed some personal and difficult issues on Mr. Rager, all with the interest of being brutally honest with his fans.

author: Greg Watkins
snippet: With his new project, Cudi keeps the same formula; he ties together different melodies that are laced by lyrics that set the mood for the entire album. Although it's not all hip-hop, Man on The Moon 2: Legend of Mr. Rager is still original in its own right, and Cudi fans will be pleased with the outcome.

author: Edwin Ortiz
snippet: A tortured soul, yes, but one with ingenious capabilities, Cudi has taken his progressive style and in just two albums has turned it into a sound that no one would dare replicate.

author: Chris Coplan
snippet: With a few simple and appealing beats, some well-timed cameos, a dash of humor, and a handful of semi-inventive rhymes with emotional substance, he actually made an album that flies (more or less) high.

author: Matthew Cole
snippet: Pursuing genius at the expense of consistency might work out just fine for Cudi.

author: David Jeffries
snippet: You have to care quite a bit about this Mr. Solo Dolo character for Man on the Moon II to fully work its magic.

author: Jayson Greene
snippet: After the two-dimensional art-school-kid clichés of Man on the Moon, kid Cudi partially makes good on his promise to loosen up his music.

Boasts and breakbeats are in short supply here. Instead, over gloomy strings, and pounding martial drums, Cudi rails against celebrity culture, confesses to coke-fuelled rages and even contemplates suicide.

author: Benjamin Boles
snippet: Like his debut album, the sequel suffers and shines due to inconsistency.

author: Anthony Fantano
snippet: There's a lot of personal struggle and triumph on this album, but I can't say Kudi's personality is bright enough here to get me feeling as if I've got a stake in it all.

author: Dave Heaton
snippet: This sequel at times plays less like continuation than repetition.

author: Chase McMullen
snippet: Man on the Moon II: The Legend of Mr. Rager is also presented in five acts, and again has no real structure to justify them. They – like the music Cudi makes today – are arbitrary labels to add to an appearance.

author: Jonah Weiner
snippet: His second album features dramatic, breathtakingly stark production by Emile and Plain Pat, but where Cudi fancies himself a deep downer, too often he’s kind of a bore.

author: Michaelangelo Matos
snippet: Paranoia isn’t the only problem with Man On The Moon II; it’s that Cudi doesn’t have much grasp of any of the styles or modes he tries out.

What Diamond Eyes reveals to us is the Deftones steadfast refusal to hide behind anything they've ever done before; and in taking a huge risk in exposing a new side to them in the wake of such a tragedy has exposed just how high they really can go.

author: David Buchanan
snippet: Diamond Eyes might very well say it best — this place is death — but on that same note, this place is also life that both giveth and taketh away, so never lose sight of your dreams in the haze of stardom or lonesome alike. This is a true testament to that.

As armistice appears to exist on this sixth album; the more ethereal elements of the band's sound have been reined in, but so has much of the agresion, resulting in a smoother ride that allows Moreno's melodic ear to shine and seduce.

author: Brad Barrett
snippet: In essence this is their most fluid recording, unbroken by exploratory concerns.

author: Jason Pettigrew
snippet: Diamond Eyes is more concise than 2006's "Saturday Night Wrist" because it streamlines (or disposes) much of that album's sonic excesses while still delivering taut songs.

author: Mark Shukla
snippet: The first four tracks set a blistering pace as churning riffs transition relentlessly into fret-burning breakdowns; all the while Chino Moreno deploying his wounded croon and lacerating howl with an intensity that remains impressively undiminished.

author: Rob Parker
snippet: A brilliant, invigorating reintroduction.

author: Stephen Thomas Erlewine
snippet: Naturally, there is quite a bit of roiling darkness here -- they’re Cure-loving metalheads, it’s in their blood -- but there’s shade and light, control of texture, with the band deepening rather than expanding. Above all, it’s a mature album: Deftones skirted the obvious response to their tragedy, realizing that the left turn is a more rewarding journey.

author: Scott Reid
snippet: Diamond Eyes incorporates all the same basic tropes as every Deftones record before and almost certainly after it, but here, for the first time in ages, they’re crafted and performed with more than mere hints of the assuredness and pummeling hooks of their one (yes) great record—a full-course meal to the last decade’s worth of scattered crumbs.

author: Scott Gordon
snippet: Granted, freedom to roam does come standard with Deftones, as do the many chunky and graceful tendencies of Diamond Eyes. What matters is that the band can still find different—and fun—ways to combine and contrast it all.

author: Simon Vozick-Levinson
snippet: The first third feels like primal-scream therapy, with frontman Chino Moreno howling himself even rawer than usual. More original are the quieter numbers that show off Deftones' subtleties.

author: Spencer Kornhaber
snippet: Blissed-out and surreal, featuring queasy slides between loud and soft, it's a work of patient design and bloody fantasy. Brutal beauty abounds, but for the first time, Deftones are imitating rather than exploring.

author: Matthew Cole
snippet: When Diamond Eyes isn't trying quite so hard to be a great record, though, it ends up being a pretty good one.

author: Erin Clendaniel
snippet: Through the decades, music fans have witnessed how the loss of a key band member can lead to a group’s demise. The Deftones have proved just the opposite.

author: Andrew Burgess
snippet: Diamond Eyes is an impressive offering from a mainstay band whose time should have already come and gone.

author: Jon Dolan
snippet: Usually ... his lyrics go for cathartic images (shaking coffins, fading faces) set to chopping riffage, whirlpool distortion and dark, soaring melodies that sound more like the Cure than Korn.
Musically this is the most satisfying Deftones album in a decade, welding their patented post-hardcore crunch with their noted love of twisted, Cure-styled melody.

author: Stephen Rowland
snippet: Diamond Eyes features some surprisingly inspired moments. There are songs such as “Sextape” or “This Place is Death”, where the energy is palpable, and it seems like Deftones are giving their all. These moments, however, are few and far between.

author: Chris Martins
snippet: Flying Lotus reaches into the past in order to create something clearly of the future – a hybridized work that challenges others to follow its dazzling blueprint.

author: Euan Wallace
snippet: This could be a modern masterpiece for electronic music, with more albums like this, he'll be incomparable, an altogether stunning album and an amazing experience for the ear.

author: Hamish Duncan
snippet: This album is a hazy, dreamy, well oiled machine; perfectly crafted and, I suspect, will be a gateway album to many more of its kind for more than a few people.

author: Jonathan Dean
snippet: Cosmogramma is futurist in form, rather than content. Reliving the future's past through a constellation of references to cosmic jazz, psychedelic funk, hip-hop, and techno, the music of Flying Lotus never fixates long enough to crystallize; any groove that spontaneously emerges is quickly subverted, churned up in favor of a creating new maps and new vectors.

author: Janne Oinonen
snippet: Cosmic by name, cosmic by nature, ‘Cosmogramma’ packs an almighty load of that rarest of commodities in modern music: some genuinely new shit. Don’t let this joyfully bewildering shuttle pass you by.

author: David Amidon
snippet: Flying Lotus, much like Yorke, Greenwood & Co., has made a definitive summary of a decade’s worth of advances in electronic music, a release that transcends genre and deserves to become a glorified phenomena by those who experience it.

author: Jory Spadea
snippet: Pink Floyd may have invented the space opera, but Cosmogramma, 2010’s first major contender for best electronica album, transcends it to another dimension.
Flying Lotus‘ third album, Cosmogramma, is a strangely cohesive amalgam of exotic sounds.

author: Matthew Cole
snippet: Steve Ellison may be all kinds of intellectual, but on Cosmogramma he never loses sight of the less reflective pleasures of his craft.

author: William Rauscher
snippet: Cosmogramma moves without warning from mood to mood, genre to genre, all part of a holistic whole.

author: Erik Thompson
snippet: There is a clear link throughout Cosmogramma between music’s renowned past and its fitful future that sounds more vital than ever before.

author: Brendan Klinkenberg
snippet: Flying Lotus clearly puts effort into crafting something that, at first listen, can seem full of random sounds and give the effect of sensory overload.  But he is out to make music people think about, and think to.

author: Katelyn Hackett
snippet: On Cosmogramma, this never-ending stream of aural textures sounds effortless, and the enthralling swirl of jazz, drum 'n' bass, dubstep and hip-hop beckons you toward the edge of something damn near cosmic.

author: Joe Colly
snippet: The L.A. producer's head music, which pulls from jazz, hip-hop, videogame sounds, IDM, and more, is more dense and rewarding than ever.

author: Patrick Taylor
snippet: “Cosmogramma” is ambitious, wonky, slippery, glitchy, and beautiful.

Even though the steady presence of featured performances helps beautify Cosmogramma, this is essentially Ellison's crowning achievement. The album is sequenced with a sense of purpose, evidential from the promo being presented as a long continuous track.

author: Colin McGowan
snippet: Cosmogramma bursts with inventiveness; I've found myself careening around my apartment to sounds I don't recognize as of this Earth. That Lotus takes these vibrant ideas and sets them to pulses that move asses is incredible. Apparently everyone else is bouncing along in agreement.

author: Paul MacInnes
snippet: Add in a dabbling in the spirit of free jazz and one might expect this album to be a wilfully discordant aural trial. But it turns out to be quite the opposite. The parts may be disparate but they are made to submit to an abiding mood of vivacity and sunniness.

author: Chris Power
snippet: Cosmogramma is dense and devotional, Ellison piloting his craft into the fading slipstream of his aunt Alice Coltrane’s cosmic strain of jazz.

author: Jim Carroll
snippet: By honing and blending electronic hip-hop, jazz and skittering bass sonics into dramatic textures and patterns, Ellison has already demonstrated that he’s got the handle on the vision thing.
Fans of experimetal electronica will be [happy], though Radiohead devotees should exercise caution.

author: Michael Cragg
snippet: Proclamations of his greatness may be slightly exaggerated, but Cosmogramma certainly adds to a deservedly growing reputation.

author: Jason Lymangrover
snippet: Cosmogramma is an instrumental genre-jumping journey for head-bopping intellectuals, and the meditative melodies by vocalists Thundercat, Laura Darlington, and Thom Yorke only add to the experience.

author: Anthony Fantano
snippet: Flying Lotus' third album is by far his most diverse, loaded with elements of jazz, hip hop, and countless hybrids of electronic music. It's dense, boundless, engaging, and fun.

author: Emily Mackay
snippet: Picking us up where the laptop prof's 'Los Angeles' debut dropped us for another nocturnal journey through LA that serves as a moody, widescreen, be-bopping riposte to UK dubstep. Only this time it's a flashier ride.
Woozy, off-track beats blend with video game blips and organic strings, harp and sax, while a cameo from Thom Yorke is woven neatly into this lush, psychedelic fabric.

author: William Ketchum III
snippet: The musical legends that guest star here wouldn’t trust Flying Lotus if he didn’t trust himself—and trust is what makes this album work. Cosmogramma stays unpredictable without going too far off course, and uses unconventional sounds to deliver digestible results.

author: David Renshaw
snippet: Dense and obtuse it may be but those who follow this most intense sonic explorer will be rewarded the greatest.

author: Mosi Reeves
snippet: Warm and inviting, his latest opus occasions swan dives into future soul, funky dubstep ("Dance of the Pseudo Nymph"), Theo Parrish–styled house ("Do the Astral Plane"), and astonishingly, Sun Ra jazz ("Arkestry").

author: Alex Young
snippet: You should stick around and see the vivid pictures Flying Lotus skillfully paints for you as you make your way through the mysterious maze that is Cosmogramma.

author: Bram E. Gieben
snippet: An ambitious, challenging album from a sonic visionary, proving FlyLo is virtually peerless – perhaps only Brainfeeder labelmate Daedelus can touch him. Not for those who enjoy verse-chorus-verse or four-on-the-floor – but true aesthetes will devour Comsogramma with relish.
Cosmogramma is futuristic magnum opus that will indubitably be heralded as one of th emost intrepid albums of 2010.

author: Laurent Fintoni
snippet: Whether or not it’s deserving of the hype it has so far accrued is neither here nor there, but I can’t help but feel that should the promo push for it have been more subdued in its approach, it may have benefited the album, and Lotus, in the long run.

author: Ash Akhtar
snippet: Slipping through dubstep, garage, techno and hip-hop, Ellison's study of electronica created with the benefit of live instrumentation presents occasional orgiastic treats, but is mostly nothing more than an anti-mellifluous exercise in listener-satisfaction which, in the long term, is likely to render 'Cosmogramma' more an anachronism than cosmogram.

author: Reef Younis
snippet: Like flicking through pirate radio stations, ‘Cosmo…’ dances between the extremes but when it levels out and you’re rewarded with blankets of warm, rolling melody, you can’t help but be seduced.

author: Jon Dolan
snippet: There's some info overload, but Ellison is an ace with pacing, and a distracted soulfulness guides the frantic laptop science.

author: Jay Steele
snippet: With their third full-length effort, Beach House forces the listener to re-examine pop music status quo while taking another giant stride as a band.

author: Heather Phares
snippet: Though it's not as eclectic and whimsical as their earlier work, Teen Dream is some of their most beautiful music, and reaffirms that they're the among the best purveyors of languidly lovelorn songs since Mazzy Star.

author: Jim Carroll
snippet: Shimmering and evocative from start to finish, Teen Dream is an album that will haunt you for many months to come.

author: Simon Vozick-Levinson
snippet: On their third LP, Teen Dream, they evolve at last, adding more variety behind Victoria Legrand’s wonderfully weary vocals.

author: Chris Martins
snippet: Teen Dream is deeper in hue than its predecessors. Its blues are bluer, even while warmer tones abound, and Scally’s guitar emotes as lithely as the voice it dances with.

author: Mark Richardson
snippet: This is both the most diverse and most listenable of their three full-lengths, and yet it never seems like a compromise.

The greatest success of Teen Dream ... is its thematic connection ... Teen Dream is concerned with nostalgia for love lost with time; the kind of love that can be explained only by harmonious moans; and the kind of devotion their last album only touched on.

author: Jesse Cataldo
snippet: Like “Norway,” a mini masterpiece of vocal and musical interplay, Teen Dream boldly complies the subtle and the overt.

author: alison king
snippet: The depth hidden amongst Teen Dream will have many people missing out; returning to this record garners it a strength as you uncover the layers of shimmering nuances and secret delights you have missed the first time round.

author: Erik Thompson
snippet: With ‘Teen Dream’, Scally and Legrand have created absorbing, atmospheric music that never strains for significance or seriousness, but is affecting all the same.

author: Philip Cosores
snippet: Beach House is clearly ready to step out from the shadows and play timeless music intended for dreamers and romantics.

author: Stephen Deusner
snippet: Dream is a go-for-broke collection that not only creates and sustains a hi-fi drowse-pop drama throughout its 10 beguiling songs, but comes across like a logical and gorgeous extension of all the band’s previous dreams.

author: Laura Snapes
snippet: They’ve made an absolutely magical record – the jagged edges of their past have been smoothed by the sea, making ‘Teen Dream’ a soft shore gem in the crown of the great chronicles of youth.

author: Chris Barth
snippet: It is, without a doubt, Beach House’s best work, and deserves to be recognized as such.

Whether it's actually getting the gist of the heartbreaking/bizarre/haunting lyrics, just getting lost in the full sound of the record, or hearing something new going on in the background, this record has something for everyone.

author: Joel Elliott
snippet: Teen Dream is just such a fantastic pop record because it never seems to try to be: it’s almost as if the duo had intended to make another mopey shoegazing affair and accidentally stumbled upon something transcendent.
This record ... makes an indelible mark.

author: Paul Terefenko
snippet: Whereas previous efforts embellished dark, distant slumber sounds, Teen Dream finds the duo maturing into friendly pop.

author: Larry Fitzmaurice
snippet: Beach House have reached the point in their career where achieving grand melodic climaxes seems to come to them effortlessly, and on Teen Dream the climaxes are as thrilling as ever before.

Teen Dream finds the duo resolving to present their songs in somewhat firmer strokes. Nothing rocks, exactly, but organs coo in sharper focus, drum machines bear with added vigour, and an eerie disquiet occasionally linger.

author: Lukas Sherman
snippet: Teen Dream will be pleasantly familiar to fans of their first two albums, but it also offers some subtle changes.

author: Neil Condron
snippet: ‘Teen Dream’ suggests that this is a band with the rarest of touches, familiar in their frailty yet fathomless in their depths.
Baltimore-based dream-pop duo Beach House continues to master its craft of producing ethereal melodies and reverberating background instrumentation.

They occupy an ethereal wonderland of their own design on Teen Dream, a place where '80s soft rock mingles with slow-pop soliloquies, producing an oscillating, supernal bliss both sparkling and somber.

author: Peter Hayward
snippet: It’s an incredibly rewarding listen, even if the self-observing anxiety that’s writ large throughout means it doesn’t quite reach the lofty heights to which its creators have bravely aspired.

author: Juan Edgardo Rodríguez
snippet: Even if there’s that wistful, pastoral-like imagery to their sound, much of the tracks stray to their own beats, in desperate search of distinction. Instead of modest waltzes and looped drum machines, there’s an evident maturity in the way the production unveils itself as richer and far more multifaceted.

author: Thomas Britt
snippet: This strain of music might seem too safe for some, but its consistency is a virtue -- around which Beach House has developed a signature sound.
It’s a shimmery, escapist release, without a doubt, but as anything more than a mild sleeping aid, Teen Dream fails to rise above its genre.

author: Melissa Maerz
snippet: On their third album, those feelings now sound like actual songs, with swelling choruses and an all-encompassing ache.

author: Rick Pearson
snippet: The slow-burning nature of the songs means that mainstream popularity may remain elusive, but Beach House are certainly a secret worth knowing about.

author: Andrzej Lukowski
snippet: It’s shot through with more than a handful of heartstoppingly wonderful moments, it vastly improves on the Devotion, and heralds the arrival as Legrand as one of the finest singers in modern indie.

author: Alex Nelson
snippet: From the slim skiffle beat of Used To Be, supplemented by its bouncing piano, to the minimalist power-balladry of Real Love and back to the smoky atmosphere of tracks like Lover Of Mine, the album is full of dream-pop gems.

author: Jody Rosen
snippet: They're more radiant than ever on their third disc, particularly on songs like "Zebra," with background chorales swooping over stately guitar plucking.

author: Andrew Ryce
snippet: They’re refining their craft, producing some of their most bewitching material yet, but the rest of it feels like they’re merely spinning their wheels while they wait for more interesting ideas to come along.
Teen Dream is a lovely album, but there's more to admire here than to actually love. Oddly, that may not be a problem.

author: Tom Hughes
snippet: With their third album, the Baltimore duo of Victoria Legrand and Alex Scally throw themselves on the ever-growing pile of American bands going for the heartstrings via a kind of wide-eyed, epic psych-pop.

author: Louise Brailey
snippet: Those looking for the next faintly interesting band from across the pond will be disappointed by Beach House’s muted sonic conservatism – much of Teen Dream props itself too readily upon a kind of medicated numbness

author: Peter Tabakis
snippet: Speak Now is a well-earned tiara atop of Taylor Swift’s blonde tresses, an album that deserves to sell zillions of records. As it no doubt will.

author: Leah Greenblatt
snippet: Speak‘s 14 tracks are perfectly contained snow globes of romance and catharsis, whole cinematic narratives rendered in four-to six-minute miniatures.

author: Sam Sodomsky
snippet: After all, this music was precisely about these moments when your fantasies no longer apply to reality, when you have to grow up and make a choice and live with it on your own. She excused herself for a moment, and when she returned, she had a better idea.

author: Dave Heaton
snippet: All of Speak Now engages in that act of making our story hers, and her story ours, which is what pop stars do well.

author: Stephen Thomas Erlewine
snippet: She may be not a girl, and not yet a woman, but on Speak Now she captures that transition with a personal grace and skill that few singer/songwriters have.

author: Joe Breen
snippet: As an album that crystalises the competing demands of childhood and adulthood and the space inbetween, it is remarkably candid and articulate.

author: Alex Macpherson
snippet: Speak Now is a conscious attempt to move beyond those childish things while retaining her balance of maturity and relatability.

author: Rob Sheffield
snippet: Swift’s third album, Speak Now, is roughly twice as good as 2008’s Fearless, which was roughly twice as good as her 2006 debut.

author: Liz Stinson
snippet: On Speak Now, Swift is strongest when she lets her country roots shine through.

author: Rick Moore
snippet: Speak Now is Taylor Swift’s best record yet, all in her voice with no co-writers. It’s a powerful statement from someone who has proven that she knows who she is, and, whether Nashville likes it or not, is here to stay.

I can still listen to a record as uneven as Speak Now and feel like Taylor Swift is somebody I could fall in love with given the chance. I can still set aside an hour of my time to truly listen to this girl who came out of nowhere to become a household name and forget about all of that because of how amazed I am at her talent.

author: Mikael Wood
snippet: Let’s have a toast for the ladies who stick it to the douchebags.

author: Steven Hyden
snippet: Speak Now falters whenever Swift lets her outsized personality be subsumed by big, generic ballads.

author: Jonathan Keefe
snippet: Speak Now is an album of expertly crafted pop music that actually justifies at least some of the critical hyperbole and commercial clout that have characterized the last two years of Swift’s career.

author: Andrew Murfett
snippet: While her delivery can sometimes be unpleasant, damn if there's not some earnest belief behind it

author: David Smyth
snippet: America's biggest-selling musician of 2008 returns with her third album and the same USP — repackaging the story songs of country for a teen pop audience — though this time it's a bit harder for her fans to relate to the extensive boy trouble she recounts.

author: Kevin Ritchie
snippet: The album expands Swift’s repertoire from country to blues and brooding arena-ballad territory, but ultimately she plays it too safe with the arrangements.

author: Chase McMullen
snippet: Recovery finds Eminem at the top of his game, roaring back to life.

author: Simon Vozick-Levinson
snippet: Eminem returns to the verbal acrobatics that defined his early work, showering these 17 songs with dazzling cadences and multisyllabic rhymes.

author: Omar Burgess
snippet: Em adapted with the times, and even during his musical missteps, he’s pushing himself to experiment.

author: Neil McCormick
snippet: This is the album many fans have been waiting for Eminem to make. At 37, he drops the fart gags and cheap pop culture slander, to let rip on a subject that actually matters to him: himself.
Throughout “Recovery,” the rapper’s first album since overcoming an addiction to pharmaceuticals, Eminem is unsparing in assessing the weakness of character that led to his descent into drugs.

author: Brian Boyd
snippet: Very much a portrait of someone on the ropes who's swinging out wildly and more often than not connecting, Recovery shows that Eminem's best defence is a full-frontal attack on most everyone and everything around him.

author: Jody Rosen
snippet: Em is just a few years shy of 40, and if he’s seeming more and more like a grumpy middle-aged man, at least he’s owning it — he sounds content to be rap’s wittiest head case.

author: John Aizlewood
snippet: After seven albums, Eminem is so far ahead of the pack he only has himself to compete with. Even by that measurement, he's winning.
Recovery is everything Relapse was not: heartfelt, dramatic and really quite good. Granted, it's not quite everything The Marshall Mathers LP was, but it feels like the same man again.

author: Alex Young
snippet: The aptly named Recovery admits the misstep that was Relapse and gives us all hope for the future of Eminem, which was looking somewhat bleak before this release.

author: Sean O'Neal
snippet: Always at his liveliest when he’s feeling persecuted, Eminem unflinchingly owns up to a lot on his road to redemption—but really, all he had to do was drop the farts and faux-Jamaican patois.

author: Chris Molnar
snippet: In a society already inured to Drake, our collective investment in Em’s personal drama makes Recovery surprisingly affecting. And every song is as earnest as the last.

author: Benjamin Meadows-Ingram
snippet: Is Recovery a classic album? No. But is it an essential one in shaping Eminem’s future? Absolutely.

author: Matt Popkin
snippet: We haven’t heard an Eminem effort like this since the beginning of the millennium.

author: Sam Wolfson
snippet: The real Slim Shady is standing once more, and his return to form is all the more convincing for its honesty.

author: David Jeffries
snippet: It may be flawed and the rapper’s attitude is sometimes one step ahead of his output, but he hasn’t sounded this unfiltered and proud since The Marshall Mathers LP.

author: Michael Cragg
snippet: He’s battled through drug addiction and, if Talkin’ 2 Myself is to be believed, a suicide attempt, to make an album that is light years ahead of his last two but that doesn’t quite scale the heights of his purple patch in the early part of the last decade.

author: Jay Soul
snippet: This will hold a bizarre position in his catalogue – “Recovery” is not his best, nor his worst, but either people will listen incessantly or barely at all. There is no middle ground.

author: Mike Schiller
snippet: For all of its stumbles into Em’s all-too-common crutches, however, Recovery is at the very least showing signs of maturity amongst raps that are as skilled as anything he’s done since The Marshall Mathers LP.

author: Paul MacInnes
snippet: Not a classic perhaps, but Recovery puts a stop to any concern that Eminem had become nothing more than a bawdy caricature.

author: Bernard Zuel
snippet: One thing missing from Recovery is humour.

author: Jason Richards
snippet: Unfortunately, the results are patchy.

author: Andy Gill
snippet: The only completely commendable sentiment on the entire album comes in the proud rehab anthem "Not Afraid", where he determines to take control of his life and become borderline decent again.

author: Adam Johns
snippet: The songs where he attempts to reiterate his past glories are arguably the biggest failures of all. The album is a sprawling, confusing, self-indulgent mess.
Fairly generalised misogyny pervades the album, though it would be churlish not to not that tracks like "White Trash Party" or "On Fire" both display flashes of Eminem's wit.

author: Martin Skivington
snippet: Recovery ... is anything but the Detroit rapster's blazing return to form. It's certainly intense, as Mathers tries to make amends with some dazzlingly intricate wordplay, but musically the album is characterised by dubious production choices, cringeworthy hooks, a complete lack of humour, and some genuinely bad songs.

author: M.T. Richards
snippet: How can such a wondrous talent as Eminem make such a bloated, sullen, and detestable album as this?

author: Jakob Dorof
snippet: For the average listener, Recovery will prove to be a very stale and disposable record; for the discerning Eminem fan, a sad and unwitting betrayal.

author: Jayson Greene
snippet: Eminem spends nearly half of Recovery insisting he's the best rapper alive, but for the first time in his career, he actually sounds clumsy.

The power trio dials back the Cream stomp and melts the bass and drums into a sludgy puddle of groove so viscous that the album feels completely of a piece, like a slab of tarmac softening in the sun.
Innerspeaker coasts so beautifully on its blissful, billowing waves of sound that readily discernible hooks almost seem like gratuitous distractions.
Nothing ever clashes; the varied elements of these songs don’t compete but rather harmonize, working together to emanate an effortless, dreamlike vibe, a “chill” record if ever there was one.

author: Zach Kelly
snippet: Innerspeaker demonstrates a subtle yet encompassing sense of control, never obstructing the grander motifs while still offering a variety of odd details that guide you back to the album's hooks.
Tame Impala succeeded in arriving to the world with a fully-fledged sound and a concise and enjoyable debut album. Innerspeaker is a record full of warm sounds and it rarely gets boring.
The best way to enjoy Innerspeaker is to turn your mind off, relax and float downstream.
‘Innerspeaker’ is a brilliantly confident body of work – one that captures the spirit of the complex, ranging, pelvic workouts of the their targets, if lacking in out-and-out highs.
Tame Impala struggle with originality ... but they've concocted such a dreamily enjoyable debut that complaining about their fidelity seems pointless.

The album's production is authentically fuzzy in a kind of multi-tracked, tape on loop kind of way; and on tracks such as 'Solitude Is Bliss' and 'Desire Be Desire Go' they show a strong sense of melody despite all the distortion and dissonance.
There’s little sense that Innerspeaker could’ve been etched out in the 21st century. Fuzz and distortion colour the whole record, preserving the rough and ready garage tone of that self-titled EP.

The songs are spacey but energised, riding an insistent groove with enough altered state to feel like the lava lamp is on high, the strobe light higher and your core temperature a little off the scale.
There are just enough standout moments to lead Innerspeaker out of dullness and predictability.
The songs that do work rock pretty hard. Innerspeaker is the type of album that might be a little hard to admit liking – it’s self-serious, self-righteous, overlong, and occasionally infuriating.

Innerspeaker won't rewrite the history books or reinvent the wheel, but at the same time it serves its purpose as a shining example of the fact that having a nostalgic outlook needn't necessarily be deemed a negative course of action.

author: Anthony Fantano
snippet: Tame Impala brings back the sounds of 60s psych like it's nobody's business, but I can't help but feel like the band is more of an exercise in nostalgia than anything else.
Innerspeaker’s songs are compositionally meticulous but also emotionless, and if an album can be described as professorial, it’s this one.

While the musicianship is excellent, there isn’t nearly enough to keep ‘Innerspeaker’ from plodding along, with plenty of good ideas, but lacking the execution to rise above very colourful mediocrity.

author: Richard Trapunski
snippet: Some might argue that the album is bloated and overlong, but it's the denseness that makes it feel like such a Statement Record.

author: Sam Lee
snippet: It seems that absolutely everything that Win and Co. lay their hands on turns into pure musical gold. It doesn't matter if it sounds how Arcade Fire 'should' sound. The simple fact remains: 'The Suburbs' is a flawless album.
The Suburbs is a giant leap forward in songcraft.

author: James Christopher Monger
snippet: If nostalgia is just pain recalled, repaired, and resold, then The Suburbs is its sales manual.

author: Andy Gill
snippet: The prevailing tone of The Suburbs is of a more reflective, nostalgic bent – as if rumination upon the past might indeed offer a valid refuge from the uncertainties and worries of the present.

author: Michael Roffman
snippet: The idea behind The Suburbs is simple, if not universal. It’s about aging. Of course it’s deeper than that, but if you were to summarize all the underlying emotions and just cut right to the chase, it’s really about coming to grips with the full package that is growing up.

‘The Suburbs’ is an astonishing achievement for Arcade Fire; it boasts exquisite sophisticated songwriting that subtly taps into a sense of modern existential anxiety and elevates its makers yet again into a different musical league entirely.

Arcade Fire, because they’re really this damn good, are among the very few indie bands that could attempt a 65-minute album about the philosophical quandaries of the suburbs and pull it off completely.

author: Sean Highkin
snippet: There’s no shortage of the group’s usual flag-waving stadium rock ... but this time around, they are balanced out by hushed, pensive ballads.

author: Leah Greenblatt
snippet: At 60-plus minutes, Suburbs could use an edit, but it seems churlish to begrudge them a little indulgence when there is so much here to savor.

author: Noel Murray
snippet: Butler and company imbue The Suburbs with such a strong sense of place and mood that it builds in impact throughout.

author: Lawrence Poole
snippet: Scanning in at 16-tracks and bookended by tantalising tasters from the title track, 'The Suburbs' is a beautifully crafted and judged record.

author: Matthew Bennett
snippet: Taking their perennial themes of loss, fear, control and time they’ve re-woven their epic art rock around their fascinating suburban theme that literally lies on our own doorstep.

author: Matthew Cole
snippet: Another triumph of emotional generosity from the most humane and vital rock group of our generation.

author: Ben Marsden
snippet: While it could be said there’s a lack of the primal force that dominated ‘Funeral’, it’s been replaced with craft and beauty.

author: Matt Pinder
snippet: There is a good mix of high energy, upbeat and hecticness in parts of this sixteen track record that go together well with calmer arrangements giving this a beauty and a beast element.

author: John Everhart
snippet: Trying to put The Suburbs in historical context at this stage is difficult, but it evokes Sonic Youth's Daydream Nation in its evocation of political discontent coupled with sheer white noise outbursts.

author: Jude Clarke
snippet: Arcade Fire have never been a band shy of tackling big themes. Their momentous debut album Funeral addressed death, somehow making it seem invigorating and inspiring, as well as tragic, epic and heartrending, while 2007's Neon Bible melded religion and natural disasters (the tsunami, the New Orleans floods) in a portentous, unsettling blend of pomp and darkness.

author: Alan Shulman
snippet: They’ve spent most of the decade shouting to be heard, but now they are content to let the music and the message flower and take root.  You might think they are just tired, but their nervous energy survives intact.

author: David Marchese
snippet: The Suburbs burns on behalf of the belief that modern culture is missing its heart — and to give up the search is to send one’s soul to oblivion.

author: Emily Mackay
snippet: They’ve judged their moment perfectly, and this deserves to be their ‘Automatic For The People’; an album that combines mass accessibility with much greater ambition.

author: Chris Barth
snippet: The Suburbs is perhaps the most coherent schizophrenic you will ever meet, for though the guidance offered in its songs may be contradictory, the subject matter is never under discussion.
At 16 tracks, this dense, complicated set covers considerably more stylistic territory than either of the band's previous albums.

author: Ian Cohen
snippet: It's a satisfying return to form-- proof that Arcade Fire can still make grand statements without sounding like they're carrying the weight of the world.

author: Conrad Amenta
snippet: The Suburbs is that composed, mature culmination in forlorn adulthood (acceptance). It’s a staid achievement—a soundtrack to unwillingly letting go of the unsustainable, both figurative and literal.

author: Andy Beta
snippet: Swelling at 16 songs and an hour-plus runtime, it’s Arcade Fire’s most ambitious and concept-driven effort to date.

author: Rick Pearson
snippet: Those in search of arms-aloft anthems will leave feeling short-changed; the rest of us will agree that, in the case of The Suburbs, less is more.

author: Brian Boyd
snippet: Finishing with the archly titled Sprawl I and Sprawl II, which drip with childhood nostalgia, there's just time for a poignant a cappella reworking of the title track before they drift back to the city again. Very big and very clever.

author: Andrew Perry
snippet: For all their mainstream commercial appeal ... you can’t take the “art” out of these art-rockers.

author: Anthony Fantano
snippet: On Arcade Fire's latest album, they take the most ambitious and immediate elements of their previous albums, and feed them into americana-style songwriting.

author: David Harris
snippet: If there is one thing that separates the Arcade Fire from their contemporaries, it’s their ability to expose a human’s beating heart and hold it up undaunted.

author: Paula Carino
snippet: The Suburbs offers plenty of the dense and stately keyboard-heavy pop that fans of the band have come to expect, with some much-appreciated frothier moments, but a melancholy theme of reluctant adulthood, or resistance to change, runs through even the more lightweight numbers.
For all its intimations of rootless drift, The Suburbs finds Arcade Fire back home, and so much happier for it.
If Funeral was organic, and Neon Bible was force-fed, The Suburbs makes do with being merely delicious. (And a little wistful, wounded, and wise.)

author: Alexis Petridis
snippet: There's something charming about the way an album about growing up in the suburban 80s gradually starts to resemble a chart rundown from 1983.

author: Rob Sheffield
snippet: The strange thing about Arcade Fire is how they instinctively scale their most intimate confessions to arena-rock levels, rolling out big drums and glossy keyboards.
The Suburbs is a prize-winning, finely tuned botanical garden, and Butler has every right to say whatever he pleases to his trespassers.

author: Michael H. Miller
snippet: Arcade Fire’s seven members resemble an archetypal family. They grew up — on record, anyway — in the bittersweet nostalgia of small neighborhoods, remembering the bedrooms of their parents and the bedrooms of their friends; moved on to the bright lights of histrionic cities, trying to avoid it when the planes hit the ground; and now, migrated to the suburbs. (Where else does one go after producing Neon Bible, one of the decade’s more somber statements on existence?) But far from a comforting escape from all that came before, Arcade Fire’s suburbia is a lot like Cheever’s: menacing, shadowing the depression of lost innocence and the paranoia of adulthood behind a pretty white picket fence.

author: Andrzej Lukowski
snippet: A few nights ago, I decided that it would be a brilliant idea to write my review of Arcade Fire’s third album in real time. I would allot myself its not inconsiderable running length to bash out this article, whilst also, crucially, knocking back a finger of beer for each mention of “the kids” or “the suburbs” in Win Butler’s lyrics.

At 16 songs, The Suburbs could have been compressed into a focused, stinging album, but as it stands, the band’s tendency to dip into art-school pretentiousness and tired lyrical clichés drags the whole ship down.

author: Louise Brailey
snippet: The Suburbs is one last attempt to understand what it means to be an adult in the face of the unavoidable future of settling down and becoming your parents.

author: Mischa Pearlman
snippet: On the whole, the introspective, personal nature of the subject matter jars with the overblown arrangements that carry them.

author: Thomas Britt
snippet: Last year’s war of words between the Flaming Lips’ Wayne Coyne and Arcade Fire front man Win Butler was, at the time, an enjoyable diversion. Although Coyne’s comments (about what he perceived as arrogance in Butler’s crew) seemed somewhat impolite and petty, the flare-up between the two acts injected some energy and fun into a modern rock scene that is too often stuffy and image-conscious. Butler responded, Coyne apologized then retracted his apology, and finally the whole affair died down. Both bands continued to sell records and make money.
So yeah, you can thank him now. He’s earned it.

author: John Twells
snippet: Thank Me Later is certainly a part of the post-808s fallout, but also among one of the first examples of what may as well be seen as a new genre altogether. It is still hip hop, just – but introspective, personal, sometimes experimental and only occasionally radio-friendly.

author: Mariel Concepcion
snippet: Toronto MC Drake has said that he wants fans to feel the different layers of his debut, “Thank Me Later.” From the sounds of it, he’s held little back, sharing with listeners his deepest thoughts.

author: Clayton Purdom
snippet: He is guilty of narcissism, cynicism, even a blank sort of stupidity—so, indeed, are my other fifty favorite rappers.

author: Ryan Dombal
snippet: Drake sings or raps the word "I" 410 times on his debut album. Even in the realm of hip-hop-- a style famous for its unswerving solipsism-- this is a feat. For comparison's sake, noted mirror watcher Kanye West managed to work only 220 "I"'s into the verses and hooks of his big break, The College Dropout. Illmatic; 210. Reasonable Doubt; 240. With Thank Me Later, Drake attempts to enter the pantheon of those rap game-busters by the sheer force of first person singular pronouns. All eyes are on him-- especially his own. But considering this mixed race, half-Jewish, all-Canadian "Degrassi: The Next Generation" alum looks and sounds unlike any major rap star before him, betting the house on nothing but himself turns out to be a wise gamble.

author: Nathan Rabin
snippet: Thank Me Later is filled with profound ambivalence about the process that transformed Drake from a supporting player in a Canadian high-school soap opera into one of the hottest acts in music.

author: Michael Saba
snippet: Drake may not have been able to meet the dizzyingly high expectations for his debut, but then again, no one could have. So he did the next best thing—release a solid and consistent album that showcases his prodigious talent.

author: Michael Cragg
snippet: Self-obsessed, paranoid, fleetingly spectacular and always interesting, Thank Me Later does indeed mark the arrival of rap's newest superstar.

author: Paul Cantor
snippet: On Thank Me Later, he explores what it’s like to have done that—to have become successful. Turns out, it’s not exactly what he thought it would be. But it still sounds pretty damn remarkable.

author: Tim Sendra
snippet: Thanks to the rich and nuanced production and Drake's thoughtful, playful, and intense lyrics, Thank Me Later is a radio-friendly, chart-topping collection of singles but also a serious examination of Drake's life that holds up as an album.

author: Ben Detrick
snippet: Ultimately, Thank Me Later‘s revelry concludes with emotional disgorgement, but no messy hangover.

author: David Renshaw
snippet: Actor turned rapper Drake’s first album proper sees the Toronto native flitting between champagne egotism and introspective self-doubt in a way that can only be described as post-Kanye.

author: Nate Knaebel
snippet: Because of his relatively privileged upbringing (he’s from a wealthy part of Toronto), Thank Me Later is less about chronicling and rising up out of his environment (like basically every rap debut since Illmatic) and more about how Drake is uncomfortable being famous.

author: Simon Vozick-Levinson
snippet: The Degrassi actor-turned-hip-hop heartthrob, who spends half of his debut Thank Me Later rapping about the anxieties and disappointments that have come with his success. The rest of the time he croons in the seductive monotone that made him so popular in the first place.

author: Daniel Roberts
snippet: It is unclear exactly what kind of artist Aubrey Drake Graham wants to be. Groomed by Lil Wayne, taken out partying with big boys like Jay-Z and Diddy, the kid seems to view himself as a member of that company—a hard rapper. But he’s bucking what seem to be his truer colors as a slower, R&B-type singer in the style of Usher or Ne-Yo. On Thank Me Later, easily one of the most anticipated releases of the summer, the identity crisis is in full swing.

author: Jody Rosen
snippet: Drake is in total command of a style that would have been hard to imagine dominating hip-hop a few years ago: He's subtle and rueful rather than loud and lively; emotionally transparent rather than thuggy.

author: Jesse Cataldo
snippet: Thank Me Later nails confused introspection in a genre famous for willful misrepresentation of self.

author: Jay Soul
snippet: He should progress and improve (unless acting lures him back again), but this is nowhere near the buzzworthy Great Rap Hope we witnessed on “So Far Gone”, this time around, it’s more like “2 Far Gone.”

author: Emily Mackay
snippet: It’s those constant and predictable superstar interjections that prevent the album from standing out as much as it had potential to do.

author: Andres Tardio
snippet: Drake proves that he can give you two sides of himself and his art: the mixtape and the album, and as Black Sheep say, the choice is yours.

author: Chris Coplan
snippet: With the roster of guest MCs and producers, Drake’s shown his understanding of the game and his willingness to learn. Even without further development and growth, his career should continue to keep people talking, good or bad, all the way to the bank.

author: Sean Highkin
snippet: Drake seems like a nice enough guy, but he doesn’t do anything on his debut album to justify his high opinion of his own career.

author: Chris Barth
snippet: Thank Me Later is a disappointment, through and through. I know we’re in this nouveau stoner rap era, but if Kid Cudi’s barely present album and this latest Drake record are any indication of the state of hip hop, I’m packing my bags and leaving. This is drizzy drivel.
By the album's close ... his vulnerability risks tipping over into maudlin self-pity.

author: Joshua Errett
snippet: After a year of anticipating what should’ve been a game-changer, Drake turns in a merely passable album and comes across as the rap music version of Justin Bieber.

author: Stephen Thomas Erlewine
snippet: There’s no question Perry is smart enough to know every rule in pop but she’s not inspired enough to ignore them, almost seeming nervous to break away from the de rigeur lite club beats that easily transition from day to night or the chilly, stainless-steel ballads designed to lose none of their luster on repeat plays.
For all the pomp and watermelon costumes, Perry is primarily a smart and personal pop songwriter. And "Teenage Dream" shows-in carefully selected spots-that she's ready to grow up.

author: Daniel Kohn
snippet: She’s not reinventing pop music or trying to change the world, but this album is an accurate barometer of where pop music is today.

author: Anna Gaca
snippet: More often, Teenage Dream feels dated, and not just because of the white girl with a feather headdress in the “Teenage Dream” video or 2010-vintage lyrical clunkers like, “That was such an epic fail.” Ironically, it’s the fresh-faced power-pop of One of the Boys that aged better; the attempt to outdo it sounds loud, insistent, compressed.

author: Leah Greenblatt
snippet: Beneath the fruity outfits and fart jokes, Perry is clearly serious about the business of hit songcraft; that doesn’t make Dream nearly cohesive as an album, but it does provide, intermittently, exactly the kind of high-fructose rush she’s aiming for.

author: Rob Sheffield
snippet: Teenage Dream is the kind of pool-party-pop gem that Gwen Stefani used to crank out on the regular, full of SoCal ambience and disco beats. It’s miles ahead of Perry’s breakthrough disc, One of the Boys, with her clever songwriting boosted by top-dollar pros: Dr. Luke, Max Martin, Tricky Stewart, Stargate.

author: David Smyth
snippet: Katy Perry's second album turns everything up to 11.

author: Kevin Courtney
snippet: Her second album sees the future Mrs Russell Brand make the leap to major-league pop queen.
She's got some distance to travel before she's a truly mind-blowing, norm-shattering pop star. She's not the new Madonna, just a very naughty girl.

author: Annabel Ross
snippet: Teenage Dream might be uneven but Perry's hits are big enough to outweigh any misses.

author: Neil McCormick
snippet: Katy Perry seems more cheeky than transgressive in her new album 'Teenage Dream'.

author: Mikael Wood
snippet: Teenage Dream won’t disappoint parents looking for reasons to worry about their kids.

author: Josh Becker
snippet: On an album that started off on such a wonderfully dreamlike note, the onslaught of tired cliches and forgettable melodies that constitutes its second half leaves the listener anxious to wake up from this Dream.

author: Marc Hawthorne
snippet: Perry returned with lots of ho-hum ballads and lackluster radio fodder as limp as the discarded lover in the dis track “Circle The Drain.”

author: Michael Cragg
snippet: It's the kind of disposable pop that leaves your head almost as soon as it's over. It's an album of singles placed in no significant order and with no particular thread.

I can forgive a couple of transgressions if Teenage Dream redeemed itself with songs that were more than trashy, one-dimensional pop, but, alas, the rest of the album is just as predictable as the VMAs and only marginally more entertaining.

author: Jason Richards
snippet: Teenage Dream is an unapologetic play for pop dominance, calculated to sound very much of the present.

author: Steve Leftridge
snippet: Now, instead of making an attempt at an artistic leap forward, Perry has, with her candy-coated follow-up, Teenage Dream, doubled down on the formula that got her here.

author: David Pott-Negrine
snippet: The most interesting thing here is the lyrics. Taken out of context, they’re not wholly remarkable and say little more then the typical lyric fodder of aren’t boys great, aren’t boys dumb, I like drinking in clubs, yadda yadda yadda. But when you put them in context with Katy Perry the popstar it becomes obvious that half of the songs were written before she became Mrs Russell Brand, and so more than likely deal with her break-up with that ball bag from the musical abomination Gym Class Heroes, and the other half are all about her new relationship with the guy who decided it would be a good idea to go to work dressed as Osama Bin Laden on the day after the September 11th terror attacks.

author: Matthew Cole
snippet: The remainder of Teenage Dream is a raunchy pop nightmare, with A-list producers lining up to churn out some of the worst work of their careers.

author: Andy Gill
snippet: It wouldn't be so bad if there were some inventive musical value to compensate, but the brutish electropop backing tracks assembled by Dr Luke et al are almost as bereft as Perry's robotic delivery of her trash lyrics.
Brooklyn duo deliver shock psychedelic masterpiece.

author: Keith Phipps
snippet: It offers one sonic reward after another, and the band remains as inviting as ever.

author: Lindsey Fortier
snippet: The new nine-song album blends psychedelia with elements of post-punk, surf rock and even folk.

author: Gregory Heaney
snippet: From the opening moments of the sublime “It’s Working” all the way to the titular closer, Congratulations is an incredible follow-up from a band that is still maturing into some unknown entity.

author: Sam Richards
snippet: This is a wilful and lovably eccentric second album from a band who've had a sniff of being pop stars and decided they'd much rather be weird and esoteric, thanks all the same.
The album evokes not claustrophobia but space and freedom: an exhilarating screw-the-consequences leap into the bizarre.

author: Anthony Fantano
snippet: MGMT's Congratulations makes me want to say this to the band: Congratulations.

author: Charles Aaron
snippet: MGMT may be dazed, but they’re not tweaked out yet.

author: Jay Steele
snippet: MGMT plots a strange course for their listeners with Congratulations, but the material here often exceeds that of the band’s initial full-length.

author: John Everhart
