snippet: They never fully reconcile this conundrum, but have nonetheless created a fine record, which, while distantly removed stylistically from their first, doesn't lose grasp of their innate pop instincts, channeling them in a more elliptical, silvery manner.

author: Chris Molnar
snippet: While MGMT may no longer peddle the kind of instant-pleasure-point melodic textures that propelled the band's most well-known songs into so many playlists, they're up to something far more interesting: releasing a major, mainstream objet d'art without for a minute fooling themselves that it "matters."

author: Leah Greenblatt
snippet: Undoubtedly, some fans will be left feeling deflated, but this odd little sonic onion ultimately rewards those patient enough to peel the layers.

author: Andrzej Lukowski
snippet: Congratulations is no more impenetrable than the Flaming Lips at their most commericial, with Sonic Boom offering a bright, upfront mix that keeps the baffling array of omichords, guitars, sitars, synths, organs and FX percolating in dynamic, uncluttered fashion.

author: Gareth O'Malley
snippet: Bold, brave, bonkers, and sometimes brilliant.

author: Tim Miller
snippet: MGMT remain great songwriters, and at the heart of much of Congratulations are great songs. It's just that this time around, they've gone back to basics, borrowing a slew of enduring influences, making popular music the way it was made when popular music was still in its infancy.

author: Scott Plagenhoef
snippet: Every track here has successful passages, but frustratingly, they too often turn out to be detours or trap doors. In general, the less cluttered and more focused their tracks are, the better they turn out.

author: Chris Barth
snippet: The fact of that matter is that Congratulations remains a sketch, a half-baked attempt to distance MGMT from its previous oeuvre.

author: Larry Weaver
snippet: In the end, it sounds less like a step forward, and more like a trek into the past glory of ’60s psychedelic – but with nothing new added to the formula.

author: Richard Trapunski
snippet: None of the songs hit as hard as Kids or Electric Feel, but there's also no filler (which is more than we can say for OS). Instead, the band delivers a consistent if self-indulgent offering of oddball prog-pop.

author: Neil McCormick
snippet: The follow-up might not exactly be an act of self-sabotage, but it veers perilously close in its aura of self-indulgence and self-amusement.

author: Bernard Zuel
snippet: Congratulations will likely be seen as a firm ''up yours'' by a lot of fans. I can see their point but I wonder if they'll see MGMT's point, that standing still is more boring than any tricky double-neck guitar heroics could ever be.

author: David Smyth
snippet: As with The Flaming Lips' recent album, Embryonic, it adds up to commercial suicide, but it makes an interesting change from bands desperately clinging to a winning formula.

author: Dave Simpson
snippet: Their mainstream audience should flee now, but Congratulations is more than mere commercial suicide. Their perversity has produced a sonic adventure, with lovely moments.

author: Will Hermes
snippet: With Congratulations, they attempt to not just keep it weird — which they've done — but to figure out how they can be in it for the long haul. It's a solid start.

author: Kevin Gary
snippet: Cliché’s, presented as is with no attempt at exploration or deconstruction, will never be revelatory or mind expanding, will never display your “artistic depth” to the popular masses. MGMT have proven this by making one of the biggest clichés of all, the “difficult second album.”

author: Emily Mackay
snippet: Overall, MGMT's refusal to co-operate with the listener jars with the crisp and professional production – which, despite Sonic Boom's involvement, is more Van Dyke Parks than Spacemen 3 and leaves Congratulations sitting somewhere in the middle, not complex enough for the prats, but too obscure for the jerks.

author: Zach Schonfeld
snippet: In the absence of Oracular’s pulsing, dance-ready synth-pop, Congratulations takes its cues from the cosmic-charged psychedelia of that album’s latter half.

author: John Murphy
snippet: It's a brave, sometimes successful, but ultimately flawed attempt to evolve and grow the band's sound. The one crime is a distinct lack of any memorable tunes, but it will certainly stand as one of 2010's more interesting releases.

author: Kevin Liedel
snippet: In striving rather openly to set their sophomore effort apart from what they view as the critically acclaimed trappings of their debut, MGMT offers what is, essentially, an album of B-sides--a few bright spots strung together with half-baked concepts and monotony, in need of a lot less knob-tweaking and a whole lot more rewrites.

MGMT have (purposely?) lost that instant magic that they effortlessly whipped up with those debut singles, and in trying to re-establish themselves as artists that don't need the commercial mainstream to survive, they've created a record that lacks any defining characteristics to call its own.

author: Michael Roffman
snippet: Here’s one important question though, and answer it after you’ve finished Congratulations: “Would you even listen to this record if it wasn’t by MGMT?”.

author: Jakob Dorof
snippet: While the only ostensible reason for MGMT’s stylistic 180 is to seem less like a lightweight pop act, the songs on Oracular were far more engaging and better written than almost anything here.

Congratulations shares nary a sonic smidgen with Oracular Spectacular, instead existing in a netherworld where mod-era psychedelia meets prog-rock and where the ecstatic heights of the band's debut don't exist.

author: Andrew Baer
snippet: None of the songs are good enough as growers or deep tracks to hold up the album.

author: Nathan Kamal
snippet: Expectations are always high on a sophomore album, and Congratulations doesn’t even try to live up to what fans may have wanted, but doesn’t quite work on its own terms, either.

If the point of music is for us to take something from it - whether it be an emotional response or a change in mindset or any sort of inspiration - then The Age Of Adz is the most selfless album ever recorded, and Sufjan is the most giving composer.

author: Simon Vozick-Levinson
snippet: The Age of Adz complements rather than distracts from the heartrending melodies and ambitious orchestration underneath.

author: Kevin Liedel
snippet: Stevens’s conceptual obsessions continue on this trippy, orchestrated journey that is, in two words, beautifully neurotic.

author: Ed Comentale
snippet: The whole album is a gorgeous mess, and you’ll immediately want to be dragged through it all over again.

author: Luis Tovar
snippet: The Age of Adz is a distinct change in style, but it is not, I would guess, a one-off experiment.

author: Chris Barth
snippet: Each pass cements that Stevens has done the impossible yet again: He's released another album that's both genre-defining and genre-defying.

author: Josh Jackson
snippet: It’s what you hope for from your favorite artists in your best moments—evolution, a little difficulty and, especially, something new.

author: Rob Hakimian
snippet: Words such as “experimental,” “bloated” and “different” will be thrown around, but the truth is that despite the new angle The Age of Adz does nothing but solidify Stevens’ position as indie rock’s most beloved and foremost purveyor of orchestral chamber-pop.

author: Ryan Dombal
snippet: But instead of succumbing to trends, Stevens barrels through with another long-form work that requires-- and rewards-- time and devotion.

author: Paul Terefenko
snippet: In some ways the change in direction makes you feel closer to him than ever – especially if you can digest Impossible Soul, a 25-minute dissection of failed love at the end of this already lofty 75-minute charmer.
The Age Of Adz ... is problematic for its mind-boggling ambitions, as Stevens harnesses his folkier songcraft and complex orchestration to electronica.

author: Jamie Atkins
snippet: Brave and beautiful, this is a thoroughly modern statement of an album – and well worth the wait.
Dazzling with its intensity, the futuristic splice of swooping symphonics and grimy looped percussion once again sets Stevens in his own orbit.

author: Alexis Petridis
snippet: You emerge from the other side of it glad not just that Stevens continued to make music, but that he chose to follow his muse to such a radical, potentially divisive place.

author: Nathan Westley
snippet: Mixing the traditional with the tools of the present, Stevens has crafted an album that half stays true to his original blue print but one that also offers a series of collisions between drum machines beats and analogue synthesisers.

author: Lauren Murphy
snippet: On The Age of Adz, his idiosyncratic imagination manifests itself in a sprawling collection of songs that mechanically rattle and clank, hiss, shudder, croon, pluck and elegantly sweep their way through 75 minutes.

author: David Smyth
snippet: This daunting opus of 75 experimental minutes makes the florid indulgences of its predecessors sound like The Ramones.

author: James Skinner
snippet: The Age of Adz is not an unqualified success; occasionally it does feel like a little too much, and until the dust has settled it is difficult to say where it will sit in his discography as a whole.

The Age of Adz sonically recalls Enjoy Your Rabbit, where Stevens indulged in more electronics. In other words, neither sounds much like Illinois, with all of its sprightly tunes and exclamation points.

author: Ryan Burleson
snippet: The Age of Adz will divide not just audiences but individuals, making them itch for the comfort of Stevens’ banjo and unflustered, literary demeanor on the one hand, while making them thankful for his honesty and ambition on the other.

author: James Christopher Monger
snippet: It's refreshing to hear him so candid, even if that forthrightness is festooned by enough bells and whistles to wake the dead.

author: Noel Murray
snippet: As an expression of a restless artist trying to stretch his own limits, The Age Of Adz is simultaneously admirable and exhausting.

author: Will Hermes
snippet: It's a semiconcept record, using work by the artist Royal Robertson as a springboard for music that evokes a visionary psyche.

author: Emily Temple
snippet: The Age of Adz builds on his previous dabblings in electronica by integrating the ideas he has clearly been stewing with the aspects of his work so dear to fans.

author: Dom Sinacola
snippet: Where he used be be so proficient at letting us hear the sound of his sad, sad heart, the directionless elliptical clutter that defines The Age of Adz just sounds to me like he's manufacturing an idea of what a sad heart might sound like. What's worse, it sounds self-indulgent.

author: Mikael Wood
snippet: Stevens sated his jam-band jones in a borderline amusing way on August's All Delighted People EP, but here all the engine-revving too often feels lazy, especially considering how vibrantly he embraces the album's fresh musical direction elsewhere.

author: Emily Mackay
snippet: Breathtakingly de trop in almost every regard, ‘The Age Of Adz’ also conjures just enough moments of heart-stopping gorgeousness to foot the bill for its dizzying excesses.
The downside of Stevens' inward journey is that it seems to have eroded his confidence, leading to a maddening tendency to sabotage his best tunes.

author: Anthony Fantano
snippet: Sufjan's latest LP isn't going to go down in history as one of my favorites, but it's not like it's all that bad either.

author: Thomas Britt
snippet: Like its concluding song, The Age of Adz is occasionally transfixing, but overall inconsistent.
“The Age of Adz” pales in comparison to Stevens’ past acoustic masterpieces, but considered on its own terms, the set offers an intriguing take on electro-folk.

author: Alan Shulman
snippet: Sure there’s some nice stuff here and no one ever said Stevens lacked ideas.  But I’m telling you that despite this, The Age of Adz is a major misfire from an artist of uncommon depth and talent.

author: Eric Dennis
snippet: Electronic dabbling frequently has a way of making songs feel distant and hollow, and The Age of Adz is no exception, its thick layers of gadgetry preventing some of its songs from making any type of lyrical connection with the listener.

author: Daniel Paton
snippet: This is an extravagant and undisciplined album that is nearly impossible to digest.

author: Leah Greenblatt
snippet: Hooligans proves that this onetime background player makes a pretty solid first banana.

author: Alex Young
snippet: This fulfilling 10 track album has very few holes, and if this is just a taste of what he has in the vaults for either himself or for other artists, he should be racking up some Grammy’s shortly.

author: Tom Gockelen-Kozlowski
snippet: For his own album, Mars has saved up a bundle of top-drawer melodies, making commercial success all but a certainty. What makes this a really exciting debut, however, is the Kanye West-style genre-bending on Grenade, The Other Side and Our First Time.

author: Will Lavin
snippet: Call it what you want genre-wise, but the bottom line is Bruno Mars is single handedly taking charge of popular music. This album is proof of that.

author: John Aizlewood
snippet: He'll be pilloried but he's doing just fine.

author: Jody Rosen
snippet: Call it bubblegum that eats like a meal.

author: Tim Sendra
snippet: As it is, Doo-Wops & Hooligans is an uneven debut that shows why Mars is likeable and popular, but doesn’t tap into his full potential as a writer or producer.

author: Andy Gill
snippet: An album that seeks too hard to display Mars' multifaceted talents.

author: Tony Clayton-Lea
snippet: Doo-Wops and Hooligans is full of the kind of catchy modern pop that is impossible to dislike or dislodge.

author: Jamie Milton
snippet: One must admit that legitimacy won’t come into the equation of Doo-Wop’s sales, which should be colossal given Mars’ current run of form.

author: Eric Henderson
snippet: Doo-Wops & Hooligans kicks up no fuss, and shortchanges on its promise of both doo-wop and hooliganism.

author: Luke Gibson
snippet: Sure the album has the opportunity to be successful, chameleons routinely do well, but make no mistake about it, Doo Wops & Hooligans is a debut that Bruno Mars will one day could look back on to regret.

author: Alexis Petridis
snippet: The saccharine sound isn't the only problem. The album's awkward title implies that Mars might have an ungainly way with words, and so it proves.

author: Kevin Ritchie
snippet: The word "lightweight" was invented for records like this - ones that nail a commercial formula but are utterly devoid of heat, emotion or compelling personality.
A thrilling comic book of an album, the unpredictable chaos of the early days replaced by the confident swagger of genuine pack leaders.

author: Stephen Thomas Erlewine
snippet: Swapping gothic pomp for metallic power pop, My Chemical Romance may streamline their excesses on Danger Days: The True Lives of the Fabulous Killjoys, the sequel to their 2006 magnum opus The Black Parade, but they by no means excise their indulgences.

author: Brent Koepp
snippet: Danger Days is an homage to fast cars, rock n’ roll and American culture. Half of the album is a blitzkrieg of blazing guitar driven songs that are meant to evoke a sense of speed.

author: Chris Mandle
snippet: An epic, end-of-days drive, taking in '80s synths, mainstream metal and gleaming pop.

author: Megan Ritt
snippet: With the theatrics serving only to enhance the music and the music layered and heightened, Danger Days shows My Chemical Romance to be a band with relevance and staying power, the very definition of evolution.

author: Camilla Pia
snippet: My Chemical Romance’s fourth effort comes as a much needed kick up the jacksy of a genre that’s lost its way of late. Perfect timing, magnificently played.

author: Stephen Ackroyd
snippet: ‘Danger Days’ is a band embracing what they are: the loudest, brightest, most exciting gang from their block.

author: Mark Beaumont
snippet: In essence, MCR are hi-def traditionalists. And Danger Days sees them impressively expand their palate. On initial listens the record seems blown-out like a rusted speaker, as if producer Rob Cavallo has tried to counteract the dour pacing of The Black Parade by fuzzing up Ray Toro’s guitar into a virtual buzz-saw.

Danger Days: The True Lives Of The Fabulous Killjoys, is literally the sonic equivalent of a comic book. Narrated by the self-described “surgeon/proctor/helicopter” Doctor Death-Defying, the 15-track album is as visceral as the superhero wannabes of Kick-Ass and a vast sonic departure for the band.
Most important, it's big fun, whether you buy into the high concept or not.

author: Dave Simpson
snippet: Their fourth album unveils an energetic pop-punk sound – somewhere between Weezer and the Dead Kennedys – although even the psychedelic S/C/A/R/E/C/R/O/W comes with a chorus designed to be sung in stadiums.

author: Mikael Wood
snippet: “Summertime” could pass for something from Coldplay’s last album. “You can run away with me anytime you want,” Way croons, but the guy doesn’t sound in a hurry to go anywhere at all. Viva la Vida Familiar.

author: Chris Coplan
snippet: Danger Days: The True Lives of the Fabulous Killjoys is a shot in the arm via the band’s reimagining of The Stooges and MC5 with their own more mainstream rock tendencies.

author: Melissa Maerz
snippet: Somewhere between the metal- messiah riffs of ” Destroya” and the Red Bull-fueled stomp of “Bulletproof Heart,” Danger Days offers a total rejection of bloated celebrity rock.

author: Max Raymond
snippet: Pop hooks are much more prominent, it’s lyrically less angst-ridden and, in consequence, is more universally accessible.

author: Jon Dolan
snippet: The glammy, gloomy band's 2006 opus The Black Parade was nearly the emo American Idiot. They never took to being that genre's sweethearts, though, so this is a clean break: synthed-up anthems suited for the car, not the coffin.

author: David Edwards
snippet: Gone are the strings, pianos, puppets and stage whispers. MCR have chosen to almost completely eschew their theatrics in place of a record that totters between the gothic punk of their earlier albums and aluminium future-pop, neatly reflecting the album's post-apocalyptic drapes.
Danger Days doesn't sound like the future, but it does sound like the sate of My Chemical Romance's art.

author: Pete Clark
snippet: There is nothing here that will startle the rocking horses, just a bunch of snappy tunes that don't outstay their welcome.
For a band feeling they had painted themselves into a corner, this is them sodding the consequences and stomping their way out.

author: Evan Sawdey
snippet: Danger Days is a far cry from the artistic plane that The Black Parade sits on: it's a decent pop-rock album, a disastrously confused concept album, and even with its marketing, much is left to be desired.

author: Andy Gill
snippet: It's all delivered in a series of shrilly efficient rockers that blend Queen bombast with Green Day bubblegum-punk – a breed of sped-up, over-primped grunge that makes you wonder if Kurt Cobain had lived into his thirties (like MCR), would he have ended up like this? Perhaps not.
The songs are forgotten once they end, and thus so is the record.

author: Lauren Murphy
snippet: As polished as these songs are, they're often too stylised to be emotionally engaging. A progression, perhaps, but at what cost?

author: Jason Heller
snippet: Pretentious yet lunkheaded, the disc’s only charm is its slick, fist-pumping arrogance. On the off chance that anyone needs a reminder of how desperate and irrelevant ’80s hair-metal sounded circa 1990, here it is.

author: Marc Hawthorne
snippet: The 10 songs here don’t collectively match the near-perfection displayed on the band’s debut, but Contra is varied and vivacious enough to make each spin as revelatory as the first time you realized what the band was getting away with and how well it pulled off the feat.

author: Jason Killingsworth
snippet: Contra opener “Horchata” displays a caliber of pop songcraft and melodic intuition that gives The Shins’ James Mercer a run for his harmony, and the feathery lightness of lead singer Ezra Koenig’s voice allows him to indulge fluttering melodies that would sink under the weight of more overbearing pipes.

author: Mike Powell
snippet: Contra works because of its juxtapositions-- of natural sounds to processed ones; of manners to tantrums; of party rhythms to deadpan poetry; of black music to white music.

author: Adam Offitzer
snippet: Those who are truly paying attention to the music will realize that Contra represents a band in complete control, a band that can avoid the sophomore slump by balancing the fine line between taking big risks and playing it safe, a band that, two full albums into its existence, has yet to release a song I do not like.

author: Leah Greenblatt
snippet: The album ... stays largely faithful to the sound they’ve built, with the international-groovy experiments of Paul Simon and Peter Gabriel still clear signposts — Simon’s almost glaringly so.

Vampire Weekend‘s second album, “Contra,” finds the New York-based band pushing its eclectic, intellectual indie rock further using a mash-up of musical genres, clever wordplay and emotional heft. The group even adds some international flair to the new set.

author: Andrew Winistorfer
snippet: As the watery floating of "I Think Ur A Contra" draws the album to a close, it becomes clear that not only did the members of Vampire Weekend succeed in creating an excellent sophomore album; they've managed to survive long enough to outlive their hype and its attendant backlash

author: Helen Brown
snippet: The boys have a delightfully dexterous way with the jambo jangle of those African electric guitars and drums which they flavour eclectically with fashionable retro electropop, woody chamber strings, witty use of vocoders and tinkly sprinklings of harpsichord.

author: Dustin Allen
snippet: Far more than a companion piece of leftover ideas, the album is light, musically savvy and, for the most part, pulls off a thick dose of shamelessly sunny pop across all of its 10 tracks.

author: Will Dana
snippet: If Vampire Weekend was Rushmore, Contra is their Royal Tenenbaums: brainy, confident and generally awesome.

author: Kevin Liedel
snippet: While Koenig rarely shies away from scholastic lyricizing, Contra succeeds apart from its cultural asides and college textbook hat-tips.

author: David Renshaw
snippet: With a mix of frantic and scrappy pop songs alongside blankets of processed peacefulness ‘Contra’ is a fun and always intriguing listen. Vampire Weekend remain the most unlikely crowd pleasers and long may they continue to make the unapproachable not just relevant but entirely necessary.

author: Dave Simpson
snippet: The 10 tracks appeal more with every play: initially sounding a bit like Paul Simon's Graceland being covered by 90s geeks They Might Be Giants, they will probably be among this year's most played and most joyful tunes.

author: Stephen Troussé
snippet: There is very little in the way of rock’n’roll on Contra – and in truth it’s all the better for it. But, bold, beautiful and carefully contrary, it’s an album by a band in complete control.
Contra is the sound of a band driving themselves to very satisfying extremes.

author: Paul Terefenko
snippet: Admirably, Contra isn’t a knee-jerk response to their debut’s detractors.

author: Andy Gill
snippet: Quite literally, a world of fun.

author: Jamie Milton
snippet: This is a momentous return, one that any subsequent decade will look at kindly. It’s yet another record that captures the sound of Brooklyn, but its ideas are wealthy and the band’s urge to try something new evident.

author: Craig McLean
snippet: Contra, like its predecessor, spills over with limber rhythms and percussive bounce, evoking sunny, "exotic" climes far from ice-cool Manhattan.
Compared to the mulch churned out by far too many, Contra will cut through most of the stuff on the radio like sunshine through clouds.

author: Lukas Sherman
snippet: Contra shows Vampire Weekend have more depth and talent than detractors give them credit for and this will be the album-warm, poignant, absurdly catchy-to get you through the dreary winter months.

author: Michael Roffman
snippet: They’re “interesting,” and if this sophomore album is any consideration of their lasting power, let’s just say they bought themselves two more years. Home run, preppies.

author: Michael Skinnider
snippet: Vampire Weekend’s willingness to write an album of exciting new material, rearranging the very core of the sound they’ve come to be known for, will be maddening on first listen for those who loved their debut—but those who stick it out will discover that there’s a more mature, innovative band in its place.

author: Jon Dolan
snippet: The balance of classical, rock, and world instrumentation, cagey rhythms, and stunning prettiness isn’t just architecturally resplendent, it’s reassuringly sweet and strangely moving.

author: Emily Mackay
snippet: With their second album Vampire Weekend have escaped their collegiate niche without sacrificing their true essence.

author: Heather Phares
snippet: With Contra, Vampire Weekend make Auto-Tune and real live guitars, Mexican drinks, Jamaican riffs and Upper West Side strings belong together, and this exciting lack of boundaries offers more possibilities than anyone could have expected.

author: Anthony Lombardi
snippet: Contra may not propose much of a rebuttal to those who thumbed their nose up at the band’s past work, but it’s not difficult to see how it could strengthen their core audience while netting them some new fans at the same time. These aren’t songs that will define boundaries or alter music’s landscape as much as help refine and expand them.

author: John Murphy
snippet: There are some mis-steps – California English employs Auto-Tune about two years too late – but overall this is a fine follow-up to their successful debut.

author: Jim Carroll
snippet: These vamps are far from dead.

author: Dom Gourlay
snippet: No one can surely blame them for sticking to what they do best, particularly when they’re capable of conjuring up tunes as deliriously hook-ridden as the majority of ‘Contra’.
If you liked Vampire Weekend, you will like Contra. It really is that simple.

author: Louise Brailey
snippet: Contra is like the vacant-looking blonde girl in Ralph Lauren that adorns the front cover; interesting on one level but after a while those studied postures, for the first time, seem disappointingly shallow.

author: Rob Hakimian
snippet: Contra doesn’t quite deliver on the promise of their debut but certainly doesn’t write off this still young band who undoubtedly still have plenty to offer.

author: Darren Carle
snippet: Contra doesn’t contain as much pop smarts as their eponymous debut, but then that record was such an explosion of ideas and styles that this seems more considered by comparison.

author: Andrzej Lukowski
snippet: Contra is a solidly entertaining, well-constructed album, and if people take to it, the tendency to mock the band will, I think, fade, simply because it doesn’t have obviously unfashionable moments to feel uneasy about.

author: David Ritter
snippet: Alas, we are weary. None of Contra‘s scant virtues can move us.

author: Grant Purdum
snippet: It’s too bad. I’ll trade a good album for a scathing — or, in this case, indifferent — critique any day.

author: Andy Gill
snippet: It's a breathtaking blizzard of creative imagination.

author: Andy Kellman
snippet: Monáe might not have much appeal beyond musical theater geeks, sci-fi nerds, and those who like their genres crossed-up, but no one can deny that very few are on her creative level.

author: Jim Carroll
snippet: The biggest question of all after this supernova, jawdropping experience is where the hell Monae goes from here.

author: Antonio Rowe
snippet: It's a debut that goes against the grain and is all the better for it.

author: Michael Cragg
snippet: Behold, pop music has found its latest superstar.

author: Justin Jacobs
snippet: Monáe may be an alien or an android, but if this is just the beginning, she may wind up a legend.

author: Simon Vozick-Levinson
snippet: On The ArchAndroid, the real story ... is her arrival as an uncontainable new talent.

author: Genevieve Koski
snippet: Monáe’s inexhaustible swagger and singular style sell both the high-concept theatrics and the schizophrenic sonics.

author: Joe Rivers
snippet: For a first album, The ArchAndroid is astoundingly accomplished.
As it stands, this is the pop album of the year, and it's tough to see how anything is going to beat it.

author: Michael Merline
snippet: The ArchAndroid is ... a career-defining performance and is deserving of all the accolades it and Cindy Mayweather’s hyper-creative brainchild are sure to receive.
The reason “ArchAndroid” is so good is because, from minute one, it is so apparent that its author loves music. And for those of us that love music, that’s a real treat.

author: Barry Walters
snippet: Monáe can really sing; she could follow in Beyoncé’s designer pumps if she wanted, but she’s clearing a new path for black female entertainers.

author: Quentin B. Huff
snippet: Suite II boasts a range of moods and musical styles that could be released on its own. Suite III, while maintaining the quality of the other Suites, wouldn’t be my choice for a standalone release—largely because it’s really strange.

author: Jude Clarke
snippet: One can but marvel at the impressive range, ambition (realised) and detail of this deeply polished, professional yet utterly, brilliantly bonkers album. An album destined, surely, to take its place among the classics of its age.

author: William Grant
snippet: It may not seem restrained, but trust when I say that nothing less than a dissertation or thesis will suffice for such a mind-bogglingly massive album.

author: John Ulmer
snippet: Monáe may be one of the fresh artists to help redefine pop music in the new decade. And even if she doesn’t – even if this album doesn’t sell much and she never quite breaks into the mainstream – at least she’s walking the tightrope and doing her own thing on her own terms.

author: Clayton Purdom
snippet: She is what we say we want. The ArchAndroid is not my favorite album of the year so far, but it is undoubtedly the best.

author: Matthew Perpetua
snippet: Where many concept albums run a high risk of being pompous, cryptic, and self-important, Monáe keeps things playful, lively, and accessible.
Here, at last, is an urban artist with all-unifying appeal.

author: Anthony Fantano
snippet: All animae references aside, this thing is great for dozens of reasons: immediate, conceptual, varied, and engaging.

author: David Smyth
snippet: Impeccable inspirations brought together by an extraordinary new talent.

author: Jason Keller
snippet: Her major label debut is blowing minds the way Outkast once could, with a musical creativity that can’t be denied.
“The ArchAndroid” could be the stuff of stage or screen, 3-D without the annoying glasses.

author: Matthew Cole
snippet: She's turned out a landmark debut that contains a full LP's worth of excellent songs and almost no bad ones, and she's done it entirely on her own highly idiosyncratic terms. And where her ambition just barely gets the better of her abilities, she puts on such a relentlessly entertaining show that you can certainly understand why she thought she could pull the whole thing off.

author: Ally Brown
snippet: There is a masterpiece here, but it’ll take a little skipping to find it.

author: Slava Kuperstein
snippet: ArchAndroid is nothing short of stunning, and should serve as an example to those stuck exploring exhausted archetypes.

author: Hays Davis
snippet: The ArchAngel [sic] succeeds at being an album of strong songs that incorporate the theme, providing a satisfying whole without struggling to wring songs from its story.

author: Emily Mackay
snippet: Her ambition is flabbergasting, let alone that she executes it with bundles of fun and a fizzing personality.

author: Chris Barth
snippet: This album is like nothing you’ve ever heard before and simultaneously like everything you’ve ever heard before.

author: Dan Nishimoto
snippet: In spite of the album’s potential obesity at 18 tracks of wildly different musical ideas, the three keep the weight off by welcoming coherence and by evenly spreading out their interests.

author: Jody Rosen
snippet: Her full-length debut ... is so ambitious, so freighted with sounds and ideas and allusions, it threatens at times to sink under its own weight.

author: Nick Freed
snippet: Monáe is able to accomplish something rarely seen in pop music: an epic album that stretches across multiple genres while still holding the majority of the listener’s attention with catchy hooks and beats.
A case of bombastic ambition only occasionally matched by musical nous.
Just Got Back From the Discomfort is a life changing record.

Linkin Park has certainly tinkered with its sound during the course of its previous three albums. But on its latest release, "A Thousand Suns," the six-piece rock act truly breaks the habit of everything we've heard from it before.
Linkin Park's fourth album plots a remarkable course. It is, in fact, nothing less than the sound of their hybrid theory soaring to its logical conclusion.

author: Leah Greenblatt
snippet: On A Thousand Suns at times the band’s odd mélange of industrial grind, hip-hop swagger, and teenage-wasteland angst feels jarring — but that should matter little to the kids who clamor for their headphone catharses.

author: Chris Colgan
snippet: This is Linkin Park's attempt at creating their own version of Dark Side of the Moon...and, shockingly, it works!

author: Stephen Thomas Erlewine
snippet: Continuing their slow crawl toward middle age, Linkin Park opt for moody over metallic on A Thousand Suns, their fifth album. A clear continuation of 2007’s Minutes to Midnight, A Thousand Suns also trades aggression for contemplation, burying the guitars under washes of chilly synthesizers.

author: Alex Young
snippet: A Thousand Suns might be a drastic shift in sound for LP, but the fans and the haters alike should be impressed. This is a solid record that hits the mark on nearly every possible level allotted it.

A Thousand Suns isn’t quite the return to the magic of debut album Hybrid Theory, as it has been billed in some quarters, but neither is it a straight re-enactment of the turgid attempt at a stadium-filler that was 2007’s Minutes to Midnight.

author: Mikael Wood
snippet: Linkin Park’s fourth studio album (and second collaboration with producer Rick Rubin) contains plenty of aggressively arty material that might surprise fans of the megapopular rap-rock outfit

author: Jody Rosen
snippet: It's the sound of Linkin Park feeling their way toward a new identity, but their skill for melody is obvious.

author: Emma Johnston
snippet: Every bit as self-important and po-faced as you’d imagine.

author: Chris Martins
snippet: The Fall at first listen seems more interesting as a concept than as music. Still, there are plenty of rough-cut pop gems.

author: John Aizlewood
snippet: The Fall suggests it's wise not to underestimate Damon Albarn's restless creativity.

author: Gareth James
snippet: A delicate beauty.

author: Chris Mandle
snippet: Damon ditches the celeb mates and takes up the iPad for his best cartoon hip-hop album to date.

author: Chris Trout
snippet: Genius, as you know, is all about the detail. The backing vocal on ‘Revolving Doors’ – if you’re still struggling with the 'song' thing, this and ‘Amarillo’ offer consolation in the form of two of Albarn’s loveliest unfinished melodies.

author: Jon Dolan
snippet: Albarn isn’t trying to say much, but The Fall is pretty consistent, from the country-radio sampling dub of “The Parish of Space Dust” to the Rust Belt planet-rock of “Detroit.”

author: Alex Thornton
snippet: While it is impressive how much Albarn squeezes out of a piece of equipment that most would assume isn’t up for the task, this is ultimately a tour-bus album—several songs are even named after the cities in which they were likely conceived.

author: Keith Pishnery
snippet: Scaling back to just an iPad and a few instruments for The Fall is somewhat surprising, and has resulted in a quieter, more singer-songwriter type of album.

author: Christian Cottingham
snippet: An electronic album that manages to sound intimate, late-summer warmth turning to autumnal melancholy, and a cartoon band that suddenly seems a little fragile.

author: Conrad Amenta
snippet: The Fall is worth spending time with, not only for the quality of some of its material, but also for what it exposes of Albarn’s careful conception of what this band should be.

author: Brad Wete
snippet: There are a few moments of brilliance, like Bobby Womack’s spirited crooning on ”Bobby in Phoenix.” Hopefully that energy will spill into their next effort — in a studio.

author: Erik Burg
snippet: The strange, yet awfully satisfying, collection of tracks certainly won’t attract new listeners to the Gorillaz catalogue, but synth-infused pop tracks like “Revolving Door” or “Hillbilly Man” will appease most listeners.

author: Alexis Petridis
snippet: Gorillaz' latest is a low-key set made on an iPad on tour. It has a few great flashes.

author: Jim Carroll
snippet: The Fall is best viewed as Damon Albarn's on-the-road notebook rather than a fully fledged Gorillaz affair.
Set free from the unwieldy set of expectations that come with a stellar cast of guest stars, ‘The Fall’ could have been Albarn’s undiluted first-person perspective of what a Gorillaz album should be.
It's a sequel of sorts to Democrazy, but sounds infinitely more accomplished--undoubtedly part of the technological point that he's making here.

author: Huw Jones
snippet: The Fall is a love letter to—and a journey into—the heart of America.

author: Dylan Nelson
snippet: In form as well as content, The Fall is more like a pet project than a full-fledged release.

author: Stephen Thomas Erlewine
snippet: The Fall winds up a little ephemeral, its pleasures as fleeting as the scenery passing outside the windows of a tour bus.

author: Joe Marvilli
snippet: There are a lot of innovative ideas, some strong moments, but also a good amount of filler. If you give it a spin, though, you’ll probably find some hidden treasures in these songs as well.

author: Nathan Kamal
snippet: For all its highlights, The Fall ultimately feels slight.

author: Stephen Deusner
snippet: The Fall may be the most earthbound Gorillaz album yet-- and at times, therefore, the most banal.

author: Anthony Fantano
snippet: On this followup to Plastic Beach, Gorillaz bring together some pretty rough ideas and simple demos. Given, the sounds here are much better than what most people can create on a MacBook--never mind an iPad.

author: Jessica Misener
snippet: The sluggish vibe on The Fall was obviously part of Albarn’s intention in creating a meandering sonic travelogue, but you end up wishing he’d pressed the gas pedal a little harder.
Gorillas are a threatened species. Gorillaz might be joining them at this rate.

author: Andy Gill
snippet: As you'd expect, it relies heavily on programmed beats of spare simplicity, and layered dubstep synth riffs over which Albarn sketches his impressions of life on the road.

author: Anthony Fantano
snippet: This album is the most abusive thing I've heard all year. It's pure, unadulterated testosterone. It's the kinda stuff that makes a perfect soundtrack to taking your shirt off and punching anything and everything withing arm's length.

author: Eduardo Rivadavia
snippet: Recorded over two days and mixed by Converge man Kurt Ballou, Unsilent Death is basically too heavy for punk, too fast for hardcore, too nimble for grindcore, and certainly too ADD-concise for death metal.

author: Emily Mackay
snippet: Frankly, with a debut this astonishing, we think the time for Marina to stop worrying is here.

author: Gareth O'Malley
snippet: Remarkably consistent, and at times quite affecting, this album lives up to all the hype. However Marina may feel about where she is now, we wouldn’t have it any other way.

author: Lindsey Fortier
snippet: On her debut album, "The Family Jewels," Diamandis backs up her bark with a promising bite.

author: Pete Clark
snippet: This is straightforward fun music, carefully crafted and delivered with verve and panache.

author: Brian Boyd
snippet: Diamandis reveals such a playful, interesting approach to song structure that you can only view this album as the opening chapter in a very, very promising career.

author: Matthew Chisling
snippet: Diamandis earns a large number of brownie points for owning a unified sound on her album that invests itself in every track, sparing no album cut for the sake of quantity over quality.
Her debut skips frrom glam-disco and bubblegum punk, to quavering piano laments and cabaret ditties. All the while, her imaginative reach is complemented by a winning pop savviness.

author: Neil McCormick
snippet: Her arch, clever debut may be too spiky and brash to be really lovable, but, if Marina has her way, you’ll probably find yourself singing along whether you like it or not.

author: Rhian Daly
snippet: Ellie Goulding may have beaten her to the early accolades of 2010 but with The Family Jewels, Marina has produced a debut album so striking and honest it makes Lights look like second rate sixth form musings in comparison.

There is a savvy depth evident throughout ‘The Family Jewels’ which simply cannot be ignored; fun, serious, poppy and unorthodox, it is an album full of contradictions, but one which rarely fails to entertain.

author: John Murphy
snippet: The Family Jewels isn’t the classic debut album that her early singles suggested was on the way, but there’s enough promise here to carry her through the hype.

author: Camilla Pia
snippet: The record is hugely entertaining; a joyful romp through quirky pop-ville in fact. She’s no Kate Bush, who she’s relentlessly compared to, but then really, who is?

author: Barry Walters
snippet: Ravishing yet famished for attention, this overachiever would be bloody irritating if she didn’t demonstrate a savvy command of pop hooks.

author: Gareth James
snippet: Marina describes the album as “intricately produced” and that’s where the problem lies. Such attention to detail leaves some of the songs feeling pretty sterile and, as a result, it’s a frustrating listen.

author: Alexis Petridis
snippet: There's no doubting that Marina Diamandis can write great pop songs. It's the rest of the package that's the problem.
A quirky, theatrical record that's full of pomp and self-importance, The Family Jewels is never less than exciting, but it does try a little too hate to be zany.

author: Joe Copplestone
snippet: Although there is definitely musical colour here, Marina’s vocal delivery and attitude has a tendency to overshadow the music, which is often melodically inventive, but we are rarely given the chance to realise this.

author: Sean O'Neal
snippet: Hailing from the same school of self-aware artifice as Lady Gaga and Little Boots, Marina Diamandis’ debut as Marina And The Diamonds benefits—and suffers—from the same irony-laden emptiness.

author: Mary Bellamy
snippet: The Family Jewels seems to be symptomatic of a broader trend at the moment to demand our female artists be both credible and commercial at the expense of achieving anything great in either camp.
All round it makes for a slightly uncomfortable listen.

author: Joe Rivers
snippet: Unfortunately, her constant insistence on being so ham-fistedly quirky and zany soon becomes wearing, and simultaneously rescues and spoils the whole album.

author: Andy Gill
snippet: It's the relentless attention-seeking of her music that's most enervating, however, its infantile aspects exacerbated by Marina's high-register vocal tic in "I Am Not a Robot" and her whistling in "Mowgli's Road", both exercises in the kind of jolly, enthusiastic tedium favoured by stage-school musicals.

author: Leah Greenblatt
snippet: At times the album's lurid sexuality can feel forced: kink as oversold diva commodity. What Loud showcases best, though, is a star undefeated by her worst circumstances — and finding redemption in exactly the kind of pop nirvana that made her famous in the first place.

author: Ryan Burleson
snippet: If it weren’t for the grab bag feel it gives off in small measure, Loud would rival Good Girl Gone Bad without much argument from anyone. It’s a dynamic R&B and dance-pop record that feels neither tenuous nor overwrought, striking about as clever a balance as one can strike in today’s distracted music economy.

author: Stacey Anderson
snippet: This is a more mature nod to the bubbly pop that established her fame. And it’s a statement from a woman who’s come into her own, and who won’t be going anywhere that isn’t worth her while. We could all do worse than to follow her lead.

author: Ryan Dombal
snippet: After responding to staggering emotional and physical trauma with the melodramatic Rated R, Rihanna returns to making effervescent pop.
Whereas many of her prior ambitions may have felt impulsive, Loud fuses them together so that they all make sense.

author: Kathy Iandoli
snippet: Loud is perhaps the work that will put her back on the fast track, and since Rihanna is officially throwing up the Roc (another proud Roc Nation signee), perhaps she’ll make the official transition from Princess to Queen the next time around.

author: Chris Mandle
snippet: Overly tiresome fetish-flirting can't drag the brilliantly adventurous and masterfully measured pop queen down.

author: Genevieve Koski
snippet: Nothing here reaches the heights of her mega-hit “Umbrella”—though “Only Girl (In The World)” comes close—but Rihanna delivers every song like it’s a smash hit in the making.

author: Peter Tabakis
snippet: It’s only been three years since Rihanna released the incredible pop anthem “Umbrella,” but the artistic distance between then and now seems vast.

author: Genice Phillips
snippet: There is a clear aspiration for this album to be ubiquitous, and well, overbearing with tunes.  Rather than follow the typical pop formula, Rihanna gives an album specifically catered to where she is now with her career, music, and life.  And blaring seems to be the point.

author: Sean Thomas
snippet: At times brilliant, at others unlike anyone else out there and occasionally frankly a bit rubbish.

author: Rick Pearson
snippet: This is the stuff of one-night stands rather than long-term romances.

author: Will Lavin
snippet: It’s enough to warm up this extremely cold winter season.

author: Bernadette McNulty
snippet: Rihanna returns to sunny sassy tunes with 'Loud'.

author: Andy Gill
snippet: Perhaps trying to distance it from the darker world of sexual violence that dominated Rated R, Rihanna has described Loud as "really sassy and flirty", though listening to tracks like the masochist drama "Love the Way You Lie" and the bluntly-titled "S&M", this seems somewhat disingenuous.

author: Sal Cinquemani
snippet: Like Janet's last hit album, Loud is a decided step away from its über-personal, melodrama-drenched predecessor.

author: Melissa Maerz
snippet: Maybe the good girl gone bad is getting better?

author: Andy Kellman
snippet: There’s just enough quality content to maintain her visibility.

author: jon Falcone
snippet: Ultimately Loud is a typical big budget pop album; nothing to sing about, but worth a dance.

author: Andrew Murfett
snippet: Determinedly upbeat it may be, but Loud is a disappointing step backwards for RiRi.

author: David Amidon
snippet: At a brief 47 minutes ... it's hard to see Rihanna fans walking away from Loud thinking she's anything other than the coolest girl in her field.

author: Lukas Sherman
snippet: Despite what she’s tried to convince us with her last few albums, that she’s a Good Girl Gone Bad, that she’s Rated R, that she’s Loud, she mostly just seems like an attractive, but not particularly adventurous or inspired pop star.

author: Kevin Ritchie
snippet: The record's best moments aim low rather than loud, with spacious, skittery beats that let loose Rihanna's Caribbean cadence.

author: Tim Lee
snippet: It’s a bold, dramatic, more than a little screwed-up and stunningly exciting statement. In short, it’s an album worth not having to wait an extra 30 days to hear. Or read about.

author: Mike Hughes
snippet: As a whole this record is less jagged than some of the older tracks, more consistent in it's quality but surprising in its variety, is that a bad thing? Listening again, side by side, all I can say for certain is that I don't know the new ones so well yet. Given the compulsive nature of what they've turned out this time round, that is bound to change anyway.
Electronic duo Crystal Castles generally operates in two distinct modes.

author: Ian Cohen
snippet: Crystal Castles return with a second self-titled album, embracing a more direct pop sound while retaining the sharp edges that made their debut so compelling.
The group’s bleak, sinister quality has always been one of its best assets, and in humanizing themselves, even in the record’s shinier latter half, the musicians take on a slightly stronger shadow.

author: Daniel Koren
snippet: Crystal Castles show a lot of growth on this album; there’s less distortion and more fluid, coherent melodies.

author: Rick Pearson
snippet: It's hard work, granted, but there's gold here if you're willing to dig.

author: Jason Morton
snippet: Dropping a lot of the 8-bit influence from their shtick and integrating an almost choral sound to certain cuts ... Crystal Castles might just have found a way to elude their haters and continue on making dance music that many people would be piss scared to dance to.

author: Joshua Errett
snippet: The Toronto duo returns with an insanely great new album.

author: Mosi Reeves
snippet: By dispensing with empty bravado, Crystal Castles reveal a depressive, darkwave charisma.

author: Nick Hanover
snippet: The biggest difference is that this time around, the approach somehow seems less schizophrenic and more like natural changes in mood than chaotic shifts- Crystal Castles are still clearly testing their audience’s patience and boundaries, but it would appear to be for some higher purpose now.

author: Heather Phares
snippet: The second Crystal Castles may not be as immediate as their debut, but it shows that the band has more to offer than just a distinctive -- and confining -- sound.

author: Mehan Jayasuriya
snippet: They’ve made a bigger, denser, more accessible record but in so doing, have not lost sight of their strengths—rather, those strengths now shine through even more clearly.

author: Justin Jacobs
snippet: CC 2 is a great entry point to the chemical burn of electronic music’s outer fringe.

author: Anthony Fantano
snippet: Crystal Castles latest album isn't exactly a reinvention of the electronic duo. I can't say they've gone v2.0 on us. Maybe it's more like a v1.4. Many of the tracks sound similar to those on the first album, but the ones that don't are more than interesting.

author: Andrew Murfett
snippet: The noise that the duo manufactures together combines the muscle of a live, dirty rock band with the hedonism - and bleeps - of a gothic rave party. More often than not, it's a thrilling combination.

author: Eric Henderson
snippet: They’ve moved on from huffing paint thinner to farting in your mouth while you are sleeping. The differences are subtle, but the key advance made is one of generosity.

author: Noah Barron
snippet: Surprisingly, it's actually super good in a sort of forgettable way.

author: James Hampson
snippet: Crystal Castles seem to really have a sense of progression with this.

author: Emily Mackay
snippet: Radio playlisted, exploring their spiritual side – have the digipunk pinups gone soft? No fear...

author: Jay Hill
snippet: Affectionately dubbed II by music writers, Crystal Castles’ second eponymous album revisits much of the same territory explored on their self-titled debut.

author: Michael Hann
snippet: The opening pairing of their second album suggests they mean to continue as they began, as the harshness of Fainting Spells gives way to Celestica, one of those swooning, melancholy European faux-classical melodies the Pet Shop Boys do so well.

author: Jim Carroll
snippet: There were hints the first time around that Ethan Kath and Alice Glass could overcome their collective tantrums, and the new record’s magnificent scope is a giant stride in the right direction. True, Crystal Castles still rely on edgy glitches and white noise figments, but these are now part of the texture rather than the only component.

author: Andrzej Lukowski
snippet: It’s pretty good, but as with any punks gone pro, Crystal Castles have lost something – attitude, fire, aggression, danger; the usual stuff.

author: Alex Young
snippet: While some tracks muddle the four-beat pop standard through radical slow-downs and speed-ups and other sporadic behavior, other parts of Crystal Castles (II) are dulling and fail to inspire much.

author: Stuart Stubbs
snippet: A second album that impressively lacks progression and winds up sounding like a CDR of the record you’ve had for two years already.

author: Jessica Faulds
snippet: Crystal Castles is the emperor’s new house band. They’re riding on enthusiasm and dance-cave savagery temperamental fits. Which is fine, but hopefully next time, they’ll make an album that holds together better, and doesn’t leave them naked.

author: Andrew Baer
snippet: Halcyon Digest goes by like a breeze, and when it’s finished there’s nothing better to do than play it again.

author: Heather Phares
snippet: It’s not as immediate as previous Deerhunter albums, but Halcyon Digest has an appeal all its own: It’s as difficult to grasp -- and as hard to shake -- as a memory lingering at the back of your brain.

author: Charlie Mcdonald
snippet: There’s nothing ground breaking in it’s execution or design, but this is a band understanding where they want to be. It has it’s faults, but every truly great album does.

author: Marc Hogan
snippet: Halcyon Digest is a record about the joy of music discovery, the thrill of listening for the first time to a potential future favorite, and that sense of boundless possibility when you're still innocent of indie-mainstream politics and your personal canon is far from set.

author: Steven Hyden
snippet: On Halcyon Digest, Cox’s two halves finally meet in the middle on a collection of grabby pop songs sung by a witty weirdo with newly discovered sex appeal.

author: Simon Jay Catling
snippet: A sublime album.

author: Gareth O'Malley
snippet: It’s one of those albums that, when it clicks, hits the listener like a ton of bricks.

author: Anthony Fantano
snippet: More albums like this, and Deerhunter will have quite the legacy going for them in 10 years.
As they've made it to their fourth album, they've quickly become one of indie's most reliable bands, each new album bringing the promise of some of the year's best music.

author: Richard Trapunski
snippet: With every album, Deerhunter strip away more layers of textural ambience and reveal what some fans knew all along: that they're a pop band.
With Halycon Digest, Deerhunter are dealing in an altogether different kind of tension.

author: Jake Kennedy
snippet: Sure, there are quiet moments – the “recorded live” Basement Scene apes the Velvets a little too much – but this is goodtime music with a hell of a lot of thought behind it.
A rather lovely record ... Fully audible at last, Cox's downcast lyrics invest these hazy tunes with gripping poignancy.
Deerhunter might be fascinated by the vanishing tricks people play, but Halcyon Digest is a thing of unmistakable substance.

author: Michael Hann
snippet: Deerhunter aren't just revivalists ... in the main this is timeless music, seemingly made with the conviction that loveliness will always be lovely.
Having defined its gauzy sound on previous albums, “Halcyon Digest” Deerhunter finds the group expanding it with knockout results.

author: Robert Ham
snippet: The gauziness is thicker, but the pop melodies and dreamy vocals of leader Bradford Cox still float on the surface, leaving a gorgeous, rainbow-colored sheen in their wake.

author: Matthew Cole
snippet: Halcyon Digest’s finest moment suggests that Deerhunter will get by just fine without the histrionics.

author: PJ Meiklem
snippet: Opener Earthquake is anything but: a soft, reassuring, laidback swirl. Stand out track Desire Lines adds a bit of tempo to a mix that subtly works its way into your head.

author: Matt Popkin
snippet: While most of the songs on the album are propelled forward by primal stomp-clap rhythms, the four-piece band from Atlanta, Georgia still manages to create its share of musical variation.

“Halcyon Digest” has made me a believer. It’s fresh, captivating, and one of the most immersive experiences of the year. Deerhunter have made a very honest album that encourages the listener to dig deeper and discover something new around every corner. And with all reservations gone, I wholly urge you to do so.

author: Jim Scott
snippet: On their fourth record, Deerhunter has settled into a comfortable, yet still thrilling, space.

author: Alan Baban
snippet: Halcyon Digest is bliss, it is Deerhunter’s best album to date—their first not to belie some raptorial need to plum my ears with mooching loudness.

author: Ryan Burleson
snippet: Deerhunter is one of the most interesting bands making music today, a loose, confident and well-versed unit that will only get better with time.

Like frontman Bradford Cox’s solo records as Atlas Sound, Halcyon Digest exists mainly as another iteration of his shifting id, deeply plumbing memories real and imagined with a sound by turns spare and sumptuous.

author: Rebecca Schiller
snippet: For all its occasional lack of bite and drama, ‘Halcyon Digest’’s tender, transgressive pop proves a fine and focused addition to a uniquely haunting body of work.

author: Andrew Burgess
snippet: Halcyon Digest is a triumph of multilayered nuance, and repeated listens reveal its genius buried just beyond the obvious.
As difficult as it might be to find fresh plaudits with which to laud Deerhunter, they continue to deserve every single redundant bit of acclaim.

author: Andrzej Lukowski
snippet: Yet I think conversely it’s Cox’s inability to totally connect to an audience that makes him such a spectacularly special songwriter.

author: Kyle Wall
snippet: This Digest isn’t particularly cohesive and a few too many loose ends are left untied, but it wouldn’t be a shock to believe that’s how Cox likes it. Though it’s been said before, he certainly has a masterpiece or two ahead of him – and from the sounds of it, it’s coming sooner rather than later.

author: Jody Rosen
snippet: The third album by Atlanta's kings of "ambient punk" is a beautiful bummer.

author: Raymond Cummings
snippet: Deerhunter has graduated, by degrees, from conjuring moods to writing proper songs, and fourth album Halcyon Digest finds Bradford Cox and company strip-mining new aural territory and toeing the line between structure and abstraction.

author: Tom Pinnock
snippet: It’s just a shame that on around half of ‘Halcyon Digest’ they’ve replaced the Deerhunter ’sound’ with something less inspired.

author: Matthew Fiander
snippet: Halcyon Digest is, to my mind, the best we’ve seen from Deerhunter, and a hint that their best is still to come.

author: Edgar Smith
snippet: The most well-crafted and terrifying album I’ve heard this year.

author: Jason Heller
snippet: The full-length is the group’s first since 1996, and although singer-keyboardist Jarboe is absent, Gira and longtime guitarist Norman Westberg have sired a leviathan of an album.

author: Sean Caldwell
snippet: Part mind numbing, part infuriating, part stimulating and always worth discussion, Swans remain a significant force in underground and independent music and this new album sees the No Wave merge with the compositionally avant-garde.

author: David Morris
snippet: My Father Will Guide Me Up a Rope To the Sky, from the title’s evocation of righteous death on down to its suffusion with keening strings and other touches of sonic Americana, is an attempt to come to terms with the dark heart of history, with that ultimate question: if we are born into crime and monstrous darkness, how do we become more than that past?

author: Corey Beasley
snippet: Whatever the case, we finally have My Father Will Guide Me Up a Rope to the Sky to judge, and—whatever baggage it might carry—what a gift it turns out to be.

author: Rebecca Schiller
snippet: It's been a 14 year wait, but Swans unleash a chaotic melee of noise as beautiful as it is ferocious.

author: Robin Jahdi
snippet: At all points it sounds exactly like Michael Gira, and just like Swans, but never sounds like any already-existing Swans record. Comebacks shouldn’t be this good, this confident. They certainly never sound this fresh.

author: Matthew Olmos
snippet: What My Father does is not so much mark a return but a synthesis of previous Swans incarnations, a sort of Voltron album for the venerable experimental band.

author: Joel Elliott
snippet: If My Father doesn’t quite achieve the perfection (what else can you call it?) of their last albums, it nevertheless takes up where they left off.

author: Noel Gardner
snippet: Yet My Father Will Guide Me Up A Rope To The Sky sounds more like the essence of Michael Gira than the Angels Of Light ever did, and ought to also serve as another broadside to the idea of reformations being inherently grubby and uncreative ventures.

author: Tommy Udo
snippet: A geography-teacher style mark out of 10 or an Argos catalogue-length assessment are both insufficient to convey the complexity and brooding majesty of this work.
Thirteen years after they retired Swans return with thunderous tour de force.
Dig deeper, though, and what we have here is a record more in line with the excellent, vengeful Americana of frontman Michael Gira's latter-day Angels Of Light fare.

author: Jesse Cataldo
snippet: Darkness is still in great supply throughout these eight long songs.
Swans return, bigger and more frightening than ever.

author: Spencer Kornhaber
snippet: Recognizable shapes of jazz and post-rock often accompany Gira’s baritone croon, but they’re always delivered between passages of fastidiously crafted clamor that’s as cauterizing as ever.

author: Thom Jurek
snippet: My Father Will Guide Me Up a Rope to the Sky is a mercilessly intense and beautiful record that only Swans could pull off, and that no matter who plays in the band, Gira was and is Swans: their sound, their musical and poetic vision, their heartbeat.

author: Jess Harvell
snippet: This album is the antithesis of 2010's gooey let's-all-be-friends chillwave fun.

author: Matthew Fiander
snippet: This music, though, it’s almost anti-music in spots. In a good way. It strips away all the comforting structures we know and leaves us awash in harsh emotion.

author: Jory Spadea
snippet: Doesn’t matter that he’s 56 years old, Gira hasn’t lost his ingenious Sidam Touch. Just as always, he spins arbitrary styles and instrumentation into casual entropy, Father being the optimistic example that, yes, bands can reconvene and as record as if they never broke up.

author: Jude Clarke
snippet: This is certainly, then, not an album to be taken lightly. Whilst this may be its chief difficulty, and one that will undoubtedly deter and daunt some listeners, it is nevertheless good to have a band and an artist with this darkly poetic a vision back recording and performing once again.

author: Paul Neeson
snippet: In the context of Swans latter output, My Father… is typically challenging, with the lead-heavy opener No Words/No Thoughts treading over nine minutes of distorted abstraction; mixing imperial, instrumental ascents with Gira’s shadowed vocals. It’s a polarizing gambit, and a sure sign that Swans have returned with an uncompromising (and nihilistic) intent.

author: Jason Keller
snippet: Swans, who emerged from the same noise-filled no wave scene in New York's early 80s as Thurston Moore, had a rotating cast of nasty-tempered psychotic rockers, with multi-instrumentalist Michael Gira at its centre. Listening to Swans' new album, the first in 14 years, you get the sense that some of that malevolence remains.

author: Anthony Fantano
snippet: I think with another LP, it's the rockier moments that will come off stronger than the acoustic ones. Because as of this point, the latter is the more memorable on this LP.
It's an album that draws on blues and gospel alongside atmospheric art-rock to end up somewhere intriguing, unnerving and frequently overwhelming.
My Father Will Guide Me Up a Rope to the Sky isn't all cranium-crushing bleakness, just mostly.

author: Leah Greenblatt
snippet: Robyn continues to languish in the cult-act remainder bin, but these 15 excellently curated tracks deserve to change that.

author: Heather Phares
snippet: Overall ... Body Talk is more focused than Robyn, and just as bold in the intimacy it creates with listeners.

author: Genevieve Koski
snippet: Over the course of Body Talk, Robyn has proved that there’s real emotion to be found among the ones and zeros of electronic music, and Pt 3. is the culmination of that outlook: euphoric, personal, and inspirational to the last beat.

author: jon Falcone
snippet: To say this has been Robyn’s year is an understatement.

author: Peter Tabakis
snippet: No matter how you consume it, Body Talk matches Robyn's brilliance, and further shows that no one puts music to a beat as marvelously as Robyn Carlsson.

author: Marc Hogan
snippet: With Body Talk, Robyn ups the ante for pop stars across the radio dial and raises her own chances of appearing on yours.

author: Kevin Ritchie
snippet: Robyn takes a range of styles from dancehall and rap to house and disco and melds them with her big pop sound featuring four-to-the-floor beats and thoughtful, unsentimental lyrics about love and loneliness.

author: Maddy Costa
snippet: You could argue that Robyn does sexy, bolshy, catchy pop so effortlessly... that Body Talk should have been edited into a straightforward killer pop album.

author: airgordon
snippet: Body Talk concludes a triptych of highly enjoyable pop albums. Let’s hope we don’t have to wait another five years for the next batch.

author: Jonathan Keefe
snippet: Robyn’s Body Talk is one of the year’s finest, most progressive pop albums, but it’s also something of a minor letdown as a standalone project.

author: Christian Hoard
snippet: This disc cherry-picks from two previous Body Talk EPs while tossing in five new tracks. It all adds up to the best dance-pop album of 2010.

author: Nia Thomas
snippet: One of the best albums released this year.

author: Rick Pearson
snippet: Proof that it's possible to have both quantity and quality.

author: Arika Dean
snippet: Body Talk is a cornucopia of cherry-picked songs from her three-part mini-album series this year, and the compilation approach really comes through: it’s full of varied electropop production that suffers from a lack of cohesiveness.

author: Nathan Kamal
snippet: Body Talk is a fine combination of some of her most pop elements, but it’s not her defining statement yet.
Robyn has what it takes to be a real force and with this display of innovation and execution, the only question left is to wonder when the rest of the world will catch on.

author: Chris Todd
snippet: While Robyn shows that her body can certainly do the talking, when it comes to walking the walk she’s prone to stumbling in directions she should avoid.

author: Evan Sawdey
snippet: It’s just a shame that while Body Talk contains some of the most extraordinary pop music to be released all year, its impact is weakened by a few poor song inclusions and a difficult track listing .

author: Paul Davey
snippet: Taken as a whole however, Body Talk suffers from the same patchiness that pervades Robyn’s previous releases.

author: Spencer Kornhaber
snippet: Conspiracy-addled claustrophobic noises swath the hooks throughout, revealing the intoxicating assuredness of a star who sought the spotlight in order to barrage it with glitter and shrapnel.
M.I.A. delivers her most cohesive and passionate album yet.

author: Gideon Brody
snippet: Made during pregnancy and early motherhood, /\/\ /\ Y /\ - as odd as it is to say - is, occasionally, hormonally imbalanced. There's a real sense of vulnerability and affection, amid the racket.

author: Matthew Bennett
snippet: Maya’s trajectory and output is now utterly unique
As with M.I.A.'s previous offerings, the beats, hooks and pervading general noise is what keeps the momentum up throughout the mishmash of electro-pop and severely distorted dance hall.

author: Charles Aaron
snippet: Exploring the mindset of impulsive youth caught up in Islamic terrorism ... is a head-spinning project. But M.I.A. embraces it fearlessly, even mischievously.

author: Daniel Willis
snippet: Through sheer originality, personality and success, M.I.A. persuades us there is a life for individuals outside of the media and when it is as vibrant and exhilarating as this it is certainly a cause for celebration.

author: Chris Barth
snippet: Let’s stop applying our external judgments and just listen to this album for what it is – a self-indulgent, confused piece of art that just happens to be pretty damn good.

author: Rob Sheffield
snippet: From the sound of Maya, she's capable of anything - except being dull.

author: Danielle Sills
snippet: M.I.A. stays true to her genre-hopping ways, changing styles drastically between songs ... Listening to /\/\ /\ Y /\, we travel around the world and back, crossing time periods, cultures, and lifestyles.

author: Andy Gill
snippet: Maya sounds like a party for Cabaret Voltaire's stroppy teen daughter.
If you’ve been looking for a quick-acting and powerful antidote to Lady Gaga, you’ve found it here – on repeat prescription.

author: James Skinner
snippet: “I got something to say” she hollers in ‘Born Free’. As long as her music remains as bold, inventive and occasionally thrilling as it is here, long may that continue.

author: James Edmund Porter
snippet: For someone as outspoken and controversial as Arulpragasam, it’s second nature for us critics to scrutinize every tweet, move, outburst, and interview, weighing each word and action by the standards of her political past. For the sake of her music, however, it’s probably best to let Maya be Maya, or even /\/\ /\ Y /\.

author: Michael Saba
snippet: Like the rebels she so often lionizes, Arulpragasam is conducting hit-and-run warfare on modern pop, snatching a hook here, a melody there, and then falling back to reshape these pilfered rhythms into unfettered anti-establishment anthems.

author: Chris Middleman
snippet: Written and recorded at her home, M.I.A.’s third full-length is less of a percussive chase through some imagined third world landscape and more of a carefully crafted, super-charged collection of pop songs centering on the things she finds most important that create dense atmospheres, rather than overwhelm the senses.

author: Kathy Iandoli
snippet: M.I.A. is our present day riot grrrl – not as vocally adept as other female artists, but painting pictures with her words that speak on a higher plane.

author: Emily Mackay
snippet: It may not quite be the equal of past glories, but it is further proof that Miss Arulpragasam is one of our most fascinating stars

author: Joe Rivers
snippet: /\/\/\Y/\ is a good album by anyone’s standards. However, it’s the fact we’re judging it against M.I.A.’s (granted, incredibly high) standards that it’s so frustrating, and we all know she can do better.

author: Justin Toland
snippet: M.I.A. remains one of the most exciting and challenging figures in the pop mainstream; let’s hope this unconvincing first attempt to respond to the demands of the mass market is a blip rather than the start of a nose dive.

author: Alexis Petridis
snippet: "You can make a killing, but don't forget the feeling," she offers, advice you can't help but wish she'd followed more closely during Maya's making.

author: Ally Brown
snippet: Everything's gone smoothly for M.I.A. up 'til now, but success is a double-edged sword. She's been forced to adjust for third album "MAYA" – also known as '/\/\/\Y/\' – and the result isn't as compelling as either of her first two records

author: Jesse Cataldo
snippet: For M.I.A., Maya feels like a crossed border.

author: Andy Kellman
snippet: Clever-clever wordplay, assaultive sound effects, and ear-fatiguing beats are amplified at the expense of singalong hooks and swinging, energizing rhythms.

author: Mehan Jayasuriya
snippet: That /\/\/\Y/\ lacks the focus and confidence of M.I.A.‘s previous albums is disappointing; that it finds Maya content to follow, rather than lead, is indefensible.

author: Anthony Fantano
snippet: /\/\ /\ Y /\ causes as much racket as its predecessors, but the shroud of noise doesn't cover the plain song structures.

author: Matthew Perpetua
snippet: There are moments of interesting noise, but in the absence of appealing grooves or memorable hooks, it barely matters.

author: Leah Greenblatt
snippet: It’s not that MAYA is some sort of spectacular failure; it’s just that nothing here feels truly vital, or nearly as revolutionary as she seems to want us to believe.

author: Alex Young
snippet: With provocative but overall senseless lyrics, a horrible undertone of feigned political vilification, and a straight up fucking dumb title, this album is truly an error, a blooper that needs to be edited out.

author: Brad Wete
snippet: Rap’s first lady may never get the appreciation brashly expected from the aforementioned “she.” But Minaj has certainly earned it here.

author: Joshua Errett
snippet: Though the mainstream gloss doesn’t suit, Minaj wears the album’s darker hues well. Overall, Pink Friday is a good look for an introduction.
Jamaica Queen's potty-mouth hits rap home run on brutally enjoyable debut.

author: Emily Mackay
snippet: One hopes that with the confidence this record brings, she’ll take a more permanent seat at hip-hop’s high table. Because when she’s at her best, she’s the bestest there is.

author: Jim Carroll
snippet: The more she's added oomph to tracks by Lil Wayne, Mariah Carey, Kanye West and others, the more her own rep has grown, meaning Pink Friday comes with a fair set of expectations. Minaj deals with these with considerable ease.

author: Chase McMullen
snippet: On the heels of the brilliant My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy and the misunderstood Recovery Minaj follows in style by putting out an album interested in both hip hop and music that simply sounds great.

author: John Murphy
snippet: It’s not everyone who can give Slim Shady a run for his money, but Minaj more than holds her own here, sounding both menacing and cartoon-like and even dropping into an approximation of a cockney accent at one point.

author: David Jeffries
snippet: In the end, Pink Friday is an ambitious, glossy stunner if fashion week is your favorite time of year, but Minaj didn’t earn her diva status this way.

author: Marc Hogan
snippet: Rap’s most hotly anticipated debut works best if you don’t think of it as a rap album at all.

author: Chris Coplan
snippet: For whatever reason ... the voices in her own head aren’t strong enough to out-sway input from others, leading to a few unimpressive moments in the LP.

author: Rob Sheffield
snippet: On Pink Friday, the year’s most anticipated hip-hop debut, she’s already rapping about the superstar life.

author: Greg Watkins
snippet: The culmination of an intense promotion campaign and tremendous hype.

author: Kathy Iandoli
snippet: Pink Friday was one of the most highly-anticipated albums of 2010, largely due to curiosity. The reality is that it could have never lived up to the hype it prematurely received. Still, there’s room for growth, and Nicki Minaj has both the skills and the following to keep moving up.

author: Genevieve Koski
snippet: Reinforcing the notion that all female MCs must also sing, Minaj spends half of the album crooning, and while her singing isn’t bad, it’s dialed into that radio-friendly sweet spot so aggressively that it loses all distinction.

author: Scott Plagenhoef
snippet: One of the most exciting new voices in hip-hop makes her proper full-length debut, doing a lot of singing and not nearly enough rapping.

author: Beca Grimm
snippet: Pink Friday, while certainly far from profound, is neatly rooted in predictability and vulgarity. But then again, would we have Minaj any other way?

author: David Smyth
snippet: Rap's new queen bee is set for a lengthy reign.

author: Andrew Murfett
snippet: This record positively rumbles. The swagger is extraordinary - and mostly justified.

author: Will Lavin
snippet: If ‘Pink Friday’ was a report card it would read: “Solid first time effort, works well with others but there’s room for improvement.”

author: David Renshaw
snippet: ‘Pink Friday’ wins merely on points, rather than the knockout punch it should have been.

author: Andy Gill
snippet: There's nothing on Pink Friday with quite the incendiary impact of her cameo on Kanye West's "Monster", but there's enough to confirm the buzz about Nicki Minaj being the future of female hip-hop.

author: Alexis Petridis
snippet: You're left with an album that's nearly fantastic, the frustrating sound of an artist who can't work out whether she should go her own way or try and fit in with the crowd, even when the right answer is staring her in the face.

author: Jesse Cataldo
snippet: The album is a whirling dervish less concerned with differing permutations of sexiness than getting violently up in your face.

author: Alex Young
snippet: Big things are in store for this rapper; bigger than Pink Friday. But everybody’s gotta break into the game somewhere.

author: Chris Barth
snippet: Pink Friday is just the type of toned-down, anonymous pop that is impossible to stop on the charts. But it’s this type of crap that signals the death of artistry, no matter how catchy the result is. This feels less like an album and more like a product, and that hollowness leaves me with a bitter taste in my mouth.

Pink Friday lives or dies on Minaj’s ability to fully embody all of the various personas she toys with, the singer, the rapper, the lover, the fighter, the tomboy, the girly girl, the big sister, the bitch. But she isn’t always engaging, and she doesn’t always sound at home with this material.

author: David Amidon
snippet: Pink Friday is a real shame, albeit a very well-marketed one, and since it’s found its niche, it’s no surprise the album was a fair success for Minaj.

author: Nick Hanover
snippet: As tempting as it is to want to give Nicki Minaj a break on Pink Friday, what with overblown expectations, there’s one very important fact to keep in mind: Nicki Minaj has become a hip-hop sensation because of how unique and adventurous she is behind the mic, not because we were in need of another bland pop star.

author: David Raposa
