snippet: Hardcore Daughters lovers will probably have plenty of bones to pick with this album. For everyone else, Daughters is a feast to be savored.
Now far removed from their grindcore past, Daughters are all the better for it on their third album.

Daughters ended their career (until further notice) with a self-titled record that was partially disheartening, as their songwriting only marginally improved because it was countered by a sonic dissonance that never allowed for any significant dynamics. But that’s what Daughters wanted; an album recorded as max volume to be played at max volume.

The drums and bass on their new, self-titled album create a punishing bedrock for the songs to set in, there's a semblance of melody in some parts, and when the band's trademark guitar stings pierce through Alexis Marshall's Danzig-esque howl, they're well paced and plotted.

author: Anthony Fantano
snippet: Daughters' self-titled album is one of the best punishments I've had all year. In terms of being noisy and aggressive as hell, it's almost up there with that Little Women album I reviewed, but I could see this LP coming across as being a lot more accessible than that one.
The experimental band is out in full force with “Daughters,” arguably creating their most finely crafted effort to date.

Daughters have been described as everything from mathcore or math metal to alternative metal to grindcore, but noise rock is the term that best captures Daughters in 2010 -- and make no mistake: this is an extremely noisy album.
There's no giant compromise here: it's still a huge wreck of noise, ruthlessly delivering the Providence staples of dueling dissonant guitars and frantic bombast.

author: Sinead Gleeson
snippet: Many loved its high arcs; others balked at the shrill notes, but no one doubted Newsom’s originality – and indie harpers are rare enough.

author: Darren Harvey
snippet: Have One On Me is winding, long-winded, densely poetic, and often challenging; but never tedious or self-indulgent.
Have One on Me is a very mature work indeed, even its resonant, discursive themes are underpinned by Newsom's usual playfulness.
To devotees ... it sounds very much like a second masterpiece: a different kind of epic to "Ys," and one with enough hooks and charms to ensnare at least a few Newsom agnostics.

author: Chris Cusack
snippet: Whether being swept up in the delicate instrumentation or contemplating the meanings within, it is, at times, a transcendental experience. Some four years in the making, Have One On Me will continue to reveal aspects of as-yet-undiscovered beauty for that long again.

author: Joe Rivers
snippet: Have One On Me is so enrapturing, so imaginative and so delicate, that it feels safe to say that in five or ten years time, you’ll go back to it and discover brand new things - whether they be the meaning of a song you’d never fathomed before or a simple amuse-bouche of a beautifully constructed oboe phrase.

author: Philip Cosores
snippet: They say you can’t please everyone, but Joanna Newsom has managed to combine two radically different song-writing styles and make a third that is very much her own, and very much an experience with a record like no other.

author: Mark Richardson
snippet: The best songs feel more like conversations rather than artworks to be hung on the wall and admired from several paces away. Newsom seems to sing from somewhere deep inside of them, and her earthy presence has a way of drawing you in, bringing you closer to her music than you've been before.

author: Simon Vozick-Levinson
snippet: While Newsom remains the most intricate lyricist currently working outside of rap, her melodies have become cleaner, her arrangements less mannered, and her singing more straightforwardly heartfelt.

author: Hari Ashurst
snippet: It is a stunning and ambitious piece of work; one for the ages.

author: Kyle Wall
snippet: Right when you decide to play it back, you’re enraptured by the hint of another momentous musical shift on the horizon. Next thing you know, you find yourself two hours into one of the most even ratios of ambition and payoff in any recent album, and you’re having a hard time hearing anything to complain about.
Have One on Me isn't at all a ploy for greater likability. It's an affecting, indulgent, and thoroughly fleshed-out monument to Newsom's considerable ambition.

I feel like I can whittle away my days listening to this album and only this album for the rest of my life, and never have to feel anything except what this album makes me feel. Which is to say, everything.

author: Jim Scott
snippet: Stripped for much of the time of the horns and orchestral adornment of the first disc, Newsom turns a celebration into a confessional. Just when it seems Newsom couldn't possibly have any more rabbits in her hat, the third disc contains some gospel flourishes that concentrate her voice in a whole new way, bending down low to grab some bit of soul.

author: Ray Finlayson
snippet: On her new album, Have One On Me, she lays on a couch in a glamorised setting with peacock feathers, exquisite lamps and animal statues around her. All these items on these covers have their obvious symbolic connotations but as Newsom pointed out in an interview, these items are also not as objective as they may appear.

author: Jeff Vrabel
snippet: It’s difficult to imagine another situation in which plinking pixie sounds, recurrent madrigal noises and radiant folk poetry could be categorically described as honking huge, but for all its girth, Have One On Me is packed with magic.

author: David Greenwald
snippet: The thing Have One On Me absolutely excels at is the creation of remarkable moments amid its rambling odes.

author: Chris Barth
snippet: Joanna Newsom resides in a space all her own – it’s safe to say that there isn’t another artist like her currently producing music, at least not that I’ve come across.
She simply delves deeper and gives what few artists can deliver: a self-contained world of warmth, crystalline detail, and intimacy that lies far beyond a Twitter feed.

author: David Smyth
snippet: It's like enrolling on a course, demanding stamina and commitment. Most of all it's a towering creative achievement, capable of delivering new pleasures for months and years to come.

author: Embling
snippet: Were brevity the chiefmost virtue of popular music, “Baby Birch” would be a turgid waste of time, rather than the deft and skillful creature it is. The same sentiment goes for the rest of the album; there is a depth to the material here that rewards — nay, demands — repeated scrutiny.
This is a record so richly involving that it promises to throw up fresh delights weeks, or even months, down the line.

author: Sarah Crompton
snippet: Each song creates a specific world, full of haunting imagery and precise, poetic evocations of mood.

author: Paul Terefenko
snippet: For long-time fans, this three-disc (or vinyl) release won’t disappoint, though it’s not a total departure.

author: Emily Mackay
snippet: It’s unlikely that you’ll often listen to it in one bout, but whether beguiled one day by its exotic petals and blooms or the next by the less showy trees in the background, Have One On Me is an Elysian record that you’ll return to again and again.

author: Will Dean
snippet: Grand, long and bold – Newsom makes it sound like the first word she sings here: easy.

Newsom's wispy singing style may still be too inaccessible for some, but hardcore fans will savor the growing vocal confidence during the two-hour-plus running time. In an era of quick musical fixes, Have One on Me is a spacious artistic statement too original to pass up.

author: Rich Hanscomb
snippet: Have One On Me’s scope and ambition is as commendable as it is slightly exhausting – it demands you immerse yourself in its world.

author: Andy Battaglia
snippet: Musically, Newsom sounds, relatively speaking, downright conventional on Have One. After the odd, goading arrangements of 2006’s Ys, she seems to have prioritized clarity and space, whether on simple songs for just harp and voice, or more elaborate ones for up to 14 players.

author: Heather Phares
snippet: At its best, these songs have the feel of an intimate live performance; at their worst, they’re lovely, but exhausting. Have One on Me is quite a technical achievement, but since Newsom has proven she can do just about anything, next time she shouldn’t try to do everything.

author: Will Hermes
snippet: Her latest firmly establishes her as a singer-songwriter to be reckoned with.

author: Matthew Cole
snippet: The end result is a strange, and strangely pretentious mess: an album pitted deep in the psychic world of stories that nonetheless can't figure out when it should begin, when it should end, or which parts are even worth the audience's attention.

author: Matthew Fiander
snippet: It’s too bad really, that Have One on Me is so overdone because there’s a decent album hidden somewhere in there. It’s an album the Newsom we saw in 2006 would have found, formed, and made shine.

author: Chris Buckle
snippet: The bold grandeur and breathtaking finesse of The National's current form is unmistakable.

There isn't a bad song on the album, and generally when people say things like that they seem to imply that there are still a few duds here and there. But High Violet is literally free of weak moments.

author: Steven Hyden
snippet: High Violet is carefully considered without being labored, richly detailed without being fussy.

author: James Skinner
snippet: It is a wild, vivid romance that The National make their own, and on High Violet it sounds just as striking, just as wild, just as vivid as ever.
High Violet is one of those rare albums where a band’s rising profile and rising talent meet in a perfect storm of anticipation and excellence.

author: Jason Lipshutz
snippet: "High Violet" synthesizes the best parts of the National's past into a fantastic present.

author: Chris Watkeys
snippet: This band has a peerless ability to make music which seeps into your consciousness, slowly ferments and finally produces a musical wine of such intoxicating majesty you’re left dumbstruck.

author: Kevin Liedel
snippet: There’s a wry beauty in subtle morbidity, and the National has struck it on High Violet.

With High Violet they are not just playing on the tension like Boxer but taking that idea and building on it, and thats the thing with The National. They build, they build honestly and meaningfully, they build a place inside your heart. Each album sits like a footprint in the snow.

author: Drew Litowitz
snippet: They’ve taken some minor risks, tailored their sound, and emerged with a record that can stand confidently beside Boxer and Alligator, all without overdoing or losing any of its predecessors’ merits.

author: David Coleman
snippet: The National’s latest is easily up there with the very best indie-rock records of the year.
High Violet isn’t simply The National’s best album; it’s already one of the strongest album of this young decade and will likely continue to be, even in another nine years from now.

author: Rob Watson
snippet: If all of the band’s records had a loose thematic core running through to them, High Violet is the band’s most grown up record – mirroring the now late-30something group’s outlook on life.

author: Chris Barth
snippet: Everyone keeps saying that this is a sad album. It’s not. It’s an honest album, a real album. And it’s breathtaking.

author: Andrew Gaerig
snippet: High Violet is the sound of a band taking a mandate to be a meaningful rock band seriously, and they play the part so fully that, to some, it may be off-putting.

author: David M. Goldstein
snippet: A massive, dynamic album that still makes good on the National’s devotion to meticulous production and a sound they’ve kept simple and distinctive for a decade.

author: Leah Greenblatt
snippet: Their fifth album High Violet is slow to blossom; its sumptuous layers and stately pace can feel almost funereal, and frontman Matt Berninger often sounds badly in need of Paxil. But Violet eventually burrows in, and stays.

author: Jason Killingsworth
snippet: Though High Violet lacks the front-to-back consistency that made Boxer such an unmitigated revelation, the new album’s peaks absolutely rival Boxer’s best tracks.

author: David Smyth
snippet: Things move at a stately pace and if it sounds bleak on paper, there's also a beauty here that reinforces how special this band is.
In anyone's book, it should be a record to treasure.

author: Ian Mathers
snippet: High Violet summons up perfectly and terribly the sneaking suspicion you start getting in your 20s that possibilities are closing off, that your life might not turn out the way you wanted it to, and that there’s probably no-one else to blame but yourself.

author: Laura Davies
snippet: ‘High Violet’ sees an already cherished band fine-tune their flaws to become something truly beguiling and brilliant. Astonishing.

author: Josh Modell
snippet: Simmering more than it strikes, High Violet coaxes you into baroque indie darkness rather than shines bright pop lights.

author: Eric Dennis
snippet: There is unarguably a gravity to both Berninger’s voice and the band’s musical sensibilities that carry the album. It’s this combination that makes these songs so visceral and emotionally impacting.

author: Dave Simpson
snippet: Crafted from humming guitars, tinkling pianos, militaristic drumming and occasional orchestration, their fifth album is beautifully subtle and grows in power with each listen.
At the peak moments of High Violet, The National are magnificent.

author: Emily Mackay
snippet: Darker and more introspectively brooding than ever, in places it’s the most immediate National effort since their overlooked eponymous debut.

author: Paul Terefenko
snippet: Building on 2007's Boxer, High Violet should keep the melancholic band's aging indie fans crying into the future.

author: Andy Gill
snippet: It's an impressive achievement overall, offering a masterclass in subtle emotional shading, which none of their current peers, and few of their inspirational influences, could equal.

author: Ed Cumming
snippet: Their greatest strength is singer Matt Berninger’s magma flow of a voice, running thickly over urgent guitars and jittery drums.

author: Elias Isquith
snippet: Should I be so surprised that High Violet ... represents their most, self-serious, dour and morose release yet?

author: Jim Scott
snippet: High Violet is a fine album, a very, very solid effort that contains some marvelous storytelling and near perfect execution. There are no faults to speak of. But that electricity, that fly by the seat of your pants thrill is something that eludes The National.

author: Will Hermes
snippet: Singer Matt Berninger's gorgeous baritone is still the band's main selling point ... Yet the tension comes mainly from composers Aaron and Bryce Dessner: The music is some of their lushest and darkest.

author: James Christopher Monger
snippet: Muscular, miserable, mighty, and meandering, High Violet aims for the seats, but only hits about half of them.
Falls away from Boxer's overwhelming quietness as they fill the erstwhile emptiness with distorted guitars, strings, brass: an ambient tangle.

author: Anthony Fantano
snippet: The National's latest is loaded with lush production and somber vocals, but the album may be a little too melancholy for its own good.

author: Charlie Frame
snippet: Despite a sincere lack of happy hardcore bangers or light-relief comedy skits, ‘High Violet’ is a tight, no-nonsense follow-up to 2007’s critically acclaimed ‘Boxer’.

author: John Murphy
snippet: While they won’t win any points for innovation, Two Door Cinema Club are going to find their way into a lot of people’s hearts during 2010.

author: Alex Young
snippet: Tourist History scratches an itch that no other album can. No matter how unoriginal it may be, it is scarily enjoyable, addictive and… irresistible. Simply put: Two Door Cinema Club just makes this kind of music so much darn better than anyone else right now.

author: Jordan Bimm
snippet: True, these lads aren’t reinventing the wheel, but what they forfeit in originality they make up for in perfect execution of cute dance-rock anthems.

author: Lauren Murphy
snippet: Ten pop gems to tap your toe to till it's a bruised, bloody stump.

author: Dom Gourlay
snippet: Tourist History is an infectious debut that may well divide opinion, but at least suggests that amidst all the uneasy listening and obtuse noises coming out of the underground at present there are still those capable of writing the odd tune or ten.

author: Heather Phares
snippet: While Two Door Cinema Club don't yet have the flawless style or emotional weight of some of their influences, Tourist History just gets catchier and more stylized as it goes on, offering a promising foundation for the band to embellish with even more personality next time.

author: Emily Mackay
snippet: Don’t tell the emos, but it seems like being happy is the new being sad.

author: Gareth O'Malley
snippet: The album has more hooks than you can shake a stick at, and there are some real promising moments here. For the most part, however, the band are in thrall to their influences, and some thinking outside the box is needed if they are to create a sound of their own.

The band's debut album 'Tourist History' is clearly far from original, yet it ultimately wins listeners over with its immediate, enthusiastic, likeable and catchy mixture of ingredients, which results in a sound that is certain to have toes tapping from the pubs to the clubs.

author: Estella Hung
snippet: While invention may not be a going concern, Two Door Cinema Club have proven on their maiden voyage that they jolly well know how to sway a crowd with infective pop gems and seemingly little sweat.

author: Chris Buckle
snippet: The excitement their best songs generate dissipates too quickly for them to firmly find their feet. But sift out the filler and seeds of longevity remain, not least in You’re Not Stubborn’s up-beat finale.

author: Matthias Scherer
snippet: Sorry boys – entry to the League of Goodness is denied.
If there was ever a defining moment for the band, this is it.

While bleakness is certainly prominent throughout, this album has many different shades and it is these contrasts that make it so vital. It's an album that bursts with ambition, and that Bring Me The Horizon pull it off so powerfully further confirms their greatness.
There Is A Hell is an impressive and ambitious third effort that proves these Brits have staying power.
The odd electronic twist sugars the pill, but it's mostly relentless if brutally effective stuff.

author: Gregory Heaney
snippet: There Is a Hell finds Bring Me the Horizon at the top of their game, and its lack of over-indulgent production makes it an album that’ll not only please fans of the band, but may surprise fans of bands like Converge who are interested in seeing what the kids are up to these days.

author: Christopher Schultz
snippet: On their third album, these dizzying British metalcore chemists swing erratically in an effort to shake genre conventions, flirting with dystopic Max Headroom stutter, electro gloom, and tender indie-folk cuddles.

Hurley represents a terrific rebound, a blast of sonic sweetness that finds the band integrating ’60s pop influences (Beach Boys; Phil Spector ”Wall of Sound” soundishness) into their tight, punk-pop songwriting.
Hurley isn't perfect, but it's the best thing Weezer have done in quite some time, and that's all we can hope for—until the next Nirvana comes along, of course.
It’s a pleasure to report, then, that ‘Hurley’, the band’s eighth album, is a return to form in a huge way.
This is the Weezer we haven’t known for a while, and is a great way to start the new decade.
Hurley is a triumph for the band in that it is finally a return to form. As a standalone record, this is arguably their most enjoyable album since Maladroit.

A bonus-track cover of Coldplay’s Viva La Vida is kind of sickly, but generally this album is yet another celebration of a band so comfortable in their own skin that you can’t help but follow their example.

author: Anthony Fantano
snippet: It might seem impossible, but this album is actually somewhat solid. I can't say it's going to make history in Weezer's discography--maybe for it's cover--but it's certainly a bright spot considering its predecessors were Raditude and Red.

While Hurley can in no way compare to The Blue Album and Pinkerton, it sits proudly atop the list of everything Weezer have done since. Sure that may not be saying much, but damn, it's a pleasant surprise.
On the whole, Hurley isn’t the catastrophe people probably expected. It’s pretty enjoyable.

Those who optimistically purchased Make Believe and Raditude will know that a good first single does not a great Weezer album make, but Hurley is packed solid, with a sense of fun and good-time melodies cropping up at every juncture.
The band’s aims are more modest now: have fun, get people to sing along, share a common feeling or two. Hurley achieves those goals with something approaching dignity. Phew.

Again, Cuomo doesn’t suppress his emotion; he just prefers sentiment (albeit delivered somewhat ironically as on lead single “Memories”), but what he loves most of all is a pure pop song and Hurley offers up its fair share.

As they grow older, Cuomo and his bandmates will never make a record that supplants their fans’ fond Pinkerton-related memories—but a few more impassioned albums like Hurley might erase the sour aftertaste of several Raditudes.

Reminiscing about their nineties days, Hurley is very much a reawakening towards more confessional material. Though it sounds more imaginary than accurate, Cuomo’s calculated verses remain purposely effortless.
All told, Hurley is a near return to form for Weezer. Indeed, it’s exactly the album they needed it to be, and it could just be enough to keep both camps of fans interested.
Luckily, thanks to some key assists from outside hands, Cuomo rarely falls into the same trap again, and the majority of Hurley is mindless (dare I even say it) fun.
Considering the decreased role of Cuomo’s actual bandmates, it’s not too surprising that Hurley feels more like one of his Alone home demo compilations than anything Weezer’s ever released.

Cuomo co-writes with a bevy of A-list song doctors, and calls in cameos from the Jackass crew and Michael Cera, seemingly just for the hell of it. The result: a Weezer record, some great cornball pop-metal tuneage, some irony, some insanity.
Eight years ago this might have been a decent debut for a Weezer-rip-off pop-punk band, but now, even at their best, Weezer too often come off now as self-parody.

author: Ian Cohen
snippet: Nobody is going to confuse this with 1990s Weezer-- there are still plenty of oddball collaborations (Michael Cera, Linda Perry) for one thing-- but the lows aren't as low or as frequent as they were in recent years.
The albums have kept coming, but the world has moved on, and the band's leader, Rivers Cuomo, seems to have lost the sure touch he once had.

At least he has some good memories of “playing Hacky Sack backstage when Audioslave were still Rage,” but naming the album after Hugo "Hurley" Reyes only magnifies the fact that Weezer have gotten a little lost in the new millennium.

As endearing as Jorge Garcia’s face is, shining warmly from the cover of Weezer’s eighth release, the timely pop reference to a Lost character is the perfect symbol for a band on a continued downward spiral into meme-based gimmickry and music with zero staying power.

Now that Cuomo is older and singing about things like fame and the alienation of age, it’s become harder to empathize. But at this steady rate of basically listenable and huge-selling albums, Weezer’s a sure bet for the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 2019, assuming Western civilization hasn’t collapsed, and no one will be able to say they didn’t succeed.
Hurley is, for the most part, chock full of the same mechanical dreck that has peppered Weezer’s last handful of releases, from Maladroit to Raditude.
Rap’s new anti-hero: unhinged, brutal and intense.
Like at the conclusion of a particularly destructive intoxicant binge, you might not like yourself very much when it’s all over.

author: David Drake
snippet: Anyone coming to this record expecting wordplay, or criticizing it for its lack thereof, is missing the point completely: Flockaveli thrives on Waka's fresh approach to the same generation gap-widening narrative that's driven street rap since before N.W.A.
Flockaveli is inevitably going to overwhelm or repulse as many people as it charms into its web. It’s hard to imagine it being a grower, either.
On a gut level ... “Flockaveli” works. It’s morally questionable, but it hits hard. The beats are banging, and Waka proves that owning a thesaurus and being clever aren’t the only way to be a rapper.
Flockaveli‘s flaw is not Waka’s coarseness, but his generosity — 25 guest verses from anonymous Brick Squad cronies suck up air instead of letting Waka breathe without mentor Gucci Mane’s oxygen tank
On his debut, Waka reduces hip-hop to a carnival-barker routine, blasting out exclamations (“Yay!” “Bang!”) over bristling beats by producer Lex Luger.
It’s comforting to hear something feeling so insular and self-involved, even if it’s only entertaining in cars and as awkward filler at parties.
Flockaveli has enough hooks and attitude to keep those bottles poppin’ all night long, and whether or not you remember any of it the next day, it does serve its purpose.
Like Waka Flocka Flame’s entire career thus far, listeners will either love or completely detest his debut album Flockaveli.

author: Mikael Wood
snippet: Valley Girl sneer with electro-glam arrangements that make brushing one’s teeth ”with a bottle of Jack” sound like an awesome way to kill the morning-after blues.

author: Andrew Burgess
snippet: Arguments of purpose and meaning aside, Animal is an infectiously good dance-pop album, and by all meaningful estimations, a towering triumph.

author: Robin Jahdi
snippet: While some corners of the pop world are conspiring to bland us all to death, Ke$ha joins Lady Gaga at the forefront of the fightback.

author: Cat Zhang
snippet: A ridiculously fun and somewhat fraught album whose garish aesthetic is being channeled anew.

author: Monica Herrera
snippet: “Animal” teems with choruses that stick with the listener for days.

author: David Jeffries
snippet: Snooty taste makers and parents should avoid Animal at all costs, but with so many fun, “TiK ToK”-type tracks, the album has plenty for both brats and the bratty at heart.
Clearly aiming for some of the Lady Gaga's action, debut album Animal contains more of the same surging synth-pop and invitations to party.

author: Jody Rosen
snippet: It's repulsive, obnoxious and ridiculously catchy.

author: Neil McCormick
snippet: There's a lot of bratty energy and some catchy twists but it will only feel fresh and vital to a teenager.

author: Laura Snapes
snippet: Clever rhythms and rhymes are testament to a musicality that the disposable nature of her subject matter hides.
Kesha’s potty mouth and questionable sense of humour are entertaining for the first three listens but her signature sound is a bit too Euro pop to actually stay hooked after this.

author: Jim Carroll
snippet: Lyrically, there may be a sense that she is out to shock, but there’s little in her off-the-shoulder wisecracking, screwball hard-chawing and acid retorts that we haven’t heard and dismissed before.

author: Paul Terefenko
snippet: If only the insipid lyrics were left off completely.

author: Dave Simpson
snippet: She comes over as an amalgam of Lady Gaga, Katy Perry and Britney, which, judging by the multimillion sales of single Tik Tok, is just what the market wants.

author: Nate Adams
snippet: Listening to Ke$ha's hyper-sexual, misanthropic disco debut Animal is a lot like watching an insecure college freshman try to heal deep emotional scarring with alcohol and promiscuity.

author: David Renshaw
snippet: Where it tries to be empowering and fun it comes off sounding like a spoilt brat singing the American Pie script through auto-tune. Not even the good American Pie either, the newest straight to DVD one's.

author: Jonathan Keefe
snippet: Just about the only thing Ke$ha makes convincing on Animal is that the current crop of party girls are every bit as soulless as they let on.
Her witless, cranked-to-11 stridency recalls Kelly Clarkson and Avril Lavigne rather than Pink or Britney.

author: Andy Gill
snippet: Her songs are pure attitude, whether slagging off rivals in "Backstabber" and "Kiss N Tell", boasting about "pissing in the Dom Perignon" at a "Party At A Rich Dude's House", or celebrating the dubious charms of a club where "they go hardcore, and there's glitter on the floor". But there's no real character behind the bogus attitude and not even any coherence to her vapid babblings.

author: Paul Brannigan
snippet: Where Avenged go from here is still in the lap of the gods. Whatever their future, though, Nightmare marks the point at which the Huntington Beach crew put away childish things and became men.

author: Billboard Staff
snippet: It’s a sweeping, quasi-thematic epic whose nearly 67 minutes mixes punky abandon with prog-rock ambition and muscle with musicality.

author: Jason Lymangrover
snippet: The group’s influences may be worn on their sleeves, but there is no denying that they have some of the best chops in the metal world.
While Avenged Sevenfold have previously been able to overcome their weaknesses, the strongest moments on Nightmare aren't quite good enough to hide its flaws.

author: Ryson Dahl
snippet: It’s stirring stuff in parts, though the old criticism still applies – A7X have far too much Metallica, Pantera and Guns N’ Roses in their sound. Get over that, though, and there’s some depth here.

author: Leonard Pierce
snippet: The irritatingly hooky “Nightmare” is already rocketing up the charts, so it’s unlikely the band’s fans will care, but Avenged Sevenfold continues to sound like five different bands on every album, none of them particularly good.

author: Anthony Fantano
snippet: There isn't an abundance of hooks or sweet melodies here. Instead, Public Strain is filled with a bleak, isolating tension. It's something that I've been looking for--subconsciously, maybe--in a 2010 record.

author: Aaron Leitko
snippet: The group's sophomore effort, Public Strain, pushes forward in both directions-- the hooks are noisier, the noise is hookier, and both are fogged over with enough reverb to make Felt records seem bone-dry by comparison.

author: Laura Snapes
snippet: Canadian four-piece's second album aims for the romantic, not just the rational.

author: Julia Reidy
snippet: So no, Public Strain isn’t the manic, dirty opus Women was. But it’s still Women. And I’m still in love with it.

author: Chris Coplan
snippet: Yes, it’s fine to use the same methods Mr. Reed implemented, but to dole out several minutes of junk noise doesn’t make you seem unique, clever, or even like students of the game; it makes you sound pretentious.

author: John-Michael Bond
snippet: There are definitely scabs here, but it’s never boring watching Wayne fall down as he figures out rock n’ roll.
Tame punk-driven guitar licks may eclipse hard basslines, but familiarity is found in Wayne's willingness to be lyrically venturesome.

author: Robert Ferguson
snippet: Lil Wayne has earned his time in the spotlight the hard way, but it’s hard to view Rebirth as anything other than resting on his laurels.

author: Christian Hoard
snippet: If you have an Internet connection, you know that it's his rock & roll record — not such a crazy idea for this leather-clad Martian with serious rock-star appeal. The problem is that Wayne has very questionable taste in rock.

author: Ryan Dombal
snippet: He really went ahead and did it: Lil Wayne finally releases his unlikely, unqualified, and quite unbelievable rock album.

author: David Jeffries
snippet: It’s more interesting to ponder Wayne's reasons for making Rebirth than to actually listen to it, because the end result is a loud and ignorable bore.

author: David Smyth
snippet: The combination of his heavily Auto-Tuned, croaky singing voice and largely tuneless metal riffing grates right from opening track American Star.

author: Alexis Petridis
snippet: Even in the hands of audacious Lil Wayne, rap-metal still ends up sounding ghastly.
That summarizes Rebirth — hackneyed writing, hackneyed pop-rock beats, usually both.

author: Laura Snapes
snippet: The Carter's much-delayed reincarnation proves rocking isn't as easy as he thinks.

author: Leah Greenblatt
snippet: Jordan returned to the basketball court after one ill-fated season in the farm leagues; we can only hope for the same for Wayne.

author: Nathan Rabin
snippet: The result plays like an over-the-top parody of a rock album.

author: Alex Thornton
snippet: Rebirth, on the other hand, is mired in trying to prove a point that no one was questioning to begin with. After the last three years, Lil Wayne can do whatever the hell he wants. “Can” and “should,” however, are two very different things.

author: Clayton Purdom
snippet: This is just an awful fucking record, and way worse than Wayne fans, obnoxious as we can be, deserve.

author: Jesse Cataldo
snippet: More concerned with emulating fashion-metal glitz than delivering anything of substance, he feels like an out-of-shape boxer being pummeled by his own beats and guests.

author: Charles Aaron
snippet: Clearly, if a stoned millionaire insists on singing and playing guitar (when he can’t technically do either), the results are gonna be sketchy. But Rebirth is far goofier than it had to be.
Rebirth is the kind of album only the painfully oblivious could make.

author: Ryan Faughnder
snippet: Wayne has created the new Pet Sounds of bad music.

author: Joshua Errett
snippet: Rebirth is - without qualification - the most embarrassing album of the last 10 years. Embarrassing for him, for his audience, for rap, for humanity.

author: Gervase de Wilde
snippet: If The Darkness came back as a rap act they might sound like this — and that's not a good thing.

author: Sean Highkin
snippet: These songs aren’t even “so bad they’re funny”–they’re just plodding and hookless and unlikable on any level.

author: Alex Young
snippet: This sounds like a musician running fast out of ideas.
In case you couldn't tell, this is one of the worst albums in the history of recorded music with a budget.

author: Patrick Taylor
snippet: It’s easily one of my favorite records of the year so far, and I’ve been evangelizing all my friends about Danny Brown. Don’t sleep on “The Hybrid.”

author: Andrew Martin
snippet: Unfortunately, Brown is still going to turn some listeners away, no matter how fantastic the production and lyrics are on The Hybrid.

author: Martin Douglas
snippet: Following the lead of Royce da 5'9" and Elzhi, this rising Detroit rapper proves he's also one of underground rap's brightest young talents on his new LP.

A twisted yet amazing album that will lure you in with its excellent sound, archaic references and soaring vocals. This album is great for those who are seeking something different that feels familiar.

author: Steel Druhm
snippet: The debut by Sweden’s Ghost ... is a goldmine of expertly written and played mega-retro 70’s style satanic heavy metal.

Opus Eponymous is an extraordinary debut that slowly peels back surprise after surprise as you delve into its 35 minutes of music. Sure, the style is old-school, but it's musically very rich, often more subtle than riff-oriented, and as closing instrumental "Genesis" proves, capable of moments of disarming beauty.

Although its songs are rife with heavy metal's favorite subject matter and unmistakably menacing brand of staccato guitar riffing, the restraint of their attack, not to mention their production (no overdriven amplifiers are to be found here), hark back to what passed for a metallic aesthetic during the very early '80s, or even before.

author: Anthony Fantano
snippet: The lyrics are very cultist and satanic, but still catchy. The slightly deadpan vocals only make the sound eerier--along with the sinister organ, of course.

author: Connor McKnight
snippet: It takes a tight musical alliance to forge a complete rock sound without full band support.

author: Jonathan Keefe
snippet: The album is as ferocious and soulful an exploration of contemporary blues as anything in recent memory.

author: Stephen Thomas Erlewine
snippet: The tough blues band of the Black Keys earliest records is back, but the group hasn’t forgotten what they’ve learned in their inwardly psychedelic mid-period.

author: Leah Greenblatt
snippet: Real songwriting, and real hooks, beneath all that mondo riffage

author: Noel Murray
snippet: Before, The Black Keys made the kind of music that crate-diggers might sample. Now they sound like they’re sampling themselves.

author: Ian Barker
snippet: An extremely intelligent record that isn’t spoiled by self-awareness; it’s genuine without being niche.
Brothers is really all about The Black Keys; swaggering journey from sub-White Stripes curio to one of the best rock'n'roll bands on the planet.
The old stomp is still here, but Alabama has stoked The Black Keys' dark side.

author: David Fricke
snippet: Thick, dirty racket, overdubbed but never overstuffed.

author: Jason Morton
snippet: The Keys sound like they're morphing into a bold new beast, but if this slab of wax is any indication they’ll keep putting quality over experimentation every time.
A new chapter for one of rock's most consistent bands.

author: Richard Trapunski
snippet: They may have other interests now, but there’s still gas left in the Black Keys’ tank

author: Ted Maider
snippet: Brothers is what we want out of rock music: brilliance and individuality
Fans will debate stand-outs but Brothers will shiver the spine of anyone in love with unsanitised rock'n'roll.

author: Emily Mackay
snippet: Lack of authenticity is no barrier for The Black Keys.

author: Jim Carroll
snippet: Album No 6 finds them in Alabama's Muscle Shoals Sound studio soaking their patented spikey, stomping blues with soulful vibes.

author: Andrew Burgess
snippet: Brothers is a woozy, murky album, fat as a tick, and riled up like a kicked hornets' nest. Whatever growing pains they've gone through as a pair has been worth it; Brothers hits harder than either of their solo albums.

author: Jason P. Woodbury
snippet: Brothers is the least stuffy record The Black Keys has put out, and it's by far their strongest.

author: Andy Gill
snippet: A new, idiosyncratic branch sprouting from this oldest of rock'n'roll roots.

author: Larry Fitzmaurice
snippet: After working with Danger Mouse on their last full-length, Black Keys sound re-energized and playful on their loosest record in years.
Brothers ... proves that the Keys can still put a few more miles on their well-driven blues machine, regardless of what direction their non-Keys work takes them.

author: Clayton Purdom
snippet: “This is an album by The Black Keys,” it declares. The music within proves why that’s a good thing—something laudatory, and worth preservation.

author: Anthony Fantano
snippet: Lots of consistency and great production, too. I wish there could have been some more contrast in the songwriting department, though.

author: Chris Middleman
snippet: This is a snakier, more nuanced Black Keys, whose command of the studio matches their command of their two-man, thunderous format.

author: Aaron Lavery
snippet: It finds The Black Keys taking on elements of what they’ve learnt on their journey here, but sticking resolutely to a recipe of guitar, drums and raspy, wisened vocals.

author: Andy Pareti
snippet: Brothers doesn’t break new ground for the band, but it continues to affirm the band’s soul, further demonstrating the unlimited power of blues music.

author: David Gassmann
snippet: That the Black Keys are still exploring new territories with enthusiasm is cause for celebration, and Brothers is the reason why.

author: Michaelangelo Matos
snippet: These guys rock hard, but they need to lose the high school poetry.

author: Will Dean
snippet: Yep, there's plenty of life here, but interest wavers when howling barroom guitar-note after howling barroom guitar-note wafts to the back of your brain.

author: Reef Younis
snippet: Different but not drastic, “Brothers” takes just the right amount of street-spirit fire, and builds towards something tentatively grander.

author: Pete Clark
snippet: A perfect soundtrack for a groovy wife-swapping party.

author: Calum Marsh
snippet: Halfaxa is something of a hand-crafted masterpiece, as unexpected as it as suddenly essential.

author: Mick Houghton
snippet:
Highly distinctive and wide ranging, the record moves from accessible haunting pop (“Dream Fortress”) to the
more freeform, deranged 4AD-like sound collages of “Hallways”.

author: Paul Bowler
snippet: Boucher was improving her craft with each release and sophomore album Halfaxa, issued later that year, was a significant step forward in quality.

author: Quinn Moreland
snippet: Halfaxa is Grimes at her most mystical.

author: April Welsh
snippet: Unfurling wisps of disjointed electronics and heavily obfuscated lyrics (rendered all the more unintelligible by her song titles), Halfaxa pays homage to a vast canon of pop, from Mariah Carey to Depeche Mode.

author: Siobhán Kane
snippet: Geidi Primes often feels as if Coco Rosie, Julianna Barwick, and Dirty Projectors have combined forces to create these wonderfully majestic and diverse soundscapes.

author: Jessica Faulds
snippet: Geidi Primes is music you’d expect to come bubbling up out of dark, dirty water.

author: Lindsay Zoladz
snippet: Perhaps Geidi Primes' greatest virtue is its resourcefulness: It excels at crafting evocative moods from deceivingly simple sonic materials and song structures.

author: Thomas A. Ward
snippet: Blending genres like paints on a palette, the Montreal-based artist’s chameleonic approach sees her switch between oriental pop (‘Sardaukar Levenbrech’), chillwave (‘Zoal, Face Dancer’), and post-rock (‘Venus In Fleurs’) with attentive ease.

author: Si Truss
snippet: Geidi Primes is the rawest, least focused and, as a result, least accessible thing in Grimes’ quickly-growing catalogue of releases.

author: Paul Bowler
snippet: It’s marred by poor production values and sketchy vocals. Yet the idiosyncrasy which has made Grimes’ music so celebrated is also prevalent, investing the Asiatic Sardaukar Levenbrech and the softly cascading Venus In Fleurs with a dark and mystical charm all her own.

author: Chris Martins
snippet: There Is Love In You, his first proper album in five years, is smoother still, and to great effect—if this isn’t the best Four Tet record yet, it’s certainly a fresh face for Hebden.

author: Darren Carle
snippet: This, his first album under the Four Tet moniker in over four years, is still an album that utilises traditional instrumentation, enough at least to appease the pigeon-holers, but it’s a work that rarely sounds so earthly.

author: Matthew Cole
snippet: There Is Love in You feels like a watershed moment all the same, as it’s that rare record where an established artist manages to surpass his own exceedingly high standards.

author: John Bush
snippet: From his debut, Hebden has always made the more alien side of electronic music sound warm and inviting; this not only accomplishes that, but ranks with his best.

author: Ben Hogwood
snippet: This is effectively Hebden's Balearic album, and while it may not please everyone with its relatively conventional outlook and lack of experimental tendencies, few will be able to deny it as a thing of beauty.

author: Shawn Reynaldo
snippet: While the songs are still complex and full of countless moving parts, each melody and note plays a specific role, leaving There Is Love with a real clarity of vision.

author: Matthew Bennett
snippet: If you love the ambiguous crossover between half-step London sounds and crushed and warped 4/4 peddled by the likes of Martyn, Burial or Joy Orbison, then the love in you will find this album.

author: Sean Thomas
snippet: In There is Love in You we see one of the last decade’s most early pioneers reminding us all that he’s still just as important as ever.

author: Mark Richardson
snippet: Driven by dance-inspired beats and ghostly sampled voices, the new Four Tet album is the most focused in Kieran Hebden's catalog, and also among his best.

There Is Love in You is expertly sequenced, played, and produced from start to finish. It's the work of a restlessly creative auteur circling back and turning out his most confident, definitive work to date.

The giddy result of years spent twisting and caressing orchestras of samples into a living, breathing organic whole, There Is Love In You brims with a playful sense of wonder, never more so than on centerpiece This Unfolds.

author: Ben Thompson
snippet: The result is a fifth Four Tet album which has the power to delight someone who has never listened to a Kraftwerk record all the way through, just as much as those who know their Walter from their Wendy Carlos.

author: Benjamin Boles
snippet: If the term “ambient house” hadn’t already been taken by the Orb in the late 80s, it would be a good way to describe this we’ll just call it really good stoner dance music instead.

Unlike the super-saturated rush of Everything Ecstatic, There Is Love In You radiates a mellow subtlety, the wonderfully named She Just Like To Fight a twinkling pastoral while the luscious groove of Plastic People pushes its most interesting clicks and skitters to the periphery.
"Rounds" is usually considered Hebden's zenith, but the highly relevant There Is Love In You gives that spellbinding release some very stiff competition.

author: Timothy Gabriele
snippet: Hebden has yet again created a wonderful space where he can rightfully be called sui generis.
The whole set is energetic but not exhausting, stopping along the road to breathe and cleanse the palate.

author: Conrad Amenta
snippet: There is Love in You renders Ringer primer, posits itself as perfect solution to messy experimentation, and while it’s hard to find the divisiveness in that, it’s also hard to be truly moved.

author: Matt Fink
snippet: Part minimalist dance record, part undulating sound collage, his new album serves as a scrapbook of nearly every idea Hebden has examined and cast aside during his career.

author: Genice Phillips
snippet: What I find so satisfying with this album, is how Four Tet envisions the lushness of a song, and sonically creates a buoyant, lighthearted blend – a complete album for the lively and lighthearted.
While he name-checks fiery saxophonist Albert Ayler on "Love Cry," the track's steady, nine-minute crest signals Hebden's return to meticulous melodicism.

Ten years ago this hand-stitched tapestry of astral-jazz harp, dusty acoustics, crackling breakbeats, music-box twinkles and twitchy "Intelligent Dance Music" might have seemed bravely genre-bending, but now it's as cosy a pair of favourite slippers.

author: Laura Snapes
snippet: This LP could have injected some creativity back into 4/4, instead it settles for quaintness.

Écailles de Lune exudes a level of confidence that’s remarkable whether viewing it from an indie rock or metal standpoint. In addition, it’s an album where there’s no language barrier whatsoever, its appeal universal.
Écailles de Lune is the kind of music that sounds viscerally exciting as you listen, so confident in its intergenre dialogue.
French artist Neige finally fits all his component parts-- arching atmospherics, celestial melodies, suffocating roars-- into one dynamic metal record.
Écailles De Lune is a wonderfully realised album, perhaps not quite as strong as its predecessor, but it has depth and an abundance of magical moments.

Écailles de Lune makes the most of its compelling fusion of black metal's theatricality and the after-echoes of shoegaze's propensity for utterly enveloping a listener, even if bandleader Neige approached that sound unconsciously at first.
Écailles de Lune sees Alcest improve in all the right ways.

author: Noctus
snippet: This may have been fine if there wasn’t only 6 songs.

author: Andy Kellman
snippet: Bieber makes all the right, charming moves for a teen, and he covers all the bases. The dance-pop songs are light on the ears yet memorable; the unrequited material sounds deeply felt; the ballads have all the necessary us-against-the-world teen-love dramatics.

author: Monica Herrera
snippet: The 16-year-old’s follow-up to last November’s “My World” shrewdly elevates him from a fleeting teen phenom into an evolving pop artist.

author: Leah Greenblatt
snippet: My World 2.0 ... won’t likely affect any adults not in the direct blast radius of Bieber’s target range. That said, the kid seems to know what he’s doing.

author: Jody Rosen
snippet: Those who dismiss Bieber out of hand are missing out on a seriously good pop record, one that mines vintage teen-pop themes but plays like a primer on 2010-model bubblegum.

author: Alex Young
snippet: Bieber’s second album release, My World 2.0, confirms that he is here to stay.
My World 2.0 is effective and innocent Top 40 material, if not terribly inventive.

author: Jim Carroll
snippet: Bigger, bolder and brasher than most of the indie records slouching this way of late, Treats is a joyous rage against the machine.

author: Matthew Cole
snippet: If it’s Sleigh Bells’s hooks versus your ear drums, I have a feeling the latter’s going to give out first.

author: Andrew Perry
snippet: Alexis Krauss sings their sexually charged, sample-based anthems with all the breathiness of a young Debbie Harry; the distorted ruckus adds to the excitement.

author: Michael Saba
snippet: Treats is just a whole goddamn lot of fun to listen to. It's a supremely raw and visceral pop masterwork, one appropriate to rocking out with headphones on, windows-down bumping on car stereos, four-A.M. warehouse dance parties and countless other summer moments that'll soon have soundtracks courtesy of Sleigh Bells.

author: Leah Greenblatt
snippet: It’s as if every element of Sleigh Bells’ genre-swerving sound — primitive guitar fuzz, pastiche beats, sugar-buzz vocals — bypasses the default snark button and burrows directly into jaded listeners’ punch-drunk pleasure centers.

author: Erik Adams
snippet: Krauss and Miller immediately reach for the jugular on nearly every track of Treats. The trick could wear thin quickly, but the tracks that previously made the Internet rounds as demos sound just as vital here as they did on first download.

author: David Renshaw
snippet: Stripping away all of the surrounding noise, it allows Krauss to bring her dizzyingly sweet voice to the fore, showing that Sleigh Bells are not just a one trick pony and that these songs work on more than just the basis that they are great at shaking windows.

author: John Murphy
snippet: Weighing in at just 32 minutes, Treats can hardly be accused of outstaying its welcome. In fact, its brevity is its strength – too much aural pummelling could be too much. As it is, as soon as the album finishes, you’ll want to put it on again straight away.

author: Arnold Pan
snippet: While part of Sleigh Bells’ appeal has to do with its bold inventiveness, a lot more of it has to be chalked up to the air of invincibility that comes through in the duo’s bruising, high-impact sound, which elicits a visceral reaction that gets you to really feel its excesses and indulge in them.

author: Andrew Baer
snippet: Being interesting, unique, fun and damn good is near impossible to pull off. Sleigh Bells has done it on Treats, and goddamn is it good.

author: Lawrence Vaughan
snippet: Dangerous and downright rebellious, this is what 21st century music should sound like.

author: Mark Richardson
snippet: The New York duo's debut full-length is a wildly fun noise-pop thrill-ride, delivering on the promise of last year's widely circulated demos.

The best part of Treats is that it makes you rethink the possibilities of this kind of music. It is possible for a former girl-group member and a former hardcore guitarist to get together to make an album that is more daring and more fun than anything you'll likely hear on Top 40 radio this year.

author: Sean Highkin
snippet: Treats is a smart, quirky debut that’s as punishing as it is melodic, and wholly satisfying.

author: Calum Marsh
snippet: This stuff is genuinely, earnestly satisfying, in the same way all great pop music is: these songs, simply and purely, sound fucking great.

author: Benjamin Boles
snippet: It's primal, visceral, addictive stuff – a perfect mix of sweet and evil unlike pretty much everything else out there.

author: Antonio Rowe
snippet: The idiom 'opposites attract' seems to be Sleigh Bells' main philosophical muse for their debut disc.
Sleigh Bells have crafted something entirely unique and that in itself is commendable, and the fact that they've done it with such a bold sound is all the more praiseworthy (or even surprising).
Sleigh Bells offer a thrilling ride.

author: Brady Baker
snippet: It’s an all-out sensory assault of over-driven bombast that subsumes mash-up culture, transcends genre-bend and sets a new standard of loud.
Abrasive and addictive, the duo have together discovered a chemistry that not only excites themselves, but almost anyone else who experiences it.

author: Michael Cragg
snippet: Treats can be a slavering, snarling beast of an album, but beneath the bravado is a sweet centre.

author: Charlie Frame
snippet: Sleigh Bells’ novelty ... lies in a tingling barrage of granular guitar distortion and overdriven, over-compressed girl-pop squall.

author: Lindsey Fortier
snippet: Make no mistake: Brooklyn duo Sleigh Bells is loud, raucous and unapologetic.

author: Reed Fischer
snippet: Rarely can sheer, brute force from a pair like Miller and Krauss make everything that comes afterward seem so irrelevant.

author: Alex Young
snippet: Greatness comes with time. Treats is loud, it’s fast, and it’s fun. Enjoy it.

author: Christopher Schultz
snippet: Monumentally caustic but hypothetically a dance band, Sleigh Bells sculpt infectious double-dutch funk from an unlikely acid bath of distorted drum machines and nasal pigfuck guitars.

author: Emily Mackay
snippet: Drawing influence across the board, it’s a work that not so much mixes genres as smashes them into one visceral, jaw-dropping hybrid.

author: Heather Phares
snippet: Given that Sleigh Bells' sound is so big -- and undeniably exciting -- songwriting falls lower on the band’s list of priorities than taking all the dramatic moments from everyone’s favorite songs and turning them into songs in their own right.

author: Joe Hemmerling
snippet: Sleigh Bells have latched onto an exciting undercurrent in contemporary pop music and put their own distinctive stamp on it.

author: Jon Dolan
snippet: Their debut suggests the White Stripes' White Blood Cells by way of M.I.A.'s Arular, noise that's friendly and cute, primitivism that masks pop smarts and respect for tradition, from New Wave to Sixties rock.

author: Justin Toland
snippet: For a new band to have established an instantly identifiable signature sound within such a short space of time is a great testament to the originality of this duo. The dirty sound of now.

author: Laura Studarus
snippet: While the lasting power of Treats past the warm weather months may be questionable, the duo is out to make hay while the sun shines with a high octane combination of combustible beats, finger snaps, cheerleader chants, beat machines, giddy screams, and unfiltered sass.

author: David Smyth
snippet: Krauss's cutesy voice gives pop appeal to even the darkest moments, however, and there's plenty here to show that their hearts really lie with the hummable.

author: Billy Hamilton
snippet: Sadly, this is Sleigh Bells’ overarching flaw: instead of offering an invigorating blueprint for tomorrow, they’ve rehashed a pale imitation of yesterday.

author: Anthony Fantano
snippet: I like the noise pop approach, but the vocals seem so contrived and boring. Not only that, but there's not much going on in the beats aside from some simple cuts and pastes.

author: Simon Vozick-Levinson
snippet: The venerable hip-hop band's first effort since joining NBC's late-night lineup delivers all the funk/soul/jazz vibes fans have come to expect.

author: Nathan Rabin
snippet: How I Got Over hearkens back to the neo-soul mellowness of The Roots' mid-'90s output, while songs like the infectious title track retain Tipping Point's pop savvy.

author: Paul Clarke
snippet: As the title suggests, it's a record which marks a transition for The Roots but which, like the America it addresses, is still aware of the burden of the recent past.

author: Steve 'Flash' Juon
snippet: The Roots aren’t just cashing in from their newfound Jimmy Fallon fame, they’re doing what they do best that nobody else in or outside the Illadeph-side can do.

author: Jake Paine
snippet: Speaking to all their audiences over the last 23 years, The Roots are as emotionally-tangible as they’ve ever been, and whether it’s debt, depression or Divine intervention, they’re walking over the bridge with us all.

author: Chris Barth
snippet: A lesson in balance.

author: Andrew Steadman
snippet: At this point in The Roots’ career, a falter would be far more surprising. How I Got Over continues the group’s tradition of quality records even as the band expands its horizons to television and beyond.

author: Nate Patrin
snippet: The Roots' latest is also their leanest and most stylistically cohesive LP to date.

author: Luke John Winkie
snippet: It's another rock-solid album from one of rap's most consistently great collectives, with no discernable weak spots to attack.

author: Anthony Fantano
snippet: On their 9th album, the Roots have kept their sound soulful and sobering. This album is the sound of recovery, and the point of view of a human being with a long road of improvements ahead.

author: Andrew Winistorfer
snippet: Gone are the frantic raps, menacing synths, and general hardness of the band's past three albums. In their place is a mellow approximation of the jazzy, old-school charm of The Roots circa Things Fall Apart.

author: Richard Trapunski
snippet: On their ninth studio album, the veteran Philly crew adds indie rock to its formula, and after two straight downer albums, it has them sounding positively re-energized.

author: Matthew Fiander
snippet: This disconnect actually amps up the album's tension and energy, as if that first half was the uphill struggle, and the rest is the triumphant sound coming down from the summit.

author: Dave Simpson
snippet: Their ninth album finds the Philadelphia veterans a unique voice in hip-hop.

author: Jason Lipshutz
snippet: “How I Got Over” finds the Roots acting as elder statesmen in hip-hop, but its mix of nifty experiments and straightforward rap eliminates any sense of predictability.

author: Ryan Drever
snippet: Paying attention and respect to the source material, The Roots have created a most unusual hit.

author: Andy Kellman
snippet: The blood doesn't really get pumping until the fifth track. Up to that point, however, the band creates some of its most downcast and alluring material, covering solitude, self-destruction, and just about every planetary ill.

author: Charles Aaron
snippet: The title of the Roots' ninth studio full-length suggests a more fulfilled mood (Obama victory, gig as America's favorite late-night house band), at least compared to the screw-faced abyss of their last two records.

author: Chris Coplan
snippet: With beats by a real-life backing band, The Roots have always stood out from other hip hop groups, and this record sees the group further their roles as innovators in a myriad of ways.

author: Nathan Brackett
snippet: When they come back to Roy Ayers-style funk ("Radio Daze"), they prove nobody does it better. Let's hear it for steady employment.
Whatever it may be How I Got Over is a great record and stands proud next to its contemporaries.

author: Matt Fink
snippet: A bit slight to be among their best handful of releases, it's still their most immediate, another album that transcends any attempts at categorization.

author: Nick Hanover
snippet: It’s unfortunately filled to the brim with often unnecessary guests, it ends abrasively with two tracks that are tonal mismatches for everything that came before and most devastatingly, the bulk of its tracks find the Roots sounding as though they’ve lost the freedom they enjoyed away from the constraints of their genre.

author: Eric Henderson
snippet: They’re driven, even though their latest venture is stylistically the most inert, contemplative, offputtingly soft music they’ve possibly ever released.
Finally, with one last crystallized cry of "woman in chains," it's over. Eccojams is done - do you select "loop all," or do you stop?

author: Christopher R. Weingarten
snippet: With Eccojams, Lopatin uses the bit-compressed technology of the present to extract the sublime from the trash heap of the past, and provides instructions on how to access it in the future.

author: Daniel Bromfield
snippet: Eccojams Vol. 1 is one of the greatest vaporwave albums ever made. It’d be wonderful if it were only the beginning of a rich tradition.
The glorious, sentient, unbalanced soundtrack to the real end of days.

author: Marc Masters
snippet: Famed noise/drone duo issue their final record, which transforms a sense of finality and reflection into often incredible instrumental passages.
Across six tracks and a taut 45 minutes, the duo offers an exemplar of themselves and noise, at their ecstatic heights.

author: Ned Raggett
snippet: Released after the duo formally called it a day, Yellow Swans' literal swan song found the two still exploring their way through often majestic drone -- if the roots of the band had always been as much in uncontrolled experimentation as in serene contemplation, here the two sides found a fine fusion.

The final LP from the Portland noise/improve duo Yellow Swans has titles indicating either that they feel trapped (“Foiled”, “Limited Space”), or that they’ve decided to change course and look forward to the future (“Opt Out”, “New Life”, “Going Places”). That’s the nature of titles for instrumental music. They work as framing devices, whether the intention is joking or seri

ous.

author: Brandon Bussolini
snippet: Going Places has the feel of a ghost bearing down on you, and the only comfort it offers lies in the fact that it feels a lot like being alive right now.

author: Leah Greenblatt
snippet: Despite her best rebellious efforts, Miley’s just not (yet) that thorny a girl.

author: Heather Phares
snippet: At times Can’t Be Tamed feels perfunctory, doing the job of showing Cyrus is growing up without making her too mature for her still-young fan base and little else.

author: Rob Sheffield
snippet: It's a Top 40 record of a high order, packed with electro-pop hooks and big Kelly Clarkson-style shout-along choruses. Cyrus' 17-year-old ire — however genuine it is — just adds spice.

Throughout “Can’t Be Tamed” Cyrus seems checked out of her vocal performances, singing with neither the tween-queen enthusiasm of her “Hannah Montana” material nor the confrontational energy of 2008’s “Breakout.”
Miley is her own woman now, and for better or worse, she is no longer a puppet of the Walt Disney corporation.

author: Alexis Petridis
snippet: It's hard to escape the feeling that, in seeking to establish a more individual identity, Cyrus has become more generic. This is compounded by the fact that the songs just aren't strong enough to overcome the customary production.

author: Daisy Bowie-Sell
snippet: Cheesy teen melodies creep into Miley Cyrus's Can’t Be Tamed.

author: Michelle Griffin
snippet: Snark aside, Cyrus's big rocking voice is displayed to good effect on the title track and the House of Mouse has laced this silly tune with earworms that nag long after you finish mocking.

author: Evan Sawdey
snippet: When you get right down to it, not only is Can’t Be Tamed a confused statement of a record, but it’s a pretty boring listen as well, as Cyrus hits on tired old pop trends (AutoTune? Really?) as a way to deliver her quasi-edgy new persona to a much more intelligent mainstream audience.

author: Niall Doherty
snippet: At a time when there’s a dearth of new guitar bands, ‘Total Life Forever’ will establish Foals as one of the UK’s most important – their second album is an inventive, thrilling and flawless masterpiece.

author: Sean O'Neal
snippet: TLF is a bid to be less in your face than in your head, and while its effect is less immediate, it’s a comedown that’s way more fun than the party.

author: Ian Mathers
snippet: As soon as Foals’ guitars begin their patient chime, it’s clear that this is a band suddenly and surprisingly in full control of its powers.

author: Robin Murray
snippet: ‘Total Life Forever’ is a massive leap forward for the band. The music writhes with a renewed ambition, capable of moving from near ambient strains of electronica to propulsive African funk in a drum break. Shifting from their 2D debut album, ‘Total Life Forever’ is a three-dimensional triumph.

author: Robert Ham
snippet: Even when Foals stretch back into the comfortable strides of danceable beats and scratchy guitars, it is tinged with something sour and slightly acidic. This isn't the same band we once knew–thank heaven for that.

author: David Bevan
snippet: At every turn, Total Life Forever is inviting. Much more alive than earlier efforts, it's an album with a complexion that constantly changes with time.

author: Andrew Ryce
snippet: Foals is a band with untapped potential: they’ve got a solid vocalist, are more than competent at their instruments, and clearly have an ear for melodies, but the way they put their music together remains mostly uninspiring.

author: Lauren Strain
snippet: Where Antidotes had blitzkriegs, Total Life Forever has drawn-out hypnoses; where Antidotes was furious and muscular and destructive, Total Life Forever is quiet and sinister and inconsolable.

author: Brittany Picklesimer
snippet: Some songs linger too long like a bee that tip-toes across your skin trying to discern whether you really are in fact pollen.

author: Gregory Heaney
snippet: Where some see restraint, others may very well see refinement, and those who appreciated Antidotes' more spacy passages will find that Foals' reinvention of their sound is a calculated risk that definitely pays off.

author: Julia Reidy
snippet: At its core, Total Life Forever is a good dance record: something you could leave on at a party and not stop moving to until its full 50 minutes have finished. But as much as it tries to run away from that, it isn’t a whole lot else.

author: Anthony Fantano
snippet: A really chill mood pervades this entire release, but much of the time I find myself wanting more.

Better than almost anyone else in this amorphous field of treated sound, Massive Attack create something almost organic, with a physical sense of beating hearts and ticking minds. The centre of the album constantly shifts, as a new song comes into focus. I believe, as with their trio of Nineties classics, we’ll still be listening to this in decades to come.
Less a depiction of the surrounding apocalypse, Heligoland is more a reflection of the anxieties within.

It still warms the blood to hear those trip-hop synths roll on the slow-burning "Flat of the Blade" (with some acid loops thrown in for good measure), but Massive Attack's arsenal has expanded and the resulting onslaught is nothing short of brilliant.

The haunting horns under Horace Andy's vocal on "Girl I Love You" and mind-tickling thump of closer "Atlas Air" are pure genius from the minds of Grantley Marshall and Robert Del Naja: creepy and danceable.

Listening to the array of styles, from the Jim O'Rourke-like folk of "Psyche", laced with Martina Topley-Bird's cosmic incantation, to "Splitting The Atom"'s opiated rocksteady or Hope Sandoval's dusky ballad, "Paradise Circus", it's conceivable Del Naja and Marshall needed every minute of those years to concoct such alluring material.
Their fissiparous approach to their work as an ensemble appears to be paying dividends once more.
Returning from a six-year long wilderness of soundtrack work and greatest hits, ‘Heligoland’ sees the duo back at the top of their game.
Through it all, Massive Attack are more menacing than midnight in the darklands. Welcome back--you've been missed terribly.

Heligoland burns slowly; songs like the Damon Albarn penned Saturday Come Slow and dubby closer Atlas Air take precious time to unfurl. Then again, it just wouldn’t be Massive Attack if you didn’t have to work for it, and the rewards are here if you're willing.

Musically the elements that define them remain – the scattered beats, the eerie, claustrophobic atmosphere, a slightly sleepy, almost trippy feel – but the songs here are their most consistent in years.
A lovely bummer, as always.

This certainly isn't the Massive Attack that floated the smoothest British house of the early '90s, and more surprisingly, it's also not the Massive Attack that created dense, immersive trip-hop during the '90s and early 2000s.
Haunting vocals by TV On The Radio's Tunde Adebimpe and Mazzy's Star's Hope Sandoval calm the jitters here, but the crew have gotten comfy just tripping out, but they sometimes forget the hooks.
The album's dusty beats, pointed electronics, and cinematic feel are pleasantly familiar, at best they recall the band's past glory rather than pushing forward their legacy.
Although much of Heligoland suggests that Massive Attack might finally have burned out, the glowing embers of what they once had can still be glimpsed providing a light in the dark.
Sure, it's a logical progression from 100th Window, but because their progressions are neither commonsense nor predictable, it's difficult to predict how it will hold up in terms of posterity.
Compared to the radical thrill of Portishead's equally long-gestated "Third," there's a sense Del Naja and Marshall are still feeling their way back.
Six songs into a characterless album, one on which ambience takes precedence over tunes, 3D and Daddy G unveil three stunning numbers that compare with anything in their back catalogue.
[The album] sees the reunited Grand "Daddy G" Marshalll abnd Robert "3D" Del Naja proving they can still corner the market in atmospheric glooom, even if their era-defining days have passed.

The music is strikingly less dense than before, though the production is as meticulous and measured as ever, but it’s also so deliberately bleak, so obvious in its intent to be capital-I Important, it all but dares you to turn your back and chuckle.
Overall, though ‘Heligoland’ is a puzzling and frustrating listen. Some good tracks can’t hide the fact that this is the stuff of an identity crisis.

Fans who have spent the better part of a decade jonesing for exactly this kind of fix will surely appreciate the effort, but for the less dependent, the songs here offer little that the band hasn't already done better.
The undercurrent of menace and sadness that defined Massive Attack's best music is largely absent, replaced with a drowsy, half-formed gloom that, if anything, suggests resignation instead of dread.

[These marquee name guests] might be the source to what is wrong with Heglioland. Usually, Massive mainstays, 3D and Daddy G, are able to bring something previously not experienced out of their collaborators. This time, nothing is connecting.
When you listen to these gloomy trip-hop jams after their best work of the 90s, the results are underwhelming.

author: Mikael Wood
snippet: The diminutive Australian diva is still delivering disco thunder from Down Under.

author: Tim Sendra
snippet: Aphrodite is the work of someone who knows exactly what her skills are and who to hire to help showcase them to perfection.

author: David Smyth
snippet: If Kylie's previous album, X, was less memorable than most, this impeccable bounceback proves yet again that she never fades for long. If she carries on at the top of her game much longer, we might really deduce a deal with Zeus.

author: Barry Walters
snippet: Minogue delivers bliss like no other (wo)man or machine.

author: Kevin Courtney
snippet: Splash on your Kylie fragrance, get your heels on and get ready to spin around the dancefloor all summer long.

author: Neil McCormick
snippet: This is a mainstream pop blast, with great intros, tingly keyboard hooklines, catchy choruses and pumping codas, to which Kylie adds the sensuality of her light, breathy, close-to-the-mic vocals.

author: Karina Halle
snippet: If Minogue was looking to do something better than her last album, she's done it, and with all the aplomb of a Goddess.
The new set casts a spell with Price's signature preternatural touches, Minogue's breathy chirp and the hooky melodies of a varied crew of dance pop-focused songwriters and producers.

author: Christel Loar
snippet: “It’s the truth, it’s a fact / I was gone and now I’m back,” sings Kylie Minogue on the title track of her latest release, Aphrodite. The hook asks, “Can you feel me on your stereo?” Yes. Yes we can, Kylie, and damn, it feels good.

author: Bernard Zuel
snippet: This is easily the best pop album Kylie's made in a decade. A genuine dance-pop disc at that, with fewer attempts to be musically topical ... and more concentration on finding songs that don't just occupy space until the ''catchy bit'' and which last beyond the first chorus. Tunes. Dancing. Hooks.

author: April Welsh
snippet: Although the album is an exercise in euphoric clubland dreaming, tracks ‘Closer’ and ‘Everything Is Beautiful’ remind us there is perhaps a more sincere side to Kylie that is often overlooked.
Her most unified work in ages.

author: Helen Clarke
snippet: Who, deep down doesn't love Kylie? Sure, there was a time when she was genuinely a bit naff - the dreg ends of the Stock, Aitken and Waterman era, for example; and 2007's X was just plain forgettable. But somewhere, throughout the past two decades, there's something for even the most stoney faced pop fan.

author: Dan Nishimoto
snippet: Aphrodite is everything you expect it to be: inspiring, motivating and celebratory.

author: Caroline Sullivan
snippet: Despite sharp production, Aphrodite is only as good as Kylie herself. And because her voice is limited to squeaks, exhalations and woe-begone sighs, it's hard to stay interested unless you happen to be on a dancefloor at 4am, which is probably the only sensible place to hear it.

author: Rob Sheffield
snippet: Aphrodite is her finest work since 1997's underrated Impossible Princess, teaming her with Madonna producer Stuart Price.

author: Sal Cinquemani
snippet: The entire album has the sonic consistency of cotton candy: It won't exactly give you a headache, but it could leave you with a stomachache.
Despite her vaguely regal poise, and a songwriting crew including Jake Shears, Calvin Harris and Tim-from-Keane, Aphrodite is dismayingly anonymous pop-trance.

author: Andy Gill
snippet: With Aphrodite, Kylie shimmies her way further down the road of single-issue synth-pop, to the detriment of any notable individual characteristics.
The rest lumbers by in a blur of anaemic vocals and dull soundscapes.

author: Andrew Ryce
snippet: King Night stands alone, both from its apparent contemporaries as well as from the band itself; it's not so much their creation as their demon offspring, the kind of solid and complete creation that lesser (or just unluckier) bands spend entire careers striving towards.

author: Rebecca Schiller
snippet: You can call this drag or witch house if you like but regardless of its genre tag this is monumental.

author: Tom Lea
snippet: There’s nothing around that’s really like King Night, an album that reaches incredibly beautiful heights ... and explores distorted, deserted depths.

author: Clayton Purdom
snippet: Salem evokes the seismic thrill of a good Gucci drop alongside all of Nico’s ghostly beauty within the very framework and timbre of their productions. The result is no less than one of 2010’s most exciting debuts.

author: Rory Gibb
snippet: Salem deal in fragments and ambiguities; their music is unmistakably dark, in all the senses above and more, and saps power from the tension they set up between reality and dream. But there’s light and beauty there too.

Whether or not you think antipathy and self-destruction are legitimate themes for music, or you feel that even the pretty remote handling of rap that Salem has done as three white kids is too much, you can’t dismiss what started all this hub-bub in the first place: the fact that the trio has crafted a sound that still doesn’t really sound like anything else.

author: Jordan Bimm
snippet: They might be unreliable performers, but their studio work is forward-thinking and beautiful in an oddly satisfying, downtrodden way.

author: Polly Rappaport
snippet: It’s a terrifying and astounding album – don’t listen to it alone.
Salem don't take themselves seriously; they're just messing around. Except that King Night is too sonically compelling to be easily dismissed as the next disposable flavor of the month.

author: Heather Phares
snippet: Throughout all of King Night, the feeling of a séance being held or a spell being cast is palpable, but Salem's ability to be affecting and menacing at the same time is pure alchemy.

author: Brendan Klinkenberg
snippet: It is not flawless, and several of the best tracks (“Frost, “Redlights”) here are simply cleaned up standouts from their earlier EP’s, but overall it is an extremely solid effort from a new and polarizing band.

author: Larry Fitzmaurice
snippet: The witch house poster band's brand of slowed-down, blown-out, culturally mishmashed electronic music has proven divisive, but it was always meant to be.

author: Michael Dix
snippet: Listening to King Night is like a watching a war-zone report in full, Technicolor widescreen: it’s not somewhere you’d want to be for too long, but in short doses it’s brutal, thrilling and scary as hell.

author: Will Hermes
snippet: A stocking stuffer for that kid in the trench coat.

author: Charlie Frame
snippet: Rave horns echo like WW2 sirens being played on a fucked-up ghetto blaster while the cast of House Of 1000 Corpses do their best Gucci Mane impressions – an interesting, if perhaps slightly contrived, oddity.

author: Alex Young
snippet: There is no journey to be found in the album, and the music is ultimately a monotonous collection of crack-pipe nightmares, a gimmick fit for play around Halloween time.

author: Steven Hyden
snippet: An aggressively regressive stew of cheap horror-movie atmospherics, booger-flinging beats, rudimentary rapping, and occasional (perhaps accidental) moments of genuine profundity, Salem’s King Night is an Insane Clown Posse record that thinks it’s too clever to be an Insane Clown Posse record.

author: Matt James
snippet: It’s relentlessly, admirably silly.

author: Mike Powell
snippet: Trash, art, or stunt? In the few effective moments, it’s all three.

author: Jakob Dorof
